<HEAD>Storm Floods Central Cuba, Killing Four People</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A weeklong storm caused heavy flooding in central <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> that killed four people and forced about 10,000 to evacuate their homes, the Cuban news agency <ORGANIZATION> Prensa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Latina </ORGANIZATION> reported. An agency dispatch from <LOCATION> Havana </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> capital, said Wednesday that flooding occurred in the provinces of <LOCATION> Cienfuegos </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Sancti </PERSON> <PERSON> Spiritus </PERSON>, <PERSON> Villa </PERSON> <PERSON> Clara </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ciego </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Avila </PERSON>. It said the storm produced power outages and paralyzed transportation. The dispatch, monitored here, said the four victims were all from <PERSON> Cienfuegos </PERSON>, which was hit the hardest. It said rescue crews, using helicopters and amphibious vehicles, evacuated about 10,000 people from their homes Wednesday and moved them to higher ground.
