<HEAD>Reagans Treated To A Night On The Town, Moscow Style</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MASHA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Reagans </ORGANIZATION> did up the town, Moscow-style, on their last night here, taking in the ballet at the opulent Bolshoi Theater, dining with the <ORGANIZATION> Gorbachevs </ORGANIZATION> at a dacha owned by the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and strolling through a moonlit Red Square. With summit business over, President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> seemed in good spirits Wednesday night, moving their seats closer together in the `` Royal Box'' the Soviet and American first couples shared at the Bolshoi and briefly clasping one another's waists as they left the ballet. But their wives, who ruffled one another's feathers earlier in the day during a visit to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s Tretyakov Gallery, appeared cool to one another and did not speak. After their private dinner at the Communist Party-owned country home on the outskirts of western <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Reagans </ORGANIZATION>, holding hands, made an impromptu stop at Red Square, walking on the cobblestone plaza between St. Basil's Cathedral and the Kremlin. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> described his Soviet evening on the town as `` wonderful ... very warm and hospitable.'' He said the couple stopped at Red Square `` because <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> has n't seen it We're leaving tomorrow and I did n't want her to miss it.'' The Reagans leave this morning for <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, where they will spend a day before returning Friday to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. In the six-tiered, gold and red Bolshoi on Sverdlov Square, the audience of about 2,000, most of them Soviets, applauded the <ORGANIZATION> Reagans </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Gorbachevs </ORGANIZATION> both at the ballet's beginning and again at its end. The dancers also ended their performance by clapping for the leaders and their wives. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> waved back at the audience, both grinning broadly. The Reagans appeared to enjoy the hour and a half of ballet. It was the first night of pure entertainment on their schedule, which had previously included official dinners complete with political toasts and journalists. But even the last evening included a touch of patriotism. American and Soviet flags hung on either side of the `` Royal Box'' at the rear of the theater, and the orchestra played national anthems from both countries before the ballet began. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> mouthed the words of the American anthem while <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> held her right hand at her heart. The Reagans and <PERSON> Raisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> used opera glasses to watch the Bolshoi Ballet perform excerpts from `` Sleeping Beauty,'' `` Swan Lake'' and `` Romeo and <PERSON> Juliet </PERSON>.'' The last excerpt was performed by <PERSON> Nine </PERSON> <PERSON> Ananiashvili </PERSON> and <PERSON> Andris </PERSON> <PERSON> Liepa </PERSON>, winners of a 1986 world ballet competition in <LOCATION> Jackson </LOCATION>, Miss. The Bolshoi Theater, founded in 1776, was the first permanent theater in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, and its ballet and opera companies gained an international reputation in the 1950s and 1960s. Tickets cost about three rubles -LRB- five dollars -RRB- but are nearly impossible for Soviets to obtain without contacts in the theater or luck enough to receive an allocation at their jobs.
