<HEAD>Yanks Beat Reds, 15-2, in Historic Baseball Matchup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN FRIEDMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In a match marked more by good will than athletic prowess, <ORGANIZATION> Johns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hopkins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> capitalized on eight errors by a team of Soviet engineers to take a 15-2 victory in the first baseball showdown between the superpowers. Before the historic game, played at the <ORGANIZATION> Lenin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Komsomol </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Automobile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Factory </ORGANIZATION> stadium, the <PERSON> Johns </PERSON> <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON> team presented the Soviets with souvenir T-shirts, and both sides clasped hands and hugged as Western reporters in town for the summit meeting crowded around. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, busy elsewhere, was unable to throw out the first pitch. A public address announcer chattered away about the rules of baseball, even during play, to a crowd just learning about the sport. But the 300 or so fans still seemed to enjoy the game, cheering lustily when the Soviet team from the D.I. <ORGANIZATION> Mendeleyev </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineering </ORGANIZATION> did well and whistling in derision when it botched a play. <PERSON> Johns </PERSON> <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON> struck immediately in the first inning when leadoff batter <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Finegan </PERSON> doubled off the left field fence and scored on two successive wild pitches by <PERSON> Alexei </PERSON> <PERSON> Koshivoy </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> Blue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jays </ORGANIZATION> put the game out of reach in the third inning, while leading 2-0, when first baseman <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Durocher </PERSON> walked, advanced to second on a Koshivoy wild pitch and scored on a single by second baseman <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> <PERSON> Bernstein </PERSON>. After two successiv