<HEAD>Security Agents Show Off Limos, Pool Guesses on Reagan Departure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>USOVO, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Music poured from the front-seat tape deck. <PERSON> Anatoly </PERSON> <PERSON> Kalinin </PERSON> snapped his fingers to the beat, and his friends passed around cigarettes and pictures of their wives for the visiting Americans to see. This was n't an impromptu gathering of youth on the Arbat pedestrian mall, but an assemblage of the usually staid gray-suited security agents who guard Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. Relaxing during a two-and-a-half hour wait for President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and his wife to finish dinner at a Communist Party-owned dacha outside <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, a dozen security men bantered with their <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> counterparts, showing off the Zil limousines they travel in and joining in an American betting pool on when the Reagans would emerge from the walled compound. `` At exactly 12 midnight!'' contended an agent identified only as <PERSON> Yevgeny </PERSON>, arguing with an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> agent who insisted that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> never stays out that late. `` I'm not just taking a guess, I'm providing you with information,'' <PERSON> Yevgeny </PERSON> stated knowingly. The American stuck by his 11 p.m. estimate, challenging, `` We'll see whose intelligence is better. Some of the security detachment had accompanied <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> in December, but the agents who had never seen <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> showed the most curiosity about life in the other superpower. They compared housing costs, divorce rates and the vastly different attitudes toward smoking in their countries. The Zil tour was impressive for the journalists, who acted as translators between the security squads. The sleek black limos are usually seen flashing past at 60 miles per hour on the broad avenue that leads from this parklike estate to the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION>. `` This costs 100,000 rubles -LRB- $ 167,000 at the official exchange rate -RRB- here,'' one of the Soviets offered with an aim to impress that would rival any car salesman. `` It's got genuine Karelian birchwood lining on the doors and all around the windows.'' One of the Americans, who did not want to be identified, said that the Soviets were a little tense on the first day of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s visit, but that the two groups quickly became accustomed to working together on their nearly identical tasks of protecting the leader `` Discipline is discipline and surveillance is surveillance,'' <PERSON> Yevgeny </PERSON> explained, when asked how the two teams worked together. The nattily dressed agents from both superpowers took turns posing for souvenir pictures. Floodlights blinked and a telephone call to the guard shack outside the compound at 10:40 p.m. alerted both teams to the presidential party's intended departure, causing moans from the bettors who had guessed the party would break up later. The agents instantly snapped to attention, with the Soviets diving into the limousines and escort cars and the Americans climbing into their wagons. The entourage got back to business so quickly that the head of the American security detachment had no chance to collect his bet winnings. His guess of 11 p.m. was only six seconds off the mark.
