<HEAD>Diplomatic Sources Say 28 Refusenik Cases Unresolved</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Western diplomatic source says 28 refusenik cases have not been resolved, contrary to information from Soviet Jewish leaders that the cases were cleared for emigration as a result of meetings between <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet officials. The source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the Jewish leaders had evidently misunderstood the situation. The confusion arose over a meeting between Assistant Secretary of State <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Schifter </PERSON> and a group of six refuseniks Wednesday morning. Refusenik scientist <PERSON> Yuli </PERSON> <PERSON> Kosharovsky </PERSON> showed reporters a list of 400 names that he said had been submitted to <PERSON> Schifter </PERSON> on Saturday for discussion with Soviet officials at meetings during the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> summit. He said <PERSON> Schifter </PERSON> told the group that 28 of the cases had been solved in the meetings taking place during the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> summit between President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. But the Western diplomatic source said later that no cases had been solved. Other refusenik sources said more than a dozen families from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kiev </LOCATION> had received permission to emigrate in the past 10 days. <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> refusenik <PERSON> Bella </PERSON> <PERSON> Gulko </PERSON> said the <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> Weinshtock </PERSON> and <PERSON> Iosif </PERSON> <PERSON> Pilmenshtein </PERSON> families of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> had received permission to emigrate this week. <PERSON> Refusenik </PERSON> <PERSON> Sergei </PERSON> <PERSON> Mkrtchyan </PERSON>, who demonstrated daily in downtown <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> with his wife and year-old daughter last week, said he was summoned to the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> visa office on Saturday and was told he could leave the country on Monday. <PERSON> Mkrtchyan </PERSON> said he knew of three <LOCATION> Kiev </LOCATION> families who also had received permission to leave the country. About 40 other refuseniks, many of them accompanied by their children, held a peaceful, half-hour demonstration Wednesday within sight of the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION>, waving banners demanding that they be allowed to emigrate. An agency helping Jewish emigres said in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> on Wednesday that the number allowed to leave the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> reached 1,145 in May, a seven-year high. The May figure was the fourth straight monthly increase and brought the total for 1988 to 4,547, said the <ORGANIZATION> Intergovernmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Migration </ORGANIZATION>. More than 8,000 Jews were permitted to emigrate in 1987, a sharp increase from previous years but far below the peak of more than 51,000 in 1979.
