<HEAD>Reagan's First Post-Summit Stop: A Call on a Close Friend</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The relationship has never been more special. So it is only natural that President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> is visiting <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>, his ideological soulmate and closest foreign ally, to tell her about the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> summit. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s two-day visit, another boost to the <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> prime minister's prestige on the international stage, comes six months after Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> stopped off to confer with her en route to the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> superpower summit. Today's is <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s third and probably last visit as president to a prime minister of whom he said recently, `` We're very good friends and it is a friendship I treasure very much.'' He will confer with Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> at her No. 10 Downing St. residence, dine there tonight and make a speech Friday on East-West relations before returning home. For <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader has been a sometimes costly, occasionally reproving but super-loyal friend. She rarely criticizes him. Asked in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> about revelations about astrology in the <LOCATION> White </LOCATION> <LOCATION> House </LOCATION>, all she would say was: `` I come under <PERSON> Libra </PERSON>, which is a very balanced sign.'' The Anglo-American bond, rooted in a common language, heritage and alliances in two world wars, is the cornerstone of her foreign policy. She stood alone in backing the 1986 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bombing raid on <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>; followed <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> out of <ORGANIZATION> UNESCO </ORGANIZATION> in 1985; was the first to deploy <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cruise missiles in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> in 1983, and last year, when the superpowers agreed to remove the missiles, she put aside her reservations and gave the deal a ringing endorsement. When other European leaders in the 16-nation <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> alliance sometimes grumble about <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> domination, Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s response is blunt. `` She's the largest, most prosperous nation in the world, and let's be thankful she has taken a leadership role,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> said in a radio interview in March. `` None of us can substitute for it. We could all help with it.'' Her <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy draws opposition taunts of `` <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s poodle,'' to which she retorts: `` I do n't think I would make a very good poodle. I might be more a sort of bulldog.'' However, some analysts see her as having subtly moved into a prime role in <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>, using both her special influence with <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and, more recently, her good relations with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> to exercise power. Elected to office 18 months before <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and recently re-elected for an unprecedented third consecutive term, 62-year-old Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> is the senior stateswoman of the Western world. She shares <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s hostility to communism and belief in free markets. She fervently believes nuclear weapons are peacekeepers. After <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> flirted with the idea of a non-nuclear world at the 1986 summit at <LOCATION> Reykjavik </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iceland </LOCATION>, Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> sped to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to make sure he did n't carry disarmament too far _ without consulting his allies. At her instigation, <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> leaders held a special summit before <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s latest meeting in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. She said the aim was to demonstrate Western unity and show `` that the president is always seen consulting his <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> allies.'' There have been some disagreements. In 1982, when <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> sought to withhold U.S.-originated technology from a Soviet natural gas pipeline, Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> ordered British companies to fulfill their contracts despite the threat of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sanctions. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> backed off, after Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> complained publicly she felt `` deeply wounded by a friend.'' A year later, Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> criticized the U.S.-led invasion of <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION> to overthrow Marxist coup leaders in the former British colony, saying `` You just do n't walk into countries like that.'' More recently, she has chided the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> about its budget deficit, making disapproving comparisons with her own stringent policies which have produced a budget surplus. But she has never shied away from backing the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in a crisis, even when it has left her isolated. She says she has never forgotten that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> put his entire Latin American policy at risk to support <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> in the 1982 <LOCATION> Falkland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> war against <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>. In April 1986 she braved uproar in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> for allowing <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to use British-based bombers in the raid on <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>, when other <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> allies had refused to help. She declared, `` I believe friendship is two ways.''
