<HEAD>Eugene McCarthy Running For President At 72</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON>, whose presidential candidacy two decades ago helped galvanize opposition to the <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> War, has placed himself in the running again this year at the age of 72. `` This year the one thing we have to do is shake up the two-party system, and that's what I hope to do,'' the silver-haired <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON> told reporters and onlookers Wednesday near Independence Hall. `` There is no real choice between Democrats and Republicans.'' <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON> dismissed the expected <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> nominee, Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, and his likely Democratic opponent, <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. `` There are two kinds of people who do n't make good presidents,'' he said, `` vice presidents and governors.'' The former senator, whose anti-war campaign in 1968 helped bring down President <PERSON> Lyndon </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, is running this year on the Consumer Party ticket. In <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON>'s first campaign, fellow Minnesotan <PERSON> Hubert </PERSON> <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON> won the Democratic nomination and Republican <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> won the election. <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON> also tried for the Democratic presidential nomination in 1972 and ran as an independent in 1976. This time he hopes to be on the ballot in at least 30 states. <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON> said his latest candidacy was not a futile gesture. `` Sure I've lost before, but I did n't feel I wasted my time, and I expect to have a significant impact,'' <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Max </PERSON> <PERSON> Weiner </PERSON>, who founded the <ORGANIZATION> Consumer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> in 1967 in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, said: `` We think both the Democrats and Republicans have failed the country, and that we are an alternative, not a spoiler. We'll give the voters an alternative. Millions do n't want to vote for anyone, and we think that <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON> will attract them.'' The party has about 4,000 members, almost all in <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>. Its platform calls for guaranteed jobs for all Americans, sharp reductions in the military budget, passage of the Equal Rights Amendment and provision of affordable housing for everyone. The party's most successful candidate to date has been <PERSON> Weiner </PERSON>, a 1987 candidate for <ORGANIZATION> Philadelphia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Weiner </PERSON> won 21 percent of the vote, which was not enough for a seat. The party affiliated itself with the campaigns of <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> candidates <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Commoner </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sonia </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> in the 1980 and 1984 presidential campaigns. <PERSON> Lance </PERSON> <PERSON> Haver </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Pennsylvania </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Consumer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON> would be formally nominated at a convention in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> late this summer. No date was announced. <PERSON> Haver </PERSON> said that he expected <LOCATION> Florence </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rice </LOCATION>, who founded the <ORGANIZATION> Harlem </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Consumer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> based in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, to be the party's vice presidential nominee. But <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON>, who says the vice presidency should be abolished, said he expected there would