<FIRST>r w PM-Hastings-Impeach     06-02 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hastings-Impeach,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>FBI Agent Says Judge Hastings Leaked Wiretap Information</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Three major investigations in the <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> area broke off in 1985 when wiretap information was allegedly leaked by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Alcee </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hastings </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agent told a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee conducting impeachment proceedings against the judge. `` There is nothing to lead me to believe that it could have been any other source than Judge <PERSON> Hastings </PERSON>,'' agent <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Mazzella </PERSON> testified Wednesday before the subcommittee on criminal justice. <PERSON> Mazzella </PERSON> said the three investigations into labor racketeering and public corruption had to be ended for fear of endangering the lives of undercover agents and informants. He said <PERSON> Hastings </PERSON> approved a 30-day wiretap on July 15, 1985, and received `` progress reports'' on it every seven days. On Aug. 15, the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> applied to <PERSON> Hastings </PERSON> for an extension of the tap, attaching an affidavit containing references to <LOCATION> Dade </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> and a man named <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> `` Waxy'' <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON>, who was a target of one of the probes. <PERSON> Mazzella </PERSON>, who was in charge of the probes, said the investigations became tainted when <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> told <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> of information he said he received from <PERSON> Hastings </PERSON>. <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> surmised that the only way anyone would know the information was from a wiretap. <PERSON> Mazzella </PERSON> said the cases involved the local longshoremen's union in zoning code cases in <LOCATION> Hialeah </LOCATION> and police selling drugs in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Village </LOCATION>. He said the wiretap was involved in all three cases. <PERSON> Hastings </PERSON>, who still sits on the federal bench in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, has not had a chance to rebut the allegations before the subcommittee. He refused to discuss the case Wednesday with reporters outside the hearing room. <PERSON> Mazzella </PERSON> said he could not find any statement to a law enforcement officer in which <PERSON> Hastings </PERSON> either confirmed or denied the allegations. The agent said reporter <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> <PERSON> Duffy </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Miami </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> told the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> he discussed the allegation with <PERSON> Hastings </PERSON> on March 25, 1986, but that <PERSON> Hastings </PERSON> did not say whether he was the source of the leak. The impeachment proceedings against <PERSON> Hastings </PERSON> stem from a bribery case in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> involving <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> attorney <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Borders </PERSON>. Borders was convicted in 1982 of arranging a $ 150,000 bribe for <PERSON> Hastings </PERSON> in exchange for modifying the sentences of two convicted racketeers. In a separate trial in 1983, <PERSON> Hastings </PERSON> was acquitted of the bribery conspiracy charges. But a five-member panel of the Atlanta-based 11th <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>, which covers <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, concluded there was convincing evidence that <PERSON> Hastings </PERSON> actually took part in the bribery scheme and then attempted a cover-up by lying under oath and manufacturing evidence. The panel's findings were endorsed unanimously by the <ORGANIZATION> Judicial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the chief policy-making body of the federal judiciary, and forwarded to <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> leaders in March 1987 with the advice that `` consideration of impeachment may be warranted.'' The judiciary subcommittee must determine whether <PERSON> Hastings </PERSON> committed the `` high crimes and misdemeanors'' that warrant impeachment. If <PERSON> Hastings </PERSON> is impeached by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> will conduct a trial to determine whether he should be removed from office.
