<FIRST>r w PM-WeatherRadar     06-02 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weather Radar,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Radars Will Sharpen America's Weather Eye</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> will turn a sharper eye to the weather in the next few years with the installation of a snazzy new radar system jointly funded by a quartet of federal agencies. The new radar will allow meteorologists, for the first time, to see the formation of tornadoes before they reach the ground. They also will be better able to pinpoint the landing site of hurricanes, predict floods and measure the flow of wind, weather scientists say. The first Next Generation Weather Radar installation is under way at <LOCATION> Norman </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Okla. </LOCATION>, with as many as 175 to follow by the mid-1990s, officials of <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION>, the private company building the system, reported Wednesday. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Naval </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oceanographic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> are anteing up $ 450 million for the new system, dubbed NEXRAD. Under development for eight years, the first system was tested at a <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION> facility in <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> before the <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> installation, expected to be operational in thefall. <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>, one of the nation's leading areas for tornadoes, will test the new radar's `` unique capability to identify rotating wind patterns within storms,'' according to <PERSON> Kurt </PERSON> <PERSON> Merl </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION>. While current radar detects only the amount of moisture in the air, the new one can follow its movement. Thus, an operator seeing wind rushing away from him, right next to a severe gust heading toward him, will recognize the signature of a rotating movement, the first sign of tornado development, said <PERSON> Les </PERSON> <PERSON> Lemon </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oceanic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atmospheric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> researcher now directing the radar development program for <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION>. Radar tests have shown that movement can be seen in mid-level clouds, before the twister reaches down for the ground. This means warning time could be expanded to `` tens of minutes,'' <PERSON> Lemon </PERSON> said. Currently the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> issues a tornado watch when conditions exist which could spawn a tornado, but ground spotters have to spot the tornadoes to issue actual warnings. The new system could cut false alarms in half, <PERSON> Lemon </PERSON> added. NEXRAD will replace a 30-year-old radar system that provides only limited weather data. <PERSON> Merl </PERSON> said the NEXRAD installations also will be coupled with on-ground rain gauges to measure precipitation for forecast areas where flooding is likely, a system that should improve warnings in flood-prone areas. In addition, <PERSON> Lemon </PERSON> noted that the system will be able to measure the winds within hurricanes within its 145-mile range. With that information, meteorologists will be better able to predict the course of hurricanes to give warnings about where they will strike land, and also to estimate the wind and surge of sea water being pushed ahead of the storm. The system's 28-foot radar dish, enclosed in a fiberglass dome, draws a profile of the air from the surface up to 70,000 feet every six minutes, <PERSON> Lemon </PERSON> explained, providing detailed information even in clear air. Many radars can not detect clear air movement, only air with water vapor or dust or some other debris to reflect the signal. The radar uses the Doppler effect, which depends on a change in frequency in a radio wave. The pencil-thin wave is sent out at a constant frequency, and bounces back off clouds, moving air, dust or whatever it strikes. There is a subtle change of frequency in signals bouncing off something coming toward the radar compared to things moving away. It's the same principle that causes a police or ambulance siren to have a slightly lower pitch when the vehicle is driving away from listeners than it does when coming toward them. <PERSON> Merl </PERSON> also said research is under way for short-range Doppler radar systems at airports to detect local wind shears, sudden shifts in wind speed and direction that have caused several airplane crashes in recent years.
</TEXT>
