<HEAD>Conference Focuses On When Aging Aircraft Should Be Retired</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A long-held industry axiom that a jetliner can fly many years beyond its initial design life if maintained and inspected properly is coming under closer scrutiny, say some participants in a three-day conference on aging aircraft. It is only one of many technical issues being debated by more than 350 aircraft design and maintenance experts meeting at the FAA-sponsored conference that began Wednesday. The participants represent airlines, aircraft manufacturers, government and aviation safety groups. All were brought together because of an increased concern about the safety of older jetliners since the in-flight breakup of a 19-year-old <ORGANIZATION> Aloha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737 in April. A 20-foot section of the plane tore away at 24,000 feet and a flight attendant was swept to her death, although the pilots managed to land the aircraft safely. <ORGANIZATION> Aloha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> officials have said repeatedly that they followed all required inspections on the jetliner. <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> Administrator <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> McArtor </PERSON> said that until the federal investigation into the incident is concluded, he could not say whether <PERSON> Aloha </PERSON> violated any <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> requirements in connection with the plane. But <PERSON> McArtor </PERSON> said during a break in the conference Wednesday that a key question that must be resolved in the coming months is whether to continue the current philosophy that relies heavily on inspections or shift the focus to a system of mandatory repairs or, at some point, mandatory aircraft retirement. In the case of <LOCATION> Aloha </LOCATION>, inspectors from both the airlines and the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> failed to detect the cracking and corrosion that is believed to have caused the breakup. `` I think we might find that the procedures are adequate, but I'm not convinced the procedures are being done with as much discipline as we might expect,'' <PERSON> McArtor </PERSON> told reporters. He said the conference is likely to spawn additional, private sessions among industry experts in the coming months on aircraft design, the human pitfalls in the inspection process and whether new federal requirements might be needed. Rep. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Glickman </PERSON>, D-Kan., one of several congressmen to address the industry group, said that the <LOCATION> Aloha </LOCATION> incident demonstrates `` the inadequacies of the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>'s maintenance inspection system. <PERSON> Glickman </PERSON> suggested that the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> must increase its research and development programs on aging aircraft and that the agency should buy old jetliners to determine how long they can be considered to be safe. `` Only by answering the question ` How long can airplanes really last?' will we be able to put into place guidelines which could save thousands of lives,'' <PERSON> Glickman </PERSON> told the conference. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Enders </PERSON>, an aviation consultant for the <ORGANIZATION> Flight </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, suggested in an interview that the <LOCATION> Aloha </LOCATION> accident will prompt increased debate over `` whether the economic life of an airplane'' should remain as dominant a factor as it has been in determining when a plane should be taken out of service. Before the Aloha accident `` generally there was a feeling that you can fly a plane indefinitely'' as long as it is properly maintained and inspected, said <PERSON> Enders </PERSON>, suggesting this philosophy may be changing. But <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoover </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, the airline trade group, reiterated that with proper maintenance and inspections aircraft `` can fly safely throughout their economically useful life.'' The Aloha plane was one of the oldest <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737s in service and had accumulated nearly 90,000 takeoffs and landings.
