`Hurkos reportedly ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARBARA METZLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Dutch psychic detective <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Hurkos </PERSON>, who helped authorities seek clues in the <PERSON> Manson </PERSON> family murders and the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Strangler </ORGANIZATION> case, died of a heart attack Wednesday, his publicist said. He was 77. <PERSON> Hurkos </PERSON>, who had part of his cancerous right lung removed in April, had just left his doctor's office when he was stricken in the hallway of a medical complex near <ORGANIZATION> Cedars-Sinai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, said publicist <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Silver </PERSON>. He was best known for helping authorities in the 1969 <PERSON> Manson </PERSON> family murders of actress <PERSON> Sharon </PERSON> <PERSON> Tate </PERSON> and supermarket owner <PERSON> Leno </PERSON> <PERSON> LaBianca </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Rosemary </PERSON>. <PERSON> Hurkos </PERSON> reportedly told authorities the person responsible for the murders was a bearded man named <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON>, according to `` The Psychic World of <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Hurkos </PERSON>'' by <PERSON> Norma </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Browning </PERSON>, published in 1970. The book also detailed <PERSON> Hurkos </PERSON>' involvement in the Strangler case of 1964, which later was made into a movie starring <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Curtis </PERSON>. <PERSON> Hurkos </PERSON> refused to budge from his position that a man he picked as the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Strangler </ORGANIZATION> was the killer and that confessed strangler <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> DeSalvo </PERSON> was not, the author wrote. `` He was very helpful in any of the police things that he worked on. Why did he go into it? Because he could felt that he probably could contribute.'' Ms. <PERSON> Silver </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Hurkos </PERSON> reportedly became psychic in 1941 after falling from a ladder and suffering a brain injury. On regaining consciousness, he realized he had `` an ability to pierce the barriers that separate the past, present and future,'' his biography states. <PERSON> Hurkos </PERSON> said he was able to see things by touching objects. `` I see pictures in my mind like a television screen. When I touch something, I can then tell what I see,'' he said. He made appearances on several television talk shows and appeared in the motion pictures `` The Amazing World of Psychic Phenomena,'' `` Mysterious Monsters,'' `` Now I Lay Me Down to Sleep'' and `` The <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> Strangler.'' He was the author of three books, `` Psychic,'' ` The Psychic World of <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Hurkos </PERSON>'' and `` <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Hurkos </PERSON>: I Have Many Lives.'' Born in <LOCATION> Dordrecht </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Holland </LOCATION>, he came to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1956 for psychic experiments, and lived in the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> area about 25 years. Surviving are his wife, <PERSON> Stephany </PERSON> <PERSON> Courtney </PERSON>; a daughter and six children from a previous marriage.
