<FIRST>r w PM-LieDetectors     06-02 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lie Detectors,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bill Restricting Company Lie Detector Tests Clears House</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Legislation that would significantly reduce the number of lie detector tests administered by private companies now needs only <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> approval to go to the president for signature into law. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> voted 251-120 on Wednesday in favor of the conference report, a compromise version of differing bills passed earlier by the two chambers. <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> approval would send the legislation to the president. The Office of Technology Assessment estimated that about 2 million such tests were administered last year, and that 90 percent were administered by private employers, mostly to job applicants but also to workers under investigation. The accuracy of test results has been questioned, and so has the competency of some examiners. Twenty-two states prohibit the tests in the private sector, and 19 regulate their private use. The legislation would permit private sector testing of applicants for only two types of jobs. Those applying for security guard positions could still be tested, and so could prospective employees who would have direct access to the manufacture, storage, distribution or sale of controlled substances. The bill also has several provisions to protect the rights of workers subject to tests. The bill would prohibit an employee from being discharged, dismissed, disciplined, discriminated against, or denied employment or promotion solely on the basis of the test, or solely for refusal to take the test. To take action against the worker, an employer would have to have additional supporting evidence. Questions on religious or political beliefs could not be asked, and all questions would have to be submitted to the examinee in writing before the examination. The examinee could end the test at any time. An employer could test an employee during an investigation involving economic loss or injury to the company. However, the employee would have to have had access to the property that is the subject of the investigation, and the employer would have to have a reasonable suspicion that the worker was involved in the incident. Before the test began, the worker would have to be given specific information about the incident under investigation. Only the federal government would be permitted to administer tests to those employed by, assigned to, or detailed to the nation's intelligence agencies and to <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> contract employees. Qualification standards would be set for examiners, who would need a license granted by the state, if one was required. The examiner also would have to maintain a $ 50,000 bond. The legislation would take effect six months after it became law.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
