<HEAD>Navy Forecasting Job Losses at Eight Public Shipyards</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> is forecasting new job reductions at its eight public shipyards, where employment already has dropped 9 percent since 1985. An unpublished naval planning document shows that the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> is projecting a 21 percent cutback in employment at the yards between now and the end of fiscal 1991. The job figures are only estimates, and are subject to change because of schedule shifts, new work or other factors. The May 11 document, obtained this week from congressional sources, projects employment requirements based on ship repair and modernization assignments for the 1989, 1990 and 1991 fiscal years. The Naval Sea Systems Command document resulted from a recent ship scheduling conference sponsored by the systems command, which oversees the eight yards. Overall, employment in the yards would shrink from about 71,100 now to 64,050 in the fall of 1989. The workforce then would shrink further to 57,150 the next year and 56,400 the year after that. The current 71,100 figure includes about 4,000 temporary and part-time employees. The systems command, in a statement in response to a reporter's query, said the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> has neither published employment projections nor announced layoffs `` However, shipyard employment figures are routinely reviewed and working documents are prepared to determine what employment levels are necessary to meet fleet operational requirements,'' the statement said. `` Exact naval shipyard employment figures will not be determined until the budget process is completed for fiscal year 1989 and beyond,'' it said. The eight yards have already seen their collective workforce trimmed by 7,000 from the 78,100 who were employed in January 1985. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> said those reductions were prompted in part by a declining number of ship overhauls. Some yards would see their workforce dip and then swell again, under the projections of the May 11 document. For example, employment at the Puget Sound Naval Shipyard in <LOCATION> Bremerton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, is estimated to dip from 11,400 to 8,500 by the fall of 1990, before climbing back to 10,000 the following year. Puget Sound spokesman <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Andrae </PERSON> said that while he was not familiar with the working document, the yard was `` pretty well aware'' of its workload over the next few years. `` I think you'll find we're not the only shipyard where you'll see some rather wide swings in manpower,'' <PERSON> Andrae </PERSON> said `` You go down for a couple of years and all of a sudden you've got to make a dramatic increase. Skilled labor does n't come easily, and that presents some challenges.'' A similar pattern was projected at the <LOCATION> Norfolk </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Naval </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Shipyard </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Portsmouth </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>. Employment at <LOCATION> Norfolk </LOCATION>, whose 12,700 workers make it the largest public yard, was forecast at 11,350 in the fall of 1989, 9,700 in 1990, and 10,900 in 1991 Employment at the <ORGANIZATION> Philadelphia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Naval </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shipyard </ORGANIZATION>, now at about 8,700, is projected to decline to 6,800. The yard likely would lay off 749 temporary workers first, officials said. The <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, shipyard would suffer the least disruption to its workforce, with its employment remaining between 5,000 and 5,250 during the three years. The Mare Island yard in northern <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> would see its workforce drop to 10,000 in the fall of 1989, followed by a loss of another 3,800 workers and then a gain of 1,300 to bring it back up to 7,500. <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Pearl </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Yard </LOCATION>, which employs about 6,100 now, would drop to 4,000. Among Eastern yards, <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION>, would go from about 8,600 to 6,200. The <LOCATION> Portsmouth </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.H. </LOCATION>, yard would remain at about 8,000 workers until 1991, then dip to 5,800 at the end of 1991.
</TEXT>
