<HEAD>Vice President Shrugs Off Conservative Figures' Influence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said in a published interview that two of the nation's well-known and outspoken conservatives are fringe elements whose support is n't necessary for victory in the presidential election. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, interviewed by The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> at his oceanside retreat in <LOCATION> Kennebunkport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> on Wednesday, shrugged off the influence of <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Viguerie </PERSON>, a writer and direct-mail specialist, and <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Caucus </ORGANIZATION>. `` There's only one or two that polarize, and <PERSON> Viguerie </PERSON> and <PERSON> Howie </PERSON> <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON> are two of them; it does n't matter in terms of total vote,'' the vice president said in the interview, published in Thursday's editions of the Times. `` There is only a handful of <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Vigueries </PERSON> out there,'' said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, the all-but certain Republican presidential nominee. Asked if he had to do business with <PERSON> Viguerie </PERSON> to win the election, he said: `` I do n't believe that.'' `` The fact that he -LRB- <PERSON> Viguerie </PERSON> -RRB- does n't agree with me on a lot of things or has opposed me for many years, that does n't bother me one iota,'' said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. <PERSON> Viguerie </PERSON>, the vice president said, `` gets his name in the paper by criticizing other Republicans all the time.'' A <PERSON> Viguerie </PERSON> spokeswoman, <PERSON> Carolyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Melenick </PERSON>, said Wednesday night that <PERSON> Viguerie </PERSON> would have no immediate comment on <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s remarks. <PERSON> Viguerie </PERSON> said last month that he would vote for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> also told the newspaper he would be meeting soon with Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said over the weekend that the two had met recently, and <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> said he would not do anything to harm <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s presidential campaign. The attorney general is under investigation by an independent counsel, and the Democrats have been using the issue to attack <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. `` I think he's been made aware by the polls and by a lot of public comment that there is the danger that this matter, if it stays exactly the way it is, could not only adversely affect me, but affect others as well,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said of <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was also asked if he agreed with President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s contention, made at the superpower summit in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, that Soviet bureaucracy, rather than <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> policy, was apparently responsible for delays in granting exit visas, or refusal to grant them at all The newspaper said the vice president did not answer directly, but said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> have `` fundamental differences'' on human rights. `` There is a long way to go before they have lived up to provisions of the <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION> final act,'' he said, adding that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was committed to `` broad, objective standards on human rights.''
