<HEAD>Court Rules Soldiers Can Wear Earring</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Male Norwegian soldiers can wear an earring if they wish, a court has ruled. The civilian court in <LOCATION> Hammerfest </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>'s northernmost town, recently handed down the decision on a soldier's appeal against a $ 48 fine he received last fall for refusing to remove a small earring, the national <ORGANIZATION> NTB </ORGANIZATION> news agency reported. <ORGANIZATION> NTB </ORGANIZATION> quoted the <ORGANIZATION> Finnmark </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dagblad </ORGANIZATION> newspaper, published in <ORGANIZATION> Tromsoe </ORGANIZATION>, as saying the unidentified soldier challenged a military regulation stating that only women are allowed to wear `` ear jewelry.'' The magistrates voted 2-1 that the code was discriminatory. The two judges voting in the soldier's favor were women, while the male judge voted to uphold the previous dress codes, <ORGANIZATION> NTB </ORGANIZATION> reported.
