<HEAD>Republicans See a Bush Opportunity to Part Company from Reagan</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS Bush comment in New York Times interview in grafs
9-10; picks up 9th graf pvs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Republican politicians say the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> summit has presented Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> with one of his best chances yet to establish a more separate identity from President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and reassure conservatives in his own party. `` There comes a time and I would say to him this is the time,'' said <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahe </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> political consultant. Conservative Republicans were especially displeased with <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s statement Wednesday that the Soviet bureaucracy _ and not policies of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> leadership _ may be the reason so many Russian dissidents are barred from leaving the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. `` I respectfully disagree with the president's statement,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.Y. </LOCATION> `` Human rights problems are endemic to the Soviet system, not just the bureaucracy, but the fundamental nature of government.'' `` I think that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> could reassure conservatives by demonstrating that he is totally realistic about the Soviets,'' said <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Stone </PERSON>, a consultant who worked on <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> presidential campaigns in 1980 and 1984, as well as on <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON>'s unsuccessful bid for the 1988 GOP presidential nomination. At a news conference in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> near the close of his summit with Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> suggested that problems Soviet citizens are having getting exit visas were caused by the bureaucracy rather than government policy. `` I just have to believe that in any government some of us do find ourselves bound in by bureaucracy,'' said the president, apparently at pains to avoid direct criticism of his Soviet hosts. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said he thought <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> was attempting to overcome these bureaucratic barriers. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> took a fairly neutral tack when he was asked about the president's remarks. The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>, which interviewed him Wednesday, asked him about it, and said in today's editions that the vice president did not respond directly. Instead, he noted that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> have `` fundamental differences'' on human rights, and added: `` There is a long way to go before they have lived up to provisions of the <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION> final act.'' But the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> comments brought quick reaction from human rights observers as well as other politicians back home. `` It's really hard to know where <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> was coming from on that,'' said <PERSON> Dawn </PERSON> <PERSON> Mann </PERSON>, a fellow at the <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Strategic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION>, an independent policy research institute. `` The fact that there still are several hundred prisoners of conscience is not attributable to bureaucratic snafus.'' Rep. <PERSON> Gus </PERSON> <PERSON> Yatron </PERSON>, D-Pa., chairman of the Human Rights subcommittee of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, defended the president and said he thought <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> was trying to be polite `` I can think of no one in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> or the administration who feels that <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s repressive policies are not the results of the repressive nature of the Soviet government,'' he said. `` I would want to give the president the benefit of the doubt.'' Rep. <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Solomon </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the senior Republican on <PERSON> Yatron </PERSON>'s subcommittee, said he thought <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s approach could help open the way for loosening of Soviet emigration policy. `` That gives wriggle for <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> to react, and without confrontational demands,'' he said. `` I'm confident that it will work.'' But within the political community, the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> comments were viewed far differently. Extreme conservatives were apoplectic. `` He's certainly become <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s No. 1 apologist for the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Viguerie </PERSON>, who has taken to criticizing <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> for being soft toward the Soviets. `` Who is he kidding?'' asked <PERSON> Juliana </PERSON> <PERSON> Pilon </PERSON> of the conservative <ORGANIZATION> Heritage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>. `` It just is n't true.'' <PERSON> Mahe </PERSON> said of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s comments, `` Those sentiments would not really reflect <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s sentiments.'' He said they could give <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> an opportunity to demonstrate to voters an area where he and the president disagree. `` What this provides him is an opportunity to say, well, I respect the president but I ca n't find myself in agreement on those things,'' he said. `` I would tell him -LRB- <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> -RRB-, the opportunity is at hand, let's jump on it,'' added <PERSON> Mahe </PERSON> `` <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s clearly trying to be kind to his hosts,'' said Stone. `` But it's an unrealistic position.''
