985, press conference held to discus the findings of the three-month investigation. <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> was hired by <PERSON> Hutton </PERSON> after the firm pleaded guilty May 2, 1985, to 2,000 counts of mail and wire fraud stemming from the check kiting scheme. The company, now part of <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, agreed to pay a $ 2 million fine and reimburse banks for millions of dollars in interest lost when branch offices wrote checks against money that had not been deposited in their checking accounts. <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> strongly defended his investigation, saying he did n't cite any top officials for wrongdoing because all he could prove was that senior executives did n't monitor the activities of branch and regional offices. `` I thought I could catch a high person, but I never could,'' <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> acknowledged that he was suspicious of high officials, including former <PERSON> Hutton </PERSON> president <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ball </PERSON>. But there was no evidence that any top <PERSON> Hutton </PERSON> official intentional sanctioned any check writing practice that was later found to be illegal, he said. `` I'm not going to put my name on something charging somebody with wrongdoing if they had n't met the test _ if they did not have the intent to do something wrong,'' <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> testified. `` I never found anybody on a high level at <PERSON> Hutton </PERSON> that knew what was going on,'' <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> said. The problem was `` they did n't have any controls at all,'' <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Hutton </PERSON> `` just letting people go wild, doing whatever they wanted to do.'' He credited the investigations he and the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> conducted with changing overdraft procedures of major corporations. <PERSON> Bell </PERSON>'s report recommended that <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Morley </PERSON>, <PERSON> Hutton </PERSON>'s `` money mobilizer,'' be relieved of any duties involving the company's banking activities <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lynch </PERSON>, a vice president whom <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> identified as the chief financial officer, was also forced to resign for failing to keep adequate controls.
