<HEAD>Explosion, Fire Kill 1, Injure At Least 10 In Industrial Park</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with 1 dead, two missing; picks
up 3rd graf pvs; SUBS 7th graf pvs, `Fire Lt. ... to UPDATE with
evacuees allowed to return home, editing to conform; ADDS byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORTH CHICAGO, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An explosion and fire ripped through an industrial park Wednesday, killing one person, injuring at least 10 and prompting 2,000 to flee before the blaze was brought under control, authorities said. Two people were unaccounted for hours after the 3:30 p.m. explosion at <ORGANIZATION> Traco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a plastics manufacturer in this industrial northern <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> suburb, said Lt. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. He said he suspected the two were <ORGANIZATION> Traco </ORGANIZATION> employees. The body was found about 11:30 p.m. in the rubble of the explosion, <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON> said. One of the injured was listed in critical condition and four were firefighters treated for heat exhaustion from battling the fire. `` It shook City Hall, which is about two miles away,'' said Mayor <PERSON> Bobby </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>, who ordered a precautionary evacuation for the 2,000 to 3,000 people who live near the Coleman Industrial Complex, due to potentially toxic fumes. The fire was brought under control about 8:30 p.m., but toxic chemicals burned in the fire included chlorine, polyvinyl chloride and polystyrene, said <PERSON> Will </PERSON> <PERSON> Flowers </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>, 27, of <LOCATION> Antioch </LOCATION> was hospitalized in critical condition with facial burns, smoke inhalation and cuts on his head, face and legs, said <PERSON> Joanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, spokeswoman at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Therese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Waukegan </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> said authorities were asking people within a two-mile area to close all doors and windows and turn off air conditioners to avoid possible respiratory injuries. <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> estimated that 2,000 people evacuated their homes but were allowed to return late in the evening. They were advised to kept doors and windows shut. The mayor said six to 10 businesses burned, but there was no immediate estimate of damages. The cause of the explosion was not immediately known. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, with a population of about 47,000, is about 35 miles north of downtown <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, and is the home of the Great Lakes Naval Training Station.
