<DATELINE>SALTA, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A cold spell that sent temperatures plunging to 3 degrees in southern <LOCATION> Patagonia </LOCATION> has led to the deaths of at least 11 people, authorities say. Winter is still 20 days away in the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hemisphere </ORGANIZATION>, but the cold snap has forced pedestrians in <LOCATION> Buenos </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aires </LOCATION> to don ski parkas and hand mittens. And heavy snows have already closed several passes in the Andes mountains between <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>. On Wednesday, police discovered the 11th victim, a man frozen to death in this northwestern city. In other incidents, authorities said three brothers burned to death in southwestern <LOCATION> Neuquen </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Province </LOCATION> when their stove overheated and caught fire, two men were found frozen to death in northwestern <LOCATION> Cordoba </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Province </LOCATION> and a middle-aged couple died of asphyxiation when their heating system failed in <LOCATION> Buenos </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aires </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Province </LOCATION>. On Tuesday, authorities found the bodies of a baby girl and an elderly man from the resort of <ORGANIZATION> Mar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> del </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Plata </ORGANIZATION> and another man near downtown <LOCATION> Salta </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Mar </LOCATION> <LOCATION> del </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plata </LOCATION> is 250 miles south of <LOCATION> Buenos </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aires </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Salta </LOCATION> is 1,000 miles northwest of the capital.
