administration so the voters can see him as they -LRB- the supporters -RRB- know him'' said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> staff chief <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON>. `` I do n't know that that means staking out a lot of different positions as much as it means trying to communicate to voters the strengths of <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s proposal for a modified spending freeze won solid support from economists who advised him this week, all of whom are <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> backers. `` We all concluded that a flexible freeze is the right way to go, that is indeed doable,'' said former deputy treasury secretary <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Darman </PERSON>, now a consultant with <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bros. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Darman </PERSON> said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> would contrast his plan with what he called the `` <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> mirage'' of <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, a dig at the Democratic front-runner's management of his state's economy. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s plan depends on a reduction in the budget deficit that is occuring anyway and a fast-rising surplus in the nation's Social Security trust fund, and no downturn in economic growth, the economists conceded. <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> economist <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Feldstein </PERSON>, who in the past has advocated tax increases to reduce the federal deficit, told reporters he's joined the ranks of true believers in the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> plan. If <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is elected, financial markets will rally on the assumption that the deficit will be attacked seriously, said <PERSON> Feldstein </PERSON>, a former chairman of President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advisers </ORGANIZATION>. `` The markets will respond and bring down interest rates another notch, 2 percentage points, and that will get us down and get us within inches of budget balance in 1993,'' said <PERSON> Feldstein </PERSON>. Democratic critics, as well as many private economists, argue that it is unlikely the budget deficit, $ 150 billion last year, can be eliminated without some form of new taxes. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s proposed `` flexible freeze'' would keep overall spending except for Social Security payments at levels in the budget approved by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for fiscal year 1989, plus inflation. The freeze would be `` flexible'' because some spending could go up, but it would have to be offset by identical reductions in other areas. However, so far, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has not provided details on which programs he would like to cut and which ones he would like to see expanded. `` There have to be choices,'' <PERSON> Feldstein </PERSON> said. `` I assume the vice president is going to wait until he sits down with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to negotiate those details.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> himself said earlier in the week that he did n't feel any `` compulsion to give 20-point programs on everyting.'' And <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON>, a key <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> supporter, told reporters: `` You will see in the campaign the detailed plans on how to deal with each of these issues. But the clock will not be set by those who ask the question. The clock will be set by the candidate.''
