<HEAD>Record Season For Ticket Sales; Production Drops</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Theatergoers gave their regards to <LOCATION> Broadway </LOCATION>, buying a record number of tickets during the 1987-88 season despite having fewer productions to choose from. During the season, which ran June 1, 1987, to May 29, $ 253 million worth of tickets were sold to more than 8.1 million theatergoers, the <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Theaters </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Producers </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday. The previous season, ticket sales were $ 209 million and attendance hit 7 million for 40 Broadway productions. The 21 percent increase in ticket sales and 16 percent increase in attendance occurred despite a drop in the number of productions to 32 during the 1987-88 season. `` This was a more balanced season between musicals and plays,'' said <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Wachtel </PERSON>, the league's research director. `` Last season we seemed to have three musical megahits _ ` Me and My Girl,' ` <ORGANIZATION> Les </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Miserables </ORGANIZATION>' and ` Starlight Express.' That focused attention on Broadway and set us up for where we are now.'' Twelve new musicals opened during the 1987-88 season compared with 11 the previous year. `` The Phantom of the Opera,'' the <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Webber </PERSON> musical that opened with a record $ 19 million advance sale, gave the biggest boost to the season. It was joined by several other strong musical shows including `` Sarafina!'', a surprise hit from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>; a revival of the Cole Porter musical `` Anything Goes,'' and `` Chess,'' a big British musical that is doing well at the box office despite mostly negative reviews. `` There's a lot of choice on Broadway which is probably why there are so many people going,'' said <PERSON> Wachtel </PERSON>. There were eight new plays on Broadway, down from 13 the previous season, but of the eight, only one _ `` Serious Money'' _ closed quickly. Five others are still running, including the four strong <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> nominees for best play _ `` A Walk in the Woods'' by <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Blessing </PERSON>, `` <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON>'s Come and Gone'' by <PERSON> August </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, `` M. Butterfly'' by <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Hwang </PERSON> and `` Speed-the-Plow'' by <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Mamet </PERSON>. `` The eight plays that have opened this year are the fewest number in the entire history of the Broadway theater,'' said <PERSON> Rocco </PERSON> <PERSON> Landesman </PERSON>, president of Jujamcyn Theaters, which owns five Broadway theaters. `` Granted they are of a high quality. If you feel like I do that the play is the lifeblood of the Broadway theater, that's a very worrisome statistic.'' If production was down, ticket prices were up. The $ 50 ticket for a musical is now the norm rather than the exception. A $ 40 top ticket for a play on weekend nights is also not unusual with such productions as `` M. Butterfly,'' `` Macbeth'' and `` Broadway Bound'' charging that amount. The average paid admission, according to the league, was $ 31.10, up from $ 29.86 for the previous season. <PERSON> Wachtel </PERSON> was optimistic about the 1988-89 season. Among the possibilities are several big musicals including `` Legs Diamond'' starring <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> and a revival of `` The Merry Widow'' starring <PERSON> Cleo </PERSON> <PERSON> Laine </PERSON>, as well as two <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> comedies. `` In terms of attendance, I think we will do very well because the last three weeks have been extraordinary,'' <PERSON> Wachtel </PERSON> said. `` We have the momentum to keep going. A lot of that may be tourism, the weakness of the dollar. The pickup we usually get from tourism during the summer is happening earlier.'' <PERSON> Landesman </PERSON> said he wants to see theatergoers attending more than just the big musical hits like `` Phantom'' or `` Les Miserables.'' `` I'd like to see more people spread out among more productions,'' said <PERSON> Landesman </PERSON>. `` Because the producing situation is so tough now, a lot of things do n't go to <LOCATION> Broadway </LOCATION> unless they are proven or established. You want to have a situation where there are a lot of things going on _ some good, some bad and some ugly.''
