 until after <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> was born. `` I kept thinking I'll have a girl and I'll tell her not to have children. I've always wanted a lot of kids. That's been my goal since I was little,'' she said. Mrs. <PERSON> Chappel </PERSON> is not bitter. She says she feels fortunate in many ways to have been blessed with four loving boys and caring friends and relatives. `` Willie hugs me and tells me he loves me. They all have taught me so much,'' she said. Because of the disease, <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> has a small esophagus, which causes difficulty in breathing. He tires easily and can walk only about a half block at a time, so she sometimes must carry him. <PERSON> Willie </PERSON>'s future might be brief, but Mrs. <PERSON> Chappel </PERSON> said she'll continue doing everything she can to make him happy `` He'll be home with me until I die or he dies. <PERSON> Willie </PERSON>'s time is my time.'' She hopes he can enroll in a day adult program for the handicapped so he can continue socializing and being around people.
