<FIRST>r a PM-AIDS-Monkeys     06-02 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS-Monkeys,0552</SECOND>
<HEAD>AIDS Virus May Have Infected Human Ancestors 20 Million Years Ago</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RAEBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A predecessor of the AIDS virus could have infected primitive human ancestors more than 20 million years ago and evolved as modern humans evolved, researchers say. A determination of the entire genetic code, or sequence, of an AIDS virus found in an African green monkey suggests that the virus did not jump recently from monkeys to humans, the researchers said in an article published today in Nature, the British scientific journal. Some researchers have suggested that these monkeys may have been the source of the human AIDS virus. A team led by <PERSON> Masanori </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayami </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> found that the African green monkey AIDS virus differed from the two known human AIDS viruses in several important respects. If the virus had jumped from monkeys to humans in recent times, the viruses would be identical or nearly so, said <PERSON> Carel </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulder </PERSON>, a biologist at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Worcester </LOCATION>. `` It is impossible that humans were infected in any recent time with this virus,'' <PERSON> Mulder </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. The Japanese researchers and <PERSON> Mulder </PERSON> say that the evidence now suggests that each species could have its own version of the AIDS virus. Two AIDS viruses have been identified in humans. They could have evolved in isolated populations in different places, the Japanese researchers reported. Humans and monkeys are descendants of primitive primates that may have lived 20 million to 30 million years ago. The Japanese researchers believe that an AIDS-like virus infected those primitive primates. As those creatures evolved into humans and various species of monkeys, the parent AIDS virus evolved into the different forms seen today, the researchers speculated. No AIDS virus is known in apes, which are more closely related to humans than are monkeys. Dr. <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Letvin </PERSON>, a primate specialist at the <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, said of the Japanese research, `` This is yet another piece of data in support of what I think should now be accepted _ that a jump of the virus did not occur.'' Asked why the virus has only recently been observed to cause disease, <PERSON> Letvin </PERSON> said that it could have existed for a long time only in isolated populations, and that it might also have evolved into its present disease-causing form in comparatively recent times. The virus that <PERSON> Hayami </PERSON> and his colleagues studied was isolated from a wild African green monkey obtained in <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>. Their determination, or sequencing, of the virus's genetic code shows that it lacks some genetic material carried by the human AIDS viruses. The two human AIDS viruses are HIV-1, which is almost exclusively responsible for the worldwide epidemic of acquired immune deficiency syndrome, and HIV-2, which is mostly limited to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> but is now slowly beginning to spread. Researchers disagree over whether HIV-2 causes disease. The African green monkey virus lacks the so-called `` R'' gene present in HIV-1 and HIV-2, the Japanese researchers report. In addition, the African green monkey virus does not appear to make monkeys sick. Researchers are trying to determine the function of the R gene, <PERSON> Mulder </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
