<HEAD>Reagan Invokes Obscure Proverb in Moscow Farewell</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> today invoked an obscure Russian proverb in his farewell to Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. `` Mr. General Secretary, if you will permit me just one more proverb,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. `` I think a very old and popular saying you have here about last Sunday, the day of our arrival, spoke to the promise we have seen fulfilled at this summit in this <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> spring.'' Then, in halting Russian, the president said, `` <LOCATION> Troitsa </LOCATION> _ ves les postroitsya.'' Literally, the proverb translates into English as `` Holiday of the Trinity _ and the whole forest will blossom.'' This is a reference to the old Russian Orthodox holiday of <LOCATION> Trinity </LOCATION>, celebrated on the last Sunday in May, and the fact that birch trees _ a symbol of <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION> _ are green then, auguring a good summer. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> arrived in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> on May 29, the last Sunday of the month.
