<TEXT>
 Share prices closed at a record high on the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> today, while the dollar posted a moderate gain against the Japanese yen. The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues gained 165.45 points, or 0.59 percent, to close at 27,869.36. The previous high for <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>'s main economic barometer was set on May 17 when the Nikkei closed at 27,819.98. The index skyrocketed in early trading, momentarily touching 27,930.58, but lost momentum after investors started selling shares for profit-taking toward the end of the morning session, brokers said. `` There is growing concern for inflation and rising interest rates,'' said a broker at a major securities firm. `` The market slowed down from late morning to the early afternoon session, but it regained strength toward the end of the day's trading,'' he added, speaking on condition of anonymity. Volume today totaled 1.9 billion shares, with 1.3 billion traded this morning. Meanwhile, the dollar rose 0.33 yen from its 125.35-yen Wednesday finish to close at 125.68 yen. It had started the day at 125.50 yen and traded mainly between 125.48-125 .78 yen Traders said bullishness prevailed in the market throughout the day, but gains in the dollar for the past four days had investors worried. They added that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency's strength against the Japanese yen has been fueled mainly through profit-taking by investors. ` Ahead of the unemployment rate release scheduled for tomorrow -LRB- Friday -RRB- in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>, market players sold the yen at the current favorable rate,'' said <PERSON> Hiroaki </PERSON> <PERSON> Shukuzawa </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Sumitomo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>.
