<HEAD>Britain Loses `Spycatcher' Case _ And A Heap Of Money With It</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CANBERRA, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The British government today lost a two-year court battle to stop a former intelligence officer from publishing his memoirs in <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> and was ordered to pay an estimated $ 900,000 in legal costs. In a unanimous decision, the High Court of <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> finally rejected the British government's attempt to stop publication of the book `` Spycatcher'' by <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, a 20-year veteran of the MI-5 counter-espionage service. Arguing that <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s catch-all Official Secrets Act committed <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> to life-long secrecy, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> also sought to seize profits from sales of the book. Unspecified legal costs, estimated by lawyers at more than $ 900,000, were awarded to <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s publisher by the <LOCATION> Canberra </LOCATION> court, which upheld lower court decisions that had all favored the publisher. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, 73, was delighted and planning a `` quiet celebration'' on his horse farm in <LOCATION> Tasmania </LOCATION>, said his lawyer, <PERSON> Malcolm </PERSON> <PERSON> Turnbull </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s deputy high commissioner in <LOCATION> Canberra </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Malcolm </PERSON> <PERSON> Dougal </PERSON>, told <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> after the hearing: `` We still believe that a crown servant has a duty of obligation, a duty of confidentiality to the government. We are naturally disappointed.'' <PERSON> Dougal </PERSON> told the British network that it was up to <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to consider whether to continue the fight in other countries. `` Spycatcher'' has been banned in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and colonial <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> by government legal action. Another hearing in the continuing fight to maintain the ban in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> takes place before <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lords </ORGANIZATION> judges on June 13. Despite the bans, the book has sold more than 1.4 million copies worldwide and 250,000 copies in <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennetto </PERSON>, spokeswoman for <ORGANIZATION> Octopus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, which controls <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s publishers, <PERSON> Heinemann </PERSON>, said in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> today: `` When this all started almost three years ago we were worried that <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> would never see the fruit of his labors being published because he has been so ill. It is delightful that he now can.'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s book, easily available in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> in U.S.-published copies, describes how the British intelligence community bugged and burgled its way around <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, snooping on individuals, politicians and foreign embassies. It alleges that right-wing intelligence officers plotted in the 1970s to destabilize the Labor government of then Prime Minister <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>. Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commons </ORGANIZATION> that the book threatened national security, but <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said he had n't revealed any secrets jeopardizing <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> In its ruling, the court said the British government had not sought to enforce private rights or private interests in a foreign state. It said <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s primary interest had been to ensure the continued secrecy of MI-5's operations and to protect national security. The judges said it was tempting to suggest that because of the close relationship between <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> an exception should be made to enable <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> to enforce its law in Australian courts. But, the court said, `` there are no manageable standards by which courts can resolve such an issue and its determination would inevitably present a risk of embarrassment in <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>'s relations with other countries.''
