<FIRST>r a PM-PregnancyRates     06-02 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pregnancy Rates,0422</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Pregnancy, Abortion Rates Higher Than Many Industrialized
Countries</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> women have higher rates of unplanned pregnancies and abortions than women in many other industrialized countries, according to a study. The study by the <ORGANIZATION> Alan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guttmacher </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, a New York-based organization that examines fertility issues, also found that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> women relied more on abortion and less on contraception to limit births than women in most other Western nations. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> women of reproductive age averaged 2.56 pregnancies and 0.76 abortions, according to the study. Only <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> showed higher pregnancy rates, at 4.33 and 3.23, respectively, among the nations studied. <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> also had a higher abortion rate, 2.24, as did <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, 0.80. The study, of all countries in <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> plus <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, appears in the current issue of the institute's Family Planning Perspectives. The lowest pregnancy rates were in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, with 1.64, and the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, with 1.68. The lowest abortion rates were in <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>, with 0.15, and the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, with 0.18. Abortion is outlawed in <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>, although abortions are still relatively easy to to obtain in <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>, the researchers said. The study found that 51.2 percent of pregnancies in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1983 were unplanned, compared with 31.8 percent in <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and 17 percent in the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>. Many contraceptives used in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and elsewhere are not approved for use in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, said Dr. <PERSON> Jacqueline </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Forrest </PERSON>, vice president for research of the institute. The more contraceptive choices available, the more likely a woman will find one that she will use consistently, she said. In addition, the study found that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> women are less likely to use birth control pills or intrauterine devices than women in other developed countries, Ms. <PERSON> Forrest </PERSON> said. These are the most effective forms of birth control. The researchers said some method of contraception was used in 1982 by 54 percent of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> women between ages 15 to 44. That level ranked low, and was similar to that of <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>. Birth control techniques used by 37 percent of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> women included pills, IUD or male or female sterilization, a `` medium'' level compared with the other countries. That ranking is largely due to the widespread use of sterilization in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> for women older than 30, the researchers said. The study used the most recent data available. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> abortion rates are 1983 figures.
