<FIRST>r i PM-HassledEmbassy 1stLd-Writethru a0407 06-02 0788</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hassled Embassy, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0407,790</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fires, Bugs, Spy Dust and Glasnost Harrass This Embassy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New 1st graf with Reagan stop at embassy; picks up 2nd graf
pvs, ``Amid it xxx''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> stopped by one of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s most hassled embassies today, saluting diplomats and staff who have lived through a `` spy dust'' scare, Soviet bugging, alleged security breaches by Marine guards and a fire. Amid it all, the blossoming of superpower relations and the radical changes in Soviet society ushered in by <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> have dramatically increased the workload of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s official eyes and ears in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> An American diplomat said the embassy workers were grateful to <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> for taking the time to have breakfast with them and their families. `` He has these embassy visits wherever he goes, but in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> in particular he's certainly aware of the unusual difficulties we've had,'' the diplomat said, speaking on condition he not be identified The biggest jolt to the comfort and convenience of the folks at No. 19-23 Tchaikovsky Street came Oct. 22, 1986, when the <ORGANIZATION> Kremlin </ORGANIZATION> retaliated for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> expulsions of Soviet diplomats. It ordered 260 Soviets to stop cooking, cleaning, driving, translating and answering phones at the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> embassy and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> consulate in <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION>. Diplomats had to do their own driving, cleaning and other chores. <PERSON> Donna </PERSON> <PERSON> Hartman </PERSON>, the wife of then-Ambassador <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Hartman </PERSON>, took over the gardening at her residence. `` We did what we had to do. It was n't heroic, but it is somewhat satisfying in knowing we survived it,'' recalled one diplomat who mopped floors and carried supplies around the embassy for six months. Gradually the embassy has bounced back, becoming a more efficient operation by necessity. The diplomatic staff was cut to make room for American staff support under a Soviet-imposed personnel ceiling of 225. The government brought in a <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles-based </LOCATION> company, <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Architects </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION>, to run the embassy. It now has 84 support employees. The diplomat said the arrangement has worked well. `` The Pacific Architects and Engineers people meshed in very well,'' she said. But some officials traveling with <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> say privately that the embassy diplomats remain overworked, and have n't been concentrating enough on their main duties: filing cables back to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> on what's going on in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. They also complain that the embassy did n't prepare well enough for the Reagan-Gorbachev summit. Embassy spokesman <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> admits the staff is having trouble coping. `` We need more hands. At a time when U.S.-Soviet contacts are exploding, the number of hands is limited by other than the personnel practices of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government,'' he said in reference to the Soviet-imposed staff limit. The diplomats are feeling under extra pressure since <PERSON> Hartman </PERSON> was succeeded by <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Matlock </PERSON>, who is described by embassy press officer <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Hurley </PERSON> as a `` hard taskmaster.'' The summit itself and the frequent visits by Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> have been an extra load on the staff, <PERSON> Hurley </PERSON> said. `` These visits prevent us from doing what we're here for: looking at <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> society and explaining it to people back home,'' he said. In addition to the withdrawal of the Soviet employees, the embassy has faced these problems in the recent years: _ In 1985, the embassy annnounced it had found traces of a chemical dubbed `` spy dust'' that Soviet agents were alleged to be using to track American diplomats It turned out the substance was not believed to be hazardous. _ Last spring, a scandal erupted over charges that <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> guards had allowed Soviet agents inside secret areas of the embassy Many of the charges fizzled, but Marine Sgt. <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Lonetree </PERSON>, an embassy guard in 1985 and 1986, was convicted of espionage for giving the <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> the identities of <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> agents and the floor plans to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> embassies in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>. _ Also last spring, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials revealed that the uncompleted $ 191 million new <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> embassy office building was riddled with hidden <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> listening devices Government investigation panels have recommended the top floors of the building be stripped off. _ Fire broke out Feb. 17 in an unoccupied fifth-floor residential section of the aging main office building Two <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> congressmen who inspected the building in April of last year had called it a `` firetrap and unsafe by accepted standards for general working conditions.'' _ And, off and on for 25 years, the Soviets have bombarded the embassy with microwave radiation Despite intense investigation, no one in the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> government is willing to say whether the purpose is espionage, interference with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> intelligence-gathering operations, or an attempt to affect the health, minds or behavior of Americans working in the embassy. Low-power microwave signals continue to be detected.
