 A convicted sex offender could face a more severe sentence if he tests positive for the AIDS virus after the state <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> refused to overturn a lower court ruling requiring the test, a prosecutor said. <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Farmer </PERSON>, a 34-year-old former flight attendant, took the test Wednesday. He was convicted in April of two counts of patronizing a juvenile male prostitute and two counts of sexual exploitation of a minor. Deputy Prosecutor <PERSON> Rebecca </PERSON> <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> contended that Farmer knew he had tested positive for the virus when he had contact with the two prostitutes, including sexual intercourse with one of them. Jurors who convicted Farmer were not told he was believed to have the virus for acquired immune defiency syndrome, which attacks the body's immune system and can be transmitted through sexual intercourse. On Tuesday, <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> commissioner <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON> upheld a May 24 <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling that Farmer submit to the test before his sentencing Tuesday. <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON> said there was a legitimate concern that Farmer, who is on court-supervised release, would continue to engage in the same sexual conduct. Defense attorney <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Iaria </PERSON> appealed <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON>' decision, but a three-judge appeals panel later upheld the ruling. By court order, the test results will not be made public. But Ms. <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> has said that if Farmer tests positive for the virus, she would use that information to argue that <PERSON> Farmer </PERSON>'s conduct is an aggravating factor that warrants a 10-year sentence. The standard sentencing range is between two years, seven months and three years, seven months. <PERSON> Iaria </PERSON> argued the test would violate a state law barring mandatory tests for the AIDS virus. However, <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON> said the law limits health officials, not judges. Joining <PERSON> Iaria </PERSON>'s attempt to block the order were the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> State Privacy Lobby.
