<FIRST>r a PM-LibelAppeal     06-02 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Libel Appeal,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Agrees Libel Suit Should Be Retried</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Reporters have an absolute right not to reveal confidential sources during legal proceedings, the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled in throwing out a $ 4.5 million libel judgment against The <ORGANIZATION> Philadelphia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inquirer </ORGANIZATION>. The unanimous opinion filed Tuesday lets stand a <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling that reaffirmed <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>'s Shield Law and reversed a 1983 verdict won by <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sprague </PERSON>, a lawyer and former first assistant district attorney in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> upheld the lower court's ruling that <PERSON> Sprague </PERSON>'s libel suit against the Inquirer be retried The suit involves several 1973 articles that reported allegations of Sprague participating in an illegal wiretapping scheme. Other articles raised questions about whether <PERSON> Sprague </PERSON>, as chief of the homicide division of the district attorney's office in 1963, extended preferential treatment to the son of former <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> Commissioner <PERSON> Rocco </PERSON> <PERSON> Urella </PERSON> <PERSON> Sr. </PERSON> in a homicide case. <PERSON> Sprague </PERSON> denied both sets of allegations. During a six-week trial in 1983, Common Pleas Judge <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lord </PERSON> ruled the jury had to disregard any evidence presented by the Inquirer based on confidential sources. Rather than divulge the reporters' sources, the newspapers' attorneys chose not to present the evidence The Shield Law, enacted in 1937, states that no reporter `` shall be required to disclose the source of any information procured or obtained by such person, in any legal proceeding, trial or investigation before any government unit.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled in 1986 that the Shield Law gave the newspaper the statutory right to withhold the identity of its sources, and ordered a new trial. Writing for the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, Chief Justice <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> N.C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nix </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> said the Shield Law's language `` is in no way ambiguous'' and agreed with the <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> that Lord had committed an error by barring the Inquirer's evidence. However, <PERSON> Nix </PERSON> differed with the <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>'s broad interpretation of the law, saying that just because evidence based on confidential sources is admitted does n't mean its reliability is guaranteed. `` The plaintiff is free to introduce rebuttal evidence and-or argue that the record does not disclose any evidence to support the reliability of the information,'' <PERSON> Nix </PERSON> wrote.
