<HEAD>US Viewers Get Look at Soviet Version of the Evening News</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 9th graf to delete reference to No-Doz, ``Vremya opened
xxx''
^By KATHRYN BAKER</NOTE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Greeting, comrades! Let's go to the videotape _ of the farm equipment? No, it's not the stuff that great <PERSON> Nielsen </PERSON> ratings are made of, but it's good enough to pull in 150 million viewers a night in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. `` Vremya,'' the Soviet news show, also picked up a few million <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> viewers this week thanks to The Discovery Channel, which ran it each night of the summit meeting between President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. The Discovery Channel, available on cable in about 32 million households, supplied a running translation with the newscast. The show, `` As They See It: Soviet Nightly News,'' was introduced by <PERSON> Hodding </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>. If American viewers were surprised by what they saw, quite possibly so were Soviets. Though stodgy farm equipment stories and use of still photographs instead of videotape illustrated a continuing lack of sophistication in Soviet television, there were segments of Monday night's edition of `` Vremya'' that suggested major changes in Soviet TV coverage since the advent of glasnost, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s policy of openness. For instance, there was a report on a meeting between President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and dissidents. The fact that it was reported at all was surprising, though it was described rather snidely by a commentator as not `` objective.'' He added, however, that the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> might learn something about human rights from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Other segments included coverage of <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s meeting with cute <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> schoolchildren who sang `` It's a Small World After All.'' The Soviet segment was hardly distinguishable from American coverage of similar events, suggesting fluff is the same the world over. `` Vremya'' opened with the biggest and seemingly dullest story of the day, the status of arms negotiations, described by a stylishly dressed anchorwoman in a droning official commentary. Much of the reporting on the Reagan-Gorbachev meetings was traditional: the co-anchors _ the man and woman do not acknowledge each other's existence _ read official communiques that included long lists of those present at official events. It hardly was exciting television, but important to Soviets who closely follow the rising and falling fortunes of various officials as indicated by their public appearances or disappearances. There was virtually no contribution from reporters on the scene, though there was videotape from a banquet the <ORGANIZATION> Gorbachevs </ORGANIZATION> threw for the <ORGANIZATION> Reagans </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> explained that much of the banquet coverage was cut because `` Vremya'' ran 35 minutes longer than its usual 40 minutes to include the speeches by <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> in their entirety. American viewers would long since have switched to `` Wheel of Fortune.'' But in the past, Soviet TV cameras were forbidden to show such scenes as the flower-decked tables at the <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> banquet. And a waiter could be seen carrying a bottle of wine, despite <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s policy of anti-alcoholism Before <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> came to power, the wives of Soviet leaders were rarely shown on television. But <PERSON> Raisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> was seen prominently sitting just in front of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> at the banquet, reading from the text of his speech as he delivered his remarks. A later segment treated her as an important Soviet official in her own right as she dedicated a statue symbolizing peace. While the Soviet and American leaders talked, so did <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Posner </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> anchor <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Brokaw </PERSON> for `` Vremya.'' It is a small world after all, because as every TV journalist, Soviet or American, knows, when you're stuck with what is basically a no-news event, what do you do? Interview each other.
