<HEAD>Police Say 36 People Murdered in Golden Temple</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police said today that Sikh extremists killed at least 36 people in the <ORGANIZATION> Golden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION> before it was besieged by police, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> reported. Many of the victims reportedly were tortured. Alos today, two more decomposed bodies were removed from the temple complex, raising to 16 the number of corpses found around the shrine since the radicals surrendered May 18, the <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> news agency reported. Police continue to maintain a cordon around the shrine at <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION> to prevent militants from returning. UNI quoted unidentified senior police sources as saying police were told of the killings by some of the 200 Sikh radicals and sympathizers who surrendered during the siege. Many of the victims were tortured before they were killed, <ORGANIZATION> UNI </ORGANIZATION> said. The extremists said the victims were beaten with iron rods and whips and that salt was rubbed into their wounds. Electric shocks also were used, <ORGANIZATION> UNI </ORGANIZATION> said. In some cases, the Sikh extremists extorted money from the victims' families on the false promise that they would be freed. The funds went to the <ORGANIZATION> Panthic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, one of a dozen Sikh extremist groups operating in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>, to buy arms and ammunition, the news agency said. There had been reports for months that people going into the shrine for worship were being kidnapped and held by militants in the complex, but the full extent of the problem did not come to light until after the police action. Most of the bodies have been found in a dump next to the Akal Takht, or the seat of temporal power of the Sikh faith. Militant Sikhs have been waging a guerrilla war for an independent homeland in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> since 1982. <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION> is the capital of <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>. The Sikhs, who make up less than 2 percent of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s 800 million people, claim they are discriminated against by <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s majority Hindus They form a majority in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>. The radicals have been blamed for killing more than 1,240 people in hit-and-run attacks in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> state this year. In 1987, 1,030 people died. The siege of the temple was launched May 9 after militants inside the complex fired on a police party outside its walls. At least 46 people were killed in fighting during the 10-day siege, most of them radicals.
