<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Asociated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Militant Sinhalese nationalists hurled bombs and grenades at voters and polling places during provincial elections today, killing a police officer, authorities said. Polls closed with less than half the eligible voters in two provinces casting ballots, election officials estimated. An opposition party immediately claimed fraud. The policeman was killed and six others wounded in two attacks on polling places in the village of <LOCATION> Mattugama </LOCATION>, 35 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>, police said. At <LOCATION> Dullewa </LOCATION>, 65 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>, gunmen jumped two policeman who had been watching a polling place. The assailants tied the officers to a tree and stole their automatic rifles but did not harm them, a police spokesman said. Late Wednesday, an airman was killed by suspected Sinhalese radicals who ambushed his car, the spokesman said on condition of anonymity. The deputy elections commissioner, <PERSON> Lakshman </PERSON> <PERSON> Perera </PERSON>, told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> that less than 50 percent of the 3.6 million eligible voters in the Central and Western provinces cast ballots. Results were not expected until Friday. The voting for provincial councils, in its second round today, was called for under last July's peace accord to end the 5-year-old revolt by militant Tamil separatists. The nationalist <ORGANIZATION> Sinhalese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> insists the accord makes too many concessions to the minority Tamils and opposes the councils, which are designed to give more autonomy to the provinces. Tamils dominate the Northern and Eastern provinces, where polling has been postponed because of fear of violence by Tamil separatists. Tamils, most of whom are Hindu, comprise 18 percent of this island nation's 16 million people. They claim discrimination by the mostly <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sinhalese </ORGANIZATION>, who make up 75 percent of the population. The rest are descendants of Christian colonialists or Moslem traders. On Wednesday, nationalist Sinhalese gangs burned down more than 15 government buildings, torched six buses and three trains and killed a policeman in a bid to disrupt today's balloting. They also put up posters threatening to kill anyone who voted and any shopkeepers who opened their stores for the next 36 hours. The government responded by tightening security and ordering security personnel to `` shoot on sight'' anyone `` engaged in the destruction of public property.'' The voters cast ballots today for 158 lawmakers from 585 candidates fielded by the governing <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Moslem </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>.
