<HEAD>Judge: Harvard Concealed Faculty Vote Switch in Discrimination
Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with attorney declining a
delay; PICKS UP 12th graf pvs, `At issue ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A lawyer for a former professor suing to become the fifth woman to receive tenure in <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>'s history pressed on with the trial today rather than accept a delay to gather more evidence <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Woodlock </PERSON> on Wednesday ruled that <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> withheld key documents in the sex-discrimination case, and he recommended suspending the non-jury trial so the attorney for <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Bund </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> could question professors who abruptly withdrew support for her tenure bid in 1981. `` My fundamental view is that cases should be decided on the merits and evidence worth submitting when possible,'' <PERSON> Woodlock </PERSON> said today. But the attorney, <PERSON> Evan </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON>, said today, `` We simply do n't have the emotional resources, let alone the financial resources, to embark on what we see as being an extremely complicated and lengthy procedure. Closing arguments then began in the trial, now in its eighth day. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> contends that she was denied tenure because of her sex and that less-qualified men than her received tenure. During testimony, a professor said the school's faculty voted 47-7 to support her bid for tenure but two days later backed her by only 29-27. Tenure decisions at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> are submitted to the faculty to gauge support for the professor; the actual decision rests with the university president. <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> had filed a motion seeking to sanction <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> for failing to provide evidence about the vote under a court order requiring that the university turn over all documents relating to <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. He asked the judge to bar <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> from using the second vote to prove its contention that <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> was denied tenure solely because her academic performance was below standard. But the judge denied the request today. Suspending the trial would have required testimony from professors who switched their votes and would have pushed the case well into the fall, attorneys for both sides said. <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> maintained that testimony by a <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> professor shows that business school Dean <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> McArthur </PERSON> lobbied the faculty to switch votes to oppose <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, who began teaching at the school in 1973. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> resigned in 1984 after she was denied tenure a second time, in 1983. At issue is the question of academic privilege, the right of a university to keep confidential the names of professors involved in judging candidates for tenure. In recommending suspending the trial, <PERSON> Woodlock </PERSON> said: `` It's a pattern of limitations placed on proof _ limitations by destruction, limitations by late disclosure ... and limitations on proof by this privilege.'' In her suit, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> also alleges the school destroyed documents requested by her to support her claim that less-qualified men received tenure from 1974 to 1984. <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> said the destruction was inadvertent. <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> attorney <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> indicated the school might risk being held in contempt of court and refuse to provide the names of the professors to preserve their academic privilege. The school claims that failing to provide the 1981 votes was an oversight and that <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> never specifically requested the results. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, 44, now a private marketing consultant, first applied for tenure in 1981. After failing to gain tenure, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> was given a three-year extension on her appointment. She submitted new academic work for review, but in 1983 was rebuffed again. She sued in 1984. Three of the business school's 90 tenured professors are women. Four women have received tenure in the business school's 80-year history, the first in 1961.
