<FIRST>r i AM-Summit-SovietPR     06-02 0548</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Summit-Soviet PR,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>For Gorbachev, Summit Was Public Relations Triumph</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MASHA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 If nothing else, the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> summit was a public relations triumph for <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. Although it produced little progress on arms control, the Reagan-Gorbachev summit showed the Soviets at their best under the intense scrutiny of 5,000 Soviet and foreign journalists who crowded central <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. Soviet officials were accessible and doggedly spontaneous. Ever-hovering <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> agents were usually young and well-dressed. Streets were swept clean and restaurants offered two <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> rarities: attentive service and fresh vegetables. Even the weather cooperated. It did n't start raining until President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> was ready to leave <LOCATION> Vnukovo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>. Veteran <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> observers said the Soviets, in style if not in substance, are increasingly emulating the West. One little-known reason why the new Soviet image appeals to Americans is that Soviet officials have frequently but quietly sought PR advice from Americans. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> image-makers responded with a variety of suggestions. They said security agents should wear lighter, less drab colors, and Soviet officials should favor open-collared shirts instead of ties and try to be more accessible. They also suggested that Soviet analysts establish eye contact because, as one public relations specialist explained, `` it connotes trust.'' `` The Soviets certainly do n't want to give Americans the credit, but there is no denying that some things went off very well because of both our input and their observance of us at the previous three summits,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kavulich </PERSON>, chairman of a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, marketing firm that has worked with the Soviets since 1986. `` Officials from <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> on down were n't running away from the television cameras, they were stepping up to them,'' <PERSON> Kavulich </PERSON> said. `` The Soviets usually carried off media events with a flair. And they reinforced the idea that they have a sense of humor.'' In a move clearly intended to appeal to Westerners, the official Soviet news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> sold summit T-shirts, buttons, records and tapes for foreign currency. It was the first time that <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> had lent its name to a commercial enterprise. Some observers suggested the Soviets might even have worked some magic with the weather, using chemicals to disperse rain clouds as they did in 1986 for the Goodwill Games and the 1985 opening of the World Youth Festival. There were some glitches. Hours after President and Mrs. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> arrived Sunday for the five-day summit, they took an unscheduled stroll along <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s pedestrian mall on Arbat Street. Soviet agents obviously were unprepared for presidential spontaneity. Forcing themselves between the Reagans and the Soviet crowd, the agents jostled the president and the startled first lady as well as journalists and passers-by. `` The Soviets knew the Reagans would have some spontaneous event to match <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s walk along <ORGANIZATION> Connecticut </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Avenue </ORGANIZATION>'' during the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> summit in December, <PERSON> Kavulich </PERSON> said. `` Agents on the street were told to let the president approach a crowd of Muscovites if he wants. But apparently, for the agents, acting as a wedge between Soviets and foreigners was almost a reflexive action,'' he said. Nevertheless, as one <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> diplomat said privately, `` The Soviets are probably patting themselves on the back. They went every night into homes throughout <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, and as each night passed, they became more familiar and more welcome guests.''
