<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Eli </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lilly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> has not closed the door to the use of its herbicide `` spike'' in a <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> program to spray <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> coca bushes, a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee chairman said today. Rep. <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> <PERSON> English </PERSON>, whose House Government Operations panel is reviewing the battle against illegal drugs, said he spoke to company representatives after the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> criticized the company during a hearing Wednesday. He said <PERSON> Lilly </PERSON> officials have objected to use of the chemical tebuthiuron, known as `` spike,'' because `` they have not done the proper testing of application by air over a wide section of countryside. They have no data. They have not seen data from -LRB- the -RRB- State -LRB- Department -RRB-, and can not assume responsibility or liability.'' <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> McKinney </PERSON>, a spokesman for the Indianapolis-based company, had no immediate comment on English's statement. But he did say that the chemical is applied both by air and on the ground in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. He described tebuthiuron as `` a broad-spectrum, soil-applied herbicide for brush and weed control on non-cropland, pasture and rangeland.'' The herbicide is `` approved for use in grazing lands, wildlife openings along ditchbanks, and utility rights of way. It is safe for humans, livestock, wildlife and the environment when used according to label directions.'' English, an <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> Democrat, said: `` We will continue discussions. We need to acquire a herbicide against coca bushes as quickly as possible. At this point, my own perception is the door is open, discussions will continue, and hopefully a solution can be found to this particular problem.'' English's statement was toned down considerably from his comment Wednesday that <PERSON> Lilly </PERSON> was `` a deserter'' in the war on drugs. The congressman later clarified his remarks to say there had not been proper aerial testing in the coca-producing region of <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>, where the chemical would be sprayed. He said the area has considerable groundwater and therefore is much different from the dry, brush areas where it is used in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. He added that the company also was concerned that the coca area in <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> `` may not be in friendly hands, and you may not have a pilot totally concentrating on the accuracy of spraying.'' At Wednesday's hearing, <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wrobleski </PERSON>, assistant secretary of state for international narcotics matters, criticized <PERSON> Lilly </PERSON> for deciding to withhold the herbicide from the spraying program _ even though it has been manufactured for more than 15 years, has been proven safe by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> standards, is widely available in this country and has been sold to the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Phyllis </PERSON> <PERSON> Oakley </PERSON> said Wednesday, `` We think the short-term impact is serious.'' The department wanted to test the chemical for use in eradicating the coca crop focused mainly in <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Huallaga </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, she said. The chemical is used in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> for clearing brush. Mrs. <PERSON> Oakley </PERSON> said <PERSON> Lilly </PERSON> apparently was worried about possible retaliatory measures by `` traffickers or terrorists.'' The company also came under pressure from environmentalists who were concerned about the ecological impact of the herbicide. Meanwhile, the subcommittee was told by agencies fighting the drug war on Wednesday that the effort is troubled by delayed equipment and financial woes. The <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> said its boats and planes often sit idle because the agency is short of money. The <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said the entire <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> border with <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> remains a haven for airborne drug smugglers because of delays in installing four of five radar balloons. Also, <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> surveillance planes have cracks in their wings and may be grounded this summer. New or modified planes authorized by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> have not yet been delivered. Construction of three new command, control, communications and intelligence centers for the drug war are behind schedule. English blamed the <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> for the delays in installing the radar balloons along the Mexican border to detect airborne drug smugglers. Only one of the five balloons, called aerostats, is in operation. `` This is a terrible failure,'' he told <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosenblatt </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> enforcement chief. `` You are costing us dearly. There's no sense of urgency about this. That's the problem.'' <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> Commandant <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Yost </PERSON> said his new, fast patrol boats and many of the agency's airplanes are operating at only 55 percent of last year's levels due to lack of money. He said it was ironic that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is ready to spend huge sums for an escalation of the military's role in the drug war, but ca n't find $ 60 million to get his vessels in the water and planes in the air full time `` Turn me loose and do n't give my mission away,'' he told the committee. <PERSON> Rosenblatt </PERSON> blamed the radar balloon delays on problems with site selection, environmental concerns, competitive bidding and bureaucratic roadblocks from other federal agencies. When he explained how he spent four months seeking competitive bids for the balloons in an effort to save money, English said, `` In effect, you cost us a heck of a lot of money'' because <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> AWACS surveillance planes have had to patrol the Mexican border to pick up the slack. English said that an AWACS costs $ 7,500 an hour to operate.
