<HEAD>National Park Managers Say Parks Better Than Ever</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs with morning session; PICKS UP 7th graf
pvs, `He noted ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TAD BARTIMUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAND TETON NATIONAL PARK, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> history professor with a passion for <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s national parks told their superintendents today they are stewards of the world's greatest university. `` I take the national park service of any society as a series of symbols about what a people chose to take pride in,'' <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Winks </PERSON> told 300 <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> managers on the second day of an extraordinary, four-day conference. `` These are the testimonials, the building blocks that <LOCATION> Americans </LOCATION> believe they have done historically. You begin to get into a heart of a people by viewing what they have chosen to preserve,'' said <PERSON> Winks </PERSON>, who has visited 315 of the 342 units of the National Park system and is a frequent participant in park service training sessions. `` Every superintendent in the National Park system is president of a small university, keeping the flame of an historical event of which we are proud,'' Winks said. `` You are stewards over what I view as the single greatest university of the world.'' On Wednesday, park managers at the first such conference in 12 years said <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s national parks are in better condition than ever. Superintendent <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Barbee </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> Director <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Penn </PERSON> <PERSON> Mott </PERSON> and others agreed that budget constraints have forced them to find new solutions to old problems, such as deteriorating maintenance and substandard housing. Environmental and citizens' groups have said threats to the parks include logging, oil drilling, pollution and commercial and residential development near parks. `` I get tired of all this ` Chicken Little' stuff,'' <PERSON> Barbee </PERSON> told reporters. `` We've made a lot of improvements. `` There is more control and management of the resources and some people do n't like that because they do n't like control, but the good side of that is ... we are more sensitive to the integrity of the resources than we have ever been,'' said <PERSON> Barbee </PERSON>, whose park, <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION>, was the world's first national park. `` I would contend that in Yellowstone -LRB- National Park -RRB-, biologically, today we are in better shape than we were 75 years ago,'' he said. He noted that 75 years ago a dairy herd, slaughterhouses, garbage dumps and other things needed to support staff and park visitors produced tons of pollution. `` As late as 1970, 80,000 pounds of wet garbage _ pizza crusts and slop _ was available to bears in open dumps. Now there are zero pounds of wet garbage, the dumps are gone, it's all hauled long distances out of the park,'' <PERSON> Barbee </PERSON> said. He said <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION>'s physical plant is also in better shape than it's ever been, even though an estimated $ 300 million is needed to repair deteroriated facilities. At Grand Canyon National Park, wild burros were once a problem, said Superintendent <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Marks </PERSON>. `` Today there are no burros in the park, the Big Horn sheep are making a comeback'' and conflicts between people on the ground and those making canyon overflights `` are being worked out,'' <PERSON> Marks </PERSON> said. During the far-ranging session with reporters, <PERSON> Mott </PERSON> denied accusations by critics in environmental groups and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> that he may have held back his best professional advice because of admininstrative opposition. `` No one, not even -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> -RRB- <PERSON> Hodel </PERSON>, has personally throttled me on what I personally feel,'' said <PERSON> Mott </PERSON>. The administration's commitment to the parks system was one of the issues discussed earlier in the day. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Horn </PERSON>, assistant secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> for Fish, Wildlife and <PERSON> Parks </PERSON>, said he was tired of `` a continuing drumbeat of critics claiming the administration is anti-park and committers of sins.'' He pointed out that the administration has proposed a $ 734 million operating budget for the <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> for the next fiscal year, compared to $ 391 million in 1980. `` That constitutes the largest operating budget in the history of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> and represents 29 percent post-inflation, real growth over the past seven years,'' <PERSON> Horn </PERSON> said. Further, the <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> employs 16,414 people, the highest level in its 72-year history, <PERSON> Horn </PERSON> said. `` These numbers bespeak a commitment to a first-class national park system,'' he said.
