<HEAD>New-Right Republicans Tell Bush: Attack Dukakis, Not Us</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Republican conservatives questioned Thursday what Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> hoped to gain politically by attacking two new-right activists whom he called `` self-appointed spokesmen'' who have been critical of him for years. The objects of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s attack _ <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Viguerie </PERSON> and <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON> _ said they still hope he defeats Democrat <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> in the fall presidential election. `` With <PERSON> George </PERSON> so far down in the polls I was wondering why he was wasting his time and energy shooting at me instead of shooting at <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>,'' said <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Caucus </ORGANIZATION>. `` If he wants to go around attacking conservatives, he's going to dig himself a deeper hole,'' said <PERSON> Viguerie </PERSON>, a conservative fund-raiser and former publisher of <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Digest </ORGANIZATION>. Recent national polls have said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is leading <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> by margins ranging from six points to 16 points among voters. Conservatives have urged the vice president to step up his attacks on the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor and portray him as a liberal out of step with the national mood. <PERSON> Viguerie </PERSON> and <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON> also have been sharply critical of President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> since he took office more than seven years ago. They have complained that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has abandoned much of the conservative agenda. Only Wednesday, <PERSON> Viguerie </PERSON> described <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> as having `` taken leave of his senses'' for suggesting in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> that the problems Soviet citizens were having emigrating to the West were caused more by bureaucratic problems than government policy. Interviewed by <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> at his summer home in <LOCATION> Kennebunkport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said of <PERSON> Viguerie </PERSON>, `` The fact that he does n't agree with me on a lot of things or has opposed me for many years, that does n't bother me. `` There's only one or two that polarize, and <PERSON> Viguerie </PERSON> and <PERSON> Howie </PERSON> <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON> are two of them. It does n't matter in terms of total vote.'' When asked if he needed to court the two new-right activists, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, `` There are some people that are almost self-appointed spokesmen that will make a claim for that. I do n't feel that at all.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said <PERSON> Viguerie </PERSON> `` gets his name in the paper by criticizing other Republicans all the time.'' `` I think it's kind of sad,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Dornan </PERSON> of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, a conservative supporter of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. `` I was hoping he would n't react to their earlier goading. ... I thought the whole thing was calmed down and we'd all be pulling together on one team.'' <PERSON> Dornan </PERSON> said <PERSON> Viguerie </PERSON> was `` absolutely correct'' in urging <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to get tougher on <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. `` If <PERSON> George </PERSON> does n't paint <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> as the liberal that he is and establish himself as a conservative then the electorate is going to opt for a change,'' said <PERSON> Dornan </PERSON>. `` It does n't serve <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> any useful purpose to attack people who have constituencies that might support him,'' said <PERSON> Lyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Nofziger </PERSON>, former <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> political director. At the same time, <PERSON> Nofziger </PERSON> noted that <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON> `` has been a vicious attacker of <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> over the last seven years.'' `` He's not running against <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Viguerie </PERSON> and he's not running against <PERSON> Howie </PERSON> <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON>; he's running against probably <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and you really ought to keep your eye on the ball,'' said <PERSON> Nofziger </PERSON>. <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON>, asked how much of a following he has, said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> `` does not have to worry about me, I only have one vote.'' He said <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Caucus </ORGANIZATION> has several hundred thousand supporters. `` Even though I'm not a great fan of the vice president or his policies, I genuinely hope he succeeds,'' said <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON>. `` I want all of us to unite behind him -LRB- <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> -RRB-,'' said <PERSON> Viguerie </PERSON>, who added that if <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> `` does n't run a polarizing election, he's history ... If he does n't run a campaign to polarize, that polarizes the country along liberal and conservative lines then he has no chance of winning.''
