<HEAD>Summit Produces `Sea Change in Atmospherics' For East-West Ties</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS pvs 20th (lasts) graf bgng, He said, to restore dropped
matter.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Image may have overwhelmed substance here this week, but <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> officials believe the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> summit will be remembered for building a foundation of openness and trust for future U.S.-Soviet relations. `` Military issues are the most important and here, progress was thin,'' said one American participant in five days of summit talks between President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. It was uncertain whether arms talks will result in agreement on a new treaty drastically reducing strategic nuclear weapons before <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> leaves office in January. That is the two leaders' condition for holding a fifth and final summit meeting this year. `` But there has been a sea change in atmospherics,'' the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official said privately. He noted that `` we are talking with them across the board'' from missile cutbacks to cultural exchanges. `` If we are going to build a future relationship, these will be the building blocks,'' he said. Another <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> diplomat with years of experience in <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> affairs said the Americans are `` feeling more confident about the relationship'' after the summit. He, too, spoke only on condition he not be identified. <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> spokesmen made their own upbeat assessment of glasnost-era summitry. `` If someone had told me three years ago that we would have such relations with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, I would have said it was a fantasy,'' said <PERSON> Georgy </PERSON> <PERSON> Arbatov </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S.A.-Canada </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Gennady </PERSON> <PERSON> Gerasimov </PERSON> said on a <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> interview that `` we do have progress, but we could have even more.'' To television viewers, the summit may have seemed designed to produce scenes of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> clasping hands and grinning at each other. There were some TV images unfavorable to the Soviets _ <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> agents roughing up the White House press corps a few hours after <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> arrived; police sealing off the apartment of a Jewish activist whom <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> intended to visit. There also were favorable Soviet images _ an aging <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> alongside a bright-eyed <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> more than 10 years his junior; <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> urging a faster pace in arms control negotiations while <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> counsels caution. Behind the images, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet aides were busy bargaining over a far wider range of issues than their predecessors during the days of East-West detente in the 1970s. `` We are finding greater openness than we have in the past,'' said the American official. Negotiators made only marginal progress this week on a proposed treaty to reduce <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet arsenals of long-range nuclear weapons by as much as 50 percent. They talked, too, about two lesser agreements that would tighten verification procedures under a 1974 accord limiting nuclear explosions and require advance notice of ballistic missile tests. The two sides also made little headway on resolving differences over <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and other regional conflicts. But they signed a handful of agreements on minor issues such as maritime rescue and radar navigation. In all the talks, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official said, the Soviets blamed past mistakes on `` old thinking'' and tried to use what they called <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s `` new thinking'' to make things work. Among the summit's little-noticed achievements, in the view of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> participants, was overcoming initial Soviet objections to a cultural agreement to exchange as many as 1,000 high school students from each country. `` In the past, the Soviets had objected to allowing Soviet students to stay in American homes and Americans to stay with Soviet families,'' said one <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official. He said the exchange students could become of the next generation of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet foreign policy experts.
</TEXT>
