<HEAD>Gorbachev's News Conference: Another Glasnost First</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> stood eyeball-to-eyeball this week with Soviet journalists who tested the uncharted bounds of glasnost, and he never blinked. Never had a <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> leader held a news conference on home territory until Wednesday, when <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> agreed to take questions from 300 Soviet and foreign reporters and government officials here for his summit talks with President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. The five Soviet journalists chosen to ask questions were polite and ideologically acceptable. But they raised issues that could never have been addressed publicly by Soviet citizens only three years ago. Articulate and in easy command of the occasion, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> deftly handled such sensitive topics as war losses in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, past Soviet stubbornness at arms negotiations and the need for a greater degree of democracy in Soviet society. By White House standards, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s news conference was windy _ it lasted two hours _ and disorganized. The order of the two dozen questions was more random than under the White House formula, which awards the first query to a wire service reporter at news conferences that seldom last longer than a half-hour. Soviet journalists are still committed advocates of official policy, but their reporting on the summit and the questions they asked <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> reflected a freer attitude. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> talked openly about the once-taboo subject of internal disputes within the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> leadership. He explained his problems with foot-dragging conservatives until Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> whispered that the Soviet journalist was asking about <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> factions that are hesitant about improving superpower relations. `` You mean you're talking not ab