<FIRST>r a AM-InfraredJoystick     06-02 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Infrared Joystick,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wireless Device Bound For Store Shelves</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY NEUMEISTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In the beginning, play was hard work. You ran, you wrestled, you clambered up cliffs with your bare hands. Then came video games. You walked over to the TV, picked up the joystick and let <PERSON> Donkey </PERSON> <PERSON> Kong </PERSON> climb the wall. Still too much work. Couch potatoes, rejoice! The wireless joystick, a device that will allow you to sit in your La-Z-Boy more than 20 feet from the tube while playing After Burner, is coming. `` It's really the ultimate stick,'' said <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Eisenberg </PERSON>, head of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> operations of <ORGANIZATION> Camerica </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, which will market the <ORGANIZATION> Freedom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stick </ORGANIZATION>. The arcade-style stick bounces an infrared beam around a room, linking up with a receiver at the television set. The manufacturer says the signal is not interrupted when someone walks by; there are no wires; it is compatible with all game systems; it works whether it is aimed at the ceiling, the floor, or up to 90 degrees from the screen. This is not the first time such a mechanism was marketed. A few years ago, a wireless joystick that used radio waves failed because the signal was easily disrupted, interrupting countless games of Pac Man. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Leung </PERSON>, associate professor at <ORGANIZATION> Simon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fraser </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, began developing the technology for the infrared joystick in 1981, said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Harding </PERSON>, president of <LOCATION> Camerica </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Leung </PERSON>'s research was proceeding apace when the video boom went bust. Instead of video games, people bought computers with video-game capabilities. But <PERSON> Harding </PERSON> said this has changed in the past year with the development of cheaper, more sophisticated video games. At the same time, parents found that computers were expensive playthings and game sets grew more attractive. The Freedom Stick will cost $ 69.95. <PERSON> Harding </PERSON> and <PERSON> Eisenberg </PERSON> said video-game makers are working to develop their own versions of the wireless device.
