<FIRST>u w AM-BirthControlPills 1stLd-Writethru   06-02 0828</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Birth Control Pills, 1st Ld-Writethru,790</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rash of Ovarian Cysts Leads Doctor To Suspect New Birth Control
Pills</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS grafs 2-3 pvs, bgng: Eventually, the, to CORRECT `bill'
to `pill'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 `` This absolutely blew my mind,'' Dr. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Caillouette </PERSON> said. `` I thought something awful was happening to me. Everytime I went into an examining room, I had a patient with ovarian cyst.'' Eventually, the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> gynecologist said, `` the lights began to go on'' and he concluded there was a connection between an outbreak of functional _ or non-cancerous _ cysts among his patients and a new type birth control pill he had been prescribing for them. Sold by three of the six major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> pharmaceutical companies that make birth control pills, the so-called multiphasic pills that went on the market in 1984 actually were not new chemical formulations, but rather new packaging of existing drugs in various strengths. Although <PERSON> Caillouette </PERSON> did n't have overall estimates of how many millions of women are taking the multiphasic pills, he said the introduction of the pills was accompanied by the most aggressive marketing program he has seen in 29 years of practice. By 1987, he said, nine of every 10 new birth control prescriptions were for a multiphasic. Largely through the efforts of <LOCATION> Caillouette </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> has ordered the three companies to intensify their post-market studies of the pills. The agency is airing the issue before an advisory committee on Friday. Specifically, the fertility and maternal health drugs advisory committee will be asked whether it believes `` it is possible to determine at the present time if monophasic and multiphasic formulations of oral contraceptives have different associations with the occurrence of functional ovarian cysts.'' The panel also will be asked whether it is willing to express a preference between monophasic and multiphasic pills. In a monophasic prescription, the same dosage is taken each day of the 21-day cycle. In a multiphasic, the dosage varies, with a woman taking perhaps 35 microgram pills on certain days of the month, 20 micograms on other days and 10 micograms on still others. The rationale given by drug companies for developing the multiphasic pills was to minimize any side-effects by providing the lowest total dosage possible over the one-month cycle. It has been presumed, based on studies, that birth control pills reduce the likelihood of functional ovarian cysts, rather than increase them. That is why <PERSON> Caillouette </PERSON> was so surprised when it dawned on him in early 1986 that each of seven patients who had developed cysts during the previous four months had been taking multiphasic pills. He recalled one patient in particular who had three operations in three months to remove the cysts `` and we kept putting her back on the triphasic pill beause she said with the others that she had breast tenderness, premenstrual syndrome and all of that.'' `` I believed what I was being told,'' <PERSON> Caillouette </PERSON> said in a recent interview. `` We knew that with patients on birth control pills, functional cysts were suppressed. After three surgeries in three months, the lights began to go on.'' So Caillouette put that patient and others with cysts back on single-dosage birth control pills. `` The cysts went away and I thought, ` This is what is supposed to happen,''' he said. `` But something is going on with these phasic pills.'' <PERSON> Caillouette </PERSON>, who also is a professor at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION>, decided to present his seven case studies during a <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> medical meeting `` and following my presentation, physicians got up from the audience and presented an additional 11 cases.'' He published his findings in a medical journal last summer and began getting still more calls and letters from other physicians and patients having similar experiences with multiphasic birth control pills. <PERSON> Caillouette </PERSON> said he now knows of 68 cases in which there is a potential link between multiphasic pills and functional cysts. <PERSON> Caillouette </PERSON> said he believes development of the multiphasic pills was a `` business decision on the part of the three companies to enter into new patent protection on birth control pills.'' But rather than develop new formulations, he said the companies either `` mixed or matched pills that were off the shelf'' or in some instances merely repackaged pills of varying strength into new monthly prescriptions. `` They came out with a new patent with what they advertised to the public as a new kind of birth control pill,'' he said. `` I think it was improper. I think they misled the public _ they misled the physicians into thinking they had a new mousetrap when in fact all they were doing was mixing and matching stuff that was off the shelf.'' Representatives for the three companies _ <ORGANIZATION> Ortho </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pharmaceutical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Wyeth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Syntex </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> _ all denied in separate telephone interviews any improprieties in winning approval of the multiphasic pills and said they were cooperating with the FDA-ordered reviews.
</TEXT>
