<SECOND>AM-Marijuana-Trauma,0402</SECOND>
<HEAD>One-Third of Trauma Victims Used Marijuana Before Injury</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than one-third of the patients at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maryland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trauma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> used marijuana several hours before sustaining their injuries, a study has found. Another third had been drinking alcohol before they were hurt, and 16.5 percent had been both drinking and smoking marijuana, according to the study appearing in the June issue of Archives of Surgery. `` To me, it was rather startling to see that an illicit drug matched in use a legal drug,'' said <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Soderstrom </PERSON>, a surgeon who headed the research team from the <ORGANIZATION> Maryland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Emergency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION>. `` The suggestion is that the use of this drug alone and in combination with alcohol may be the reason why they got hurt and ended up hurting someone else,'' <PERSON> Soderstrom </PERSON> said. The study, based on leftover blood samples collected from July 29, 1985, to May 8, 1986, provided a `` phenomenally high number of positives for marijuana,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cone </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Johns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hopkins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Addiction </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Francis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Scott </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Key </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. `` There's a common misconception that marijuana is a safe drug. But the statistics coming out of that study clearly show that people who are using marijuana are involved in accidents at a much higher rate than you would expect,'' <PERSON> Cone </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Soderstrom </PERSON> said more studies need to be done, since the marijuana use rate he detected was four to 10 times as great as the rate reported in previous studies of car crash victims in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Soderstrom </PERSON>'s study is based on blood samples from 1,023 patients treated at the shock-trauma center. About two thirds had been involved in car crashes, while the others suffered their injuries in falls, assaults and accidents. About 73 percent were men and 58.4 percent were 30 or younger. The results showed 34.7 percent of the patients tested had used marijuana and 33.5 percent were under the influence of alcohol. <PERSON> Soderstrom </PERSON> said that of 393 drivers admitted, 1 in 6 had both marijuana and alcohol in their systems. More than three-quarters of those who drank registered blood-alcohol levels equal to or higher than the 0.1 level commonly used to determine drunkenness. <PERSON> Soderstrom </PERSON> said blood sample testing, or radioimmunoassay, rarely registers positive levels more than four hours after use of marijuana.
