<TEXT>
 A proposed mandatory drug-testing program for airline workers prompted sharp criticism Thursday from airline labor unions, which argued there is no evidence of a problem in the industry to warrant it. The union officials were among witnesses who testified at a public hearing on a proposed <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> regulation that would require a broad range of drug tests, including random screening of tens of thousands of pilots, flight attendants and other airline employees. Representatives of airline management backed the regulations, as did administration officials. The drug-testing program `` is crucial in our effort to establish a drug-free aviation system,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Burnley </PERSON>, who conducted the hearing with <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> Administrator <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> McArtor </PERSON>. The proposed regulations call for pre-employment tests, post-accident tests, tests if drug use is suspected and a system of random tests of employees. <LOCATION> Burnley </LOCATION> and <PERSON> McArtor </PERSON> have repeatedly called for a drug-testing program in aviation and last year began random testing of <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> employees in a variety of safety-related jobs, including air traffic controllers. `` We are concerned ... that -LRB- the department -RRB- may ahve already decided on the main elements of this proposal'' especially random testing, said <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Woolfolk </PERSON>, representing the 40,000-member <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilots </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. He said the union is `` uncompromisingly opposed to random drug testing of pilots'' because no evidence has been shown that such tests are needed or that they will be able to identify the small number _ if any _ of drug users in the industry. `` To locate that one pilot, many thousands of tests would have to be given,'' <PERSON> Woolfolk </PERSON> said. `` ... Instead of eliminating drug abuse, -LRB- the mandatory testing -RRB- will merely spawn resentment, opposition and litigation.'' Capt. C.R. Paty of the <ORGANIZATION> Allied </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilots </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, which represents pilots at <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, complained that commercial aviators are being singled out while private pilots, in whom more of a drug problem has been documented, are not subject to the testing. `` Regulations are proposed to monitor our conduct, while pilots in the general aviation sector whose statistics reveal some measure of drug abuse, are left unregulated,'' <PERSON> Paty </PERSON> said in a written statement. Representatives of flight attendants unions also opposed the rule, as did groups representing private pilots and air taxi operators. Society's drug problem `` should be dealt with by reasonable, not intrusive means. Targeting specific, highly visible groups without cause is not reasonable,'' said <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Moreau </PERSON>, vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Flight </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Attendants </ORGANIZATION>. The pilot and flight attendant groups suggested that instead of mandatory random testing, the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> help the industry develop a voluntary detection and rehabilitation program for drug abuse similar to the program the industry for years has used to deal with alcoholism. But the drug-testing regulation received the endorsement of the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, the trade group for the major airlines. `` We support, as we have from the beginning, the goals of the proposed -LRB- testing -RRB- rule. ... The justification clearly must be the protection of public safety.'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Landry </PERSON>, the trade association's general counsel. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> plans to hold further hearings on the drug-testing rule in <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> on June 7 and <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> on June 9. A final rule is likely before the end of the year.
