<HEAD>House Vote Sends Bill to Senate for Final Approval</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The House today overwhelmingly approved and sent to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> a catastrophic health insurance bill designed to protect <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> beneficiaries from the financial devastation of a prolonged, acute illness. The bill, the most sweeping expansion of <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> in its 23-year history, includes the program's first-ever outpatient prescription drug benefit. Approval by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> is likely after its Memorial Day recess. Health and Human Services Secretary <PERSON> Otis </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowen </PERSON> has said he will recommend that President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> sign the legislation despite earlier administration misgivings that the bill is too broad. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> voted for the bill 328-72. Rep. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>, D-Ill., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, called the plan `` a good, reasonable and responsible agreement'' and said he expected approval by the president Under the legislation, the out-of-pocket deductible for doctor bills covered by <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> _ the amount paid by each recipient before government aid takes over all costs _ will wind up somewhere between $ 1,320 a year and $ 1,400. The hospital benefit is already set: full, 365 day-a-year coverage after a one-day deductible that rises along with average hospital costs. The 1988 deductible is $ 540. Once fully implemented in 1993, the new prescription drug benefit will pay 80 percent of those costs after a $ 655 deductible. By contrast, <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> now pays no more than 80 percent of doctor bills no matter how high they climb and only 60 days of full hospital coverage after a one-day deductible. The only prescription drugs now covered by <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> are a handful of particularly expensive ones such as anti-rejection medication for organ transplant patients. All of the additional benefits are to be paid for by additional charges to <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> enrollees. The charges will be a blend of flat monthly premium increases deducted from Social Security checks and an additional, sliding - scale supplemental premium charged the estimated 40 percent of the elderly to be subject to federal income taxes The additional flat premium will start at about $ 4 a month in 1989, climbing to $ 10.20 in 1993. The so-called supplemental premium, tantamount to an income tax surcharge, is expected to total an additional $ 22 a year for each $ 150 of income tax owed in 1989, climbing to an additional $ 42 a year on each $ 150 of tax liability by 1993.
</TEXT>
