ce. The violence occurred despite the deployment of an estimated 15,000 police and other security forces in the two districts. An Indian-sponsored peace accord called for the creation of the councils. The accord, signed July 29, called for the minority Tamils to end their five-year insurgency in exchange for more say in government. The Sinhalese front, outlawed after a failed 1971 coup, contends that the pact makes too many concessions to the Tamils and has vowed to block it. It has been blamed for killing more than 300 people since July. Tamils, who are mostly Hindus and compose 18 percent of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s 16 million population, claim they are discriminated against by the island's majority Sinhalese Buddhists. A Tamil rebel group, the <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tamil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eelam </ORGANIZATION>, rejected the accord. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> has sent more than 50,000 soldiers to the island to quell the Tamil rebellion. Four district councils were elected April 28. Another council will be selected next week in the south. Elections in the north and east have been delayed indefinitely because of the continuing Tamil insurgency.
