</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880602-0168 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 1717EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-AIDSCommission-Excerpts     06-02 0820</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS Commission-Excerpts,800</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-AIDS Commission Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here are major recommendations issued Thursday by retired <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>. Adm. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON>, chairman of the White House AIDS commission.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>INCIDENCE AND PREVALENCE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 States should begin to require reporting of HIV-positive antibody tests and should pass this information on to the Centers for Disease Control, without patient names. Terminology must be selected and used carefully to make the public more aware of the entire spectrum of HIV infection, from initial infection to seroconversion to full-blown AIDS. Extensive research should be conducted and results widely disseminated to provide more accurate information on the spread of HIV into the heterosexual population. Additional data on the progression rates from infection to disease to death are necessary.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>PATIENT CARE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Physicians should begin to more frequently utilize the HIV antibody test as a diagnostic tool, and incorporate the test and counseling into the normal range of services offered to patients. Funds should be made directly available to community-based organizations serving the needs of home-bound persons with AIDS, especially in the area of nutrition, psychosocial and direct care support.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>HEALTH CARE PROVIDERS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Health care profession schools should be given incentives to recruit medical students into specialties that are underrepresented but needed due to the HIV epidemic. The Department of Labor should move expeditiously, within one year, to develop a permanent and enforceable standard covering blood-borne diseases, with penalties for noncompliance, to protect health care and other workers whose jobs involve exposure to blood and blood-contaminated bodily fluids.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>RESEARCH, FDA</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Make the development of appropriate animal models for HIV-related research an immediate and high priority. Establish a federally supported computerized network of all HIV-related research activities to promote greater exchange of information and data between researchers. All approaches to vaccine development should continue to be explored and developed until one or more are successful. Standards for condom safety should be increased and studies should be conducted to determine the effects of spermicides, solvents and other lubricants on latex. Studies to determine the shelf life of latex condoms, with or without lubricants or spermicides, should be performed, and packaging dated accordingly.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>PREVENTION</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 States should adopt strong statutes that protect the confidentiality of a person's test results and that protect a person from discriminatory retaliation. All state and local health agencies should be adequately funded to develop HIV partner notification programs without diverting resources from other sexually transmitted disease partner notification programs. Quarantine or isolation of HIV-infected individuals based only on HIV status without consideration of an individual's behavior is not appropriate and should not be adopted by any state.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>EDUCATION</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Centers for Disease Control should conduct a 90-day study on the effectiveness of purchasing paid advertising, in addition to requesting advertising at no cost, to prevent misinformation about the HIV epidemic going to the general public. State boards of education should mandate that an AIDS education curriculum with appropriate content for age be offered to all students at each schooling level -LRB- e.g., elementary, middle and high school -RRB- throughout the state.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>SOCIETAL ISSUES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Abuse </ORGANIZATION>, in conjunction with state agencies, local drug abuse officials and representatives of drug treatment providers, should develop a plan for increasing the capacity of the drug treatment system so that the goal of treatment-on-demand can be met.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>THE WORKPLACE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Public and private employers should ensure that their workplace policies provide HIV-infected employees with the same rights and benefits offered other employees with other illnesses and disabilities.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>LEGAL AND ETHICAL</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Comprehensive federal anti-discrimination legislation which prohibits discrimination against persons with disabilities in the public and private sectors, including employment, housing, public accommodations and participation in government programs, should be enacted. Each school system should establish a board-developed policy, with accompanying guidelines, for dealing with an individual with HIV infection in the school before it is confronted with the first case. The commission recommends ... adoption of federal legislation that mandates that identifying information obtained by any provider, laboratory, payor or agency through HIV testing and counseling can not be disclosed without the written consent of the individual -LRB- except under certain specific circumstances. -RRB-
</TEXT>
<HEAD>THE FUTURE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> should enact legislation which expands the <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Emergencies </ORGANIZATION> provision of the Public Health Services Act to enhance the authority of the surgeon general when the president determines and declares public health emergencies in the nation. The surgeon general should sit as the principal spokesperson on the president's cabinet whenever issues related to the public health emergency are discussed. The surgeon general's office should be established as an independent entity within the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>. The surgeon general should construct the administration's budget requests for the public health emergency in consultation with the heads of all affected agencies and without clearance of the Office of Management and Budget before submission to the president.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
