<BYLINE>Party Official Calls For Publication of Khrushchev Speech on Stalin
^By BRIAN FRIEDMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> member on Thursday called for the publication of a `` secret speech'' <PERSON> Nikita </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON> gave in 1956 that detailed dictator <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s crimes against society. `` If the party is keeping secrets from Communists in the pages of its history that are not state secrets, then it is clear that it does n't serve the unity of the party,'' said <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rusakov </PERSON>, dean of the Philosophy and <ORGANIZATION> Scientific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communism </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Sverdlovsk </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>. The article by <PERSON> Rusakov </PERSON>, a teacher of Marxism-Leninism, was published in Thursday's editions of the Sovietskaya Kultura newspaper. It appeared to be the latest example in the leadership's campaign to open up the pages of Soviet history and break down the barriers erected by those who are clinging to the old policy of guarding and controlling all information <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON>'s address to the 20th Party Congress, held three years after the death of <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> in 1953, described the dictator's crimes in the 29 years he served as Soviet leader. About 20 million Soviets were killed in political purges carried out under <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> and in the drive to collectivize agriculture, according to estimates by Western historians. Under Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s policy of `` glasnost,'' or greater openness on selected topics, <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s crimes are no longer a taboo subject The name of <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON>, who was ousted as leader in 1964, is appearing more frequently in the press. The call by <PERSON> Rusakov </PERSON> to publish <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON>'s denunciation of <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> is not the first. In October, prominent Soviet scientist <PERSON> Vitaly </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldansky </PERSON> also said <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON>'s report, known in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> as his `` secret speech'' because it was delivered behind closed doors, should be published. The withholding of the information from Soviets was `` ridiculous,'' <PERSON> Rusakov </PERSON> said, since the text of the speech was leaked almost immediately in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>. `` All the world a long time ago read the ` secret' report by N.S. <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON> at the 20th Party Congress of the <ORGANIZATION> CPSU </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> -RRB-, but an overwhelming majority of Soviet Communists do n't know this document, which so radically changed the evaluation of the development of the party and the state,'' the educator wrote. He said the whole nation, not just party members, awaits the publication of <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON>'s report, as well as the documents of all party congresses, conferences and plenums. <PERSON> Rusakov </PERSON> said that was necessary for historical research, which he said was a part of glasnost. He said the documents should also be put before the public to overcome `` the stereotypes and myths which were created and indoctrinated into the consciousness of the people.'' He called for an accounting of how people were politically repressed and who was responsible. `` This is the sole means to avoid the gossip, rumors and ill-intended falsification of the internal life and history of the party,'' he said.
