<FIRST>r w AM-LostDies     06-02 0566</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lost Dies,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dies for Gold Coins Missing, Mint Admits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Dies used to strike the most valuable coin minted by the government are missing, a <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official acknowledged Thursday. The Secret Service is investigating the disappearance in January of 24 dies for the obverse, or front, of 1-ounce gold bullion Eagles, said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Mint. They were lost or stolen while en route between mints in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Point </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, he said. The Eagle has a face value of $ 50 but the sales price, currently $ 460 to $ 470, fluctuates with the price of spot gold. The dies, which are 5-inch-long cylinders the width of a coin, are worth about $ 40 each, <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said. He said the missing dies likely would be of little use to counterfeiters because all were for one side of the coin. But Rep. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Annunzio </PERSON>, D-Ill., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee that oversees the Mint, branded the loss _ the second such mishap in two years _ `` unpardonable. In the first incident, 44 dies used to strike the $ 1 <ORGANIZATION> Statue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberty </ORGANIZATION> commemorative coins disappeared in April 1986 on their way to the Royal Canadian Mint in <LOCATION> Ottawa </LOCATION>. Only one was ever recovered. It turned up last year in the possession of a Canadian coin dealer at a coin show in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. After the 1986 incident, the Mint began hiring armored cars for cross-border shipments but continued to use overnight mail services for delivery within the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Normally employees of the delivery service sign for the dies at each transfer point, but <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said a clerk at the <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Francisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mint </ORGANIZATION> apparently failed to complete a shipping form requiring that. `` They were shipped as ordinary freight, as if they were a crate of oranges,'' <PERSON> Annunzio </PERSON> said in a recent speech on the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> floor. `` Someone apparently figured out that a package going from one mint to another mint would be valuable.'' <PERSON> Annunzio </PERSON> said he would grill Mint officials on the subject at budget hearings conducted by his subcommittee later this year. `` I intend to find out why security for dies was so deliberately lax,'' he said. `` Losing dies once because of slack shipping procedures is inexcusable; losing dies a second time is unpardonable.'' <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said about 75,000 dies are shipped around the country each year. They are made in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> and sent to regional mints, depending on production schedules. Dies used to mint `` proof'' coins for collectors are sent to <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> for a special polishing process. Beginning in late April, the Mint began using armored cars for domestic, as well as cross-border shipments, he said. `` I think our record's pretty good. ... Obviously it was a mistake and we do n't like them to happen and we moved quickly to make sure it does n't happen again,'' he said. The clerk has not been disciplined, <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said, but `` We're working on that process right now. However, <PERSON> Annunzio </PERSON> noted that the change in shipping procedures came three months after the Eagle dies disappeared. `` The Mint's foot-dragging on switching to a secure method of shipping dies is inexplicable,'' he said in the floor speech, delivered May 25 and first reported in Thursday's editions of The Washington Post. `` Was the Mint trying to pinch pennies? ... Quite frankly I do not have the answers,'' he said.
</TEXT>
