<FIRST>u i AM-Summit-Allies     06-02 0604</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Summit-Allies,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shultz Briefs NATO, Allies Cheer Better East-West Relations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> allies Thursday that the failure to reach a strategic arms agreement at the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> summit was a blessing `` in a curious way'' because it allowed more attention to be focused on human rights and other issues. The allies, in turn, cheered what they called a broad improvement in East-West relations. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> met with European foreign ministers and other alliance officials for about two hours before flying to <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to join President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. He plans to leave Friday on a new mission to the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> to push his plan for <LOCATION> Arab-Israeli </LOCATION> peace talks. `` I certainly feel, and I believe all my fellow foreign ministers felt, the outcome was a very good one,'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said at a news conference. He said the two leaders had scored advances in numerous areas of arms control, including negotiations to ban chemical weapons, cut long-range nuclear missiles and reduce East-West conventional forces. <PERSON> Hans-Dietrich </PERSON> <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON>, the West German foreign minister, told reporters after meeting with <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> that his government was pleased with the summit results, despite the lack of a big breakthrough in arms control. `` We share his opinion that it was a successful and substantial summit,'' <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON> said. `` Through this summit the American-Soviet relationship got a new stability, a new perspective.'' Other alliance officials were equally upbeat. `` What is important is the judgment that <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> gave that the political climate of the meeting was a substantial success,'' Italian Foreign Minister <PERSON> Giulio </PERSON> <PERSON> Andreotti </PERSON> told reporters. <PERSON> Lord </PERSON> <PERSON> Carrington </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> secretary general, underscored the emphasis <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> put on human rights issues during the summit, as well as the progress reported in various areas of arms control. `` All these are elements of an increasingly stable relationship between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> which can only benefit the alliance,'' <PERSON> Carrington </PERSON> said. In his news conference, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> discounted <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s comment on Wednesday that the summit could have achieved more in arms control. `` Always it's possible to achieve more ... but it simply was n't possible to work through all of the difficult issues, and I think we all recognize that,'' he said <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said that absent a major arms control breakthrough, the superpowers were able to give more attention to three other main agenda items: human rights, bilateral relations and regional issues such as the Angolan civil war. He called this a blessing `` in a curious way.'' `` The absence of anything like that has caused people to reflect on what may be the more important meaning of what the president, the general secretary and others have managed to put together here,'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said. `` People can see more clearly than otherwise that the -LRB- superpower -RRB- relationship now proceeds on the basis of an established, four-part agenda.'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> declined to rule out a U.S.-Soviet agreement on 30 percent to 50 percent reductions in strategic, or long-range, nuclear weapons before <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> leaves office next January. The main stumbling block is Soviet objections to <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s Strategic Defense Initiative for developing a space-based defense against ballistic missiles. `` It's possible. We're going to work hard on it,'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said. Negotiations are scheduled to resume in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> on July 12. <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON> said he told <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> that the Europeans were particularly eager to see a strategic arms accord, since the Soviet long-range missiles can be targeted on <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> as well as <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> territory. <PERSON> Andreotti </PERSON> said <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> meeting that <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> had demonstrated at the summit a determination `` to want to conclude initiatives with this administration to the maximum extent possible.''
