<HEAD>British Government Loses `Spycatcher' Battle in Australia</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with three grafs to move up references to Thatcher's
campaign and press freedom. Pick up 3rd pvs, `The judges...' SUBS
7th pvs, `Prime Minister...' to conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s government Thursday lost a three-year court battle to block Australian publication of a former intelligence agent's memoirs. Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s expensive crusade against <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s `` Spycatcher'' had prompted protests that the government was infringing on freedom of the press <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>'s highest court, the seven-judge High Court in the capital of <LOCATION> Canberra </LOCATION>, ruled against <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> in its final bid to suppress the book. The judges accepted <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s contention that <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> was bound by a lifetime oath of silence about his 25 years with the MI5 counterespionage agency, but they said <LOCATION> Australian </LOCATION> courts had no jurisdiction to enforce a British security regulation. They unanimously rejected the British government's attempt to seize all profits from `` Spycatcher'' to prevent further publication of the book in <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>. About 240,000 copies of the book had been sold in <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> after lower courts ruled in <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s favor, and publishers <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Heinemann </PERSON> released 200,000 paperback copies immediately after Thursday's verdict. The judgment also releases nearly $ 3.6 million in royalties to the 73-year-old <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, who lives on a horse farm in <LOCATION> Tasmania </LOCATION> and is said to be in poor health. The publicity from Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s campaign against the book accounts for much of the book's stunning commercial success. More than 1.4 million copies have been sold in 40 countries, including the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, despite the government's continued ban in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>. The British taxpayer is left with an legal bill estimated at $ 3.6 million. In the Australian case alone, the government was ordered to pay an estimated $ 900,000 in legal costs. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s book, frequently smuggled into <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> by tourists and Britons returning from overseas, describes his 20-year career in the MI5 counterespionage service. It alleges that the security service eavesdropped on foreign embassies, burgled offices, stole documents, plotted assassination attempts and discussed how to bring down <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> government in the 1970s. Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s attempt to suppress the memoirs dates from September 1985 when an Australian court granted a temporary injunction against the book. The subsequent hearings prompted newspapers in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> to publish extracts of `` Spycatcher,'' and the government immediately clamped down, creating a confrontation over press freedom. The government maintains it has pursued the case to uphold the principle that former security officers are bound by a lifetime oath of silence about their work. To relax the rule, officials argue, would seriously undermine national security. Lawmaker <PERSON> Tam </PERSON> <PERSON> Dalyell </PERSON> of the opposition <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> said the government was squandering public money on its legal challenges. `` It was obvious to many lawyers and politicians many moons ago that this -LRB- Australian decision -RRB- would happen,'' <PERSON> Dalyell </PERSON> said. `` It was political obstinacy and stupidity on behalf of the government. ... The government must now abandon all other proceedings relating to this book around the world.'' The government still hopes to block `` Spycatcher'' in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, where it has banned the book and brought a half-dozen court cases to prevent newspapers from publishing extracts. On June 13, the nation's highest court, the five-judge Law Lords of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lords </ORGANIZATION>, is to decide whether to overturn a ban imposed on publication of extracts from `` Spycatcher'' in three newspapers, The Sunday Times, The Observer and The Guardian. Conservative <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Mates </PERSON> said the principle confidentiality on which the government based its case should be defended to the last. `` And I think the government has been entirely right to do that, difficult and embarrassing as it has been,'' he said in an interview with <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>.
