<HEAD>Life of Salvadoran President</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Duarte</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here is a partial chronology of the life and career of President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Napoleon </PERSON> <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON> of <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, who is being treated in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> for gastric cancer. Nov. 23, 1925: Born in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>. May 1948: Graduates as civil engineer from Notre Dame, South Bend, <LOCATION> Ind </LOCATION>. Aug. 14, 1949: Marries childhood friend <PERSON> Ines </PERSON> <PERSON> Duran </PERSON>. They eventually have six children. November 1960: Co-founder of <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. March 1964: Elected to first of three terms as mayor of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>. Feb. 20, 1972: As he is winning the presidential election, the vote count is stopped by the military. <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON> is arrested, severely beaten and expelled from the country. October 1979: Returns from exile after coup by reformist-minded military officers. March 3, 1980: Named member of third military-civilian junta, after two previous juntas disbanded amid discord. Dec. 13, 1980: Named president of fourth junta. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid _ cut off by <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> administration 10 days earlier because of human rights abuses _ is reinstated. March 25, 1984: Wins plurality in presidential elections. May 6, 1984: Wins presidential runoff against rightist candidate <PERSON> Roberto </PERSON> <PERSON> d'Aubuisson </PERSON>. June 1, 1984: Assumes presidency. Oct. 15, 1984: First round of peace talks with leftist rebels held in the northern town of <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Palma </LOCATION>. March 31, 1985: <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> win majority in legislative elections. Sept. 10, 1985: His daughter <PERSON> Ines </PERSON>, 35, is kidnapped by leftist guerrillas. Oct. 24, 1985: <PERSON> Ines </PERSON> <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON> and 23 kidnapped mayors are released in exchange for 22 rebels imprisoned by government and 100 wounded guerrillas given safe conduct out of country. June 1, 1986: Proposes fresh peace talks with rebels. Proposal accepted. Sept. 14, 1986: Travels to town of <LOCATION> Sesori </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> northeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> for talks with guerrillas. Rebels, saying government forces have militarized the town, refuse to attend. <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON> says insurgents do n't want peace. Oct. 10, 1986: Major earthquake devastates <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>. An estimated 1,500 people killed, scores of thousands left homeless. Oct. 14, 1987: During White House ceremony, <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON> leaves speakers platform to kiss <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> flag. Though applauded in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, he is criticized at home for subservient attitude. March 20, 1988: <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> defeated by rightist <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> in legislative and municipal elections. May 27: Government says he is suffering from bleeding ulcer, will go to <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> for treatment. May 31: <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON>, before leaving for <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, says his ailment is `` of a malignant nature.'' Delegates presidency to Vice President <PERSON> Rodolfo </PERSON> <PERSON> Castillo </PERSON> <PERSON> Claramount </PERSON>. June 1: <PERSON> Castillo </PERSON> confirms that <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON> has stomach and liver cancer. Calls him a `` man on the verge of death.'' June 2: <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON> vows to fight his cancer and urges countrymen to `` never lose the liberty they have now.''
