<HEAD>Federal Study Cites Need To Find Way To Evaluate Doctors,
Hospitals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Consumers lack adequate information to evaluate the quality of care from doctors and hospitals, according to a congressional study released Thursday. The study by the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assessment </ORGANIZATION>, prepared at the request of Rep. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Scheuer </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, said there now is no single source readily available to the consumer to evaluate the quality of care, and what little information is available is difficult to collect and understand. Such evaluations could be created, the report said, if congress would act to require the data to be collected and released to the public. `` We have all kinds of high-tech medical equipment now, but when it comes to information for consumers on the quality of medical care, we are still in the ice age,'' <PERSON> Scheuer </PERSON> said in releasing the report. `` What information is available is inadquate and frequently incomprehensible.'' <PERSON> Scheuer </PERSON> said he will conduct hearings to determine the best way to evaluate the qualilty of work by doctors and hospitals and then will push for a legislation requiring that this information be distributed to consumers. `` We're trying to develop a system to give consumers information that they need,'' he said. `` We know now that there are valid indicators to assess both hospitals and doctors.'' The <ORGANIZATION> OTA </ORGANIZATION> report said quality of care information could be used not only by individual consumers, but also by companies and labor unions that are selecting hospitals, physician groups and health maintenance organizations. Doctors could find the information on other doctors useful in deciding on referrals and in hiring staff physicians at hospitals or HMOs. For now, the report said consumers rely mostly on the suggestions and experiences of friends and families to select doctors and hospitals.
