<FIRST>u w AM-CompetitivenessIndex     06-02 0729</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Competitiveness Index,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study Says U.S. Living Standard Rises Slower Than in Other
Countries</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The standard of living of workers in other major countries has risen four times as fast as the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> standard of living in the past 15 years, according to a new study on American competitiveness released Thursday. The report, prepared by the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Competitiveness </ORGANIZATION>, concluded that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> had lost ground not only in terms of living standards, but also in the related areas of international trade, productivity and investment. `` In an increasingly global economy, others are either fast gaining on us or have surpassed <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> in the areas that will determine future competitive success,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Porter </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> economics professor who served as a consultant on the study. `` If we continue along the path we've been on since 1972, we could lose the competitiveness battle altogether.'' The council is a coalition of executives from industry, organized labor and higher education who got together in 1986 to help American companies compete more effectively in world markets. The new report is certain to heighten the debate in the presidential campaign over whether the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is becoming a second-rate economic power. Critics of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration policies point to the country's status as the world's largest debtor nation to highlight their contention that a string of record trade deficits during the 1980s shows that <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> has lost the ability to compete internationally. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration has dismissed such concerns, contending that the country's trade deficits have begun to improve and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is currently enjoying the longest peacetime expansion on record. But the council's report argued that the administration's position neglects long-term economic trends that paint a more distressing picture `` We would hope that both presidential candidates will have strong programs to propose in this area,'' <PERSON> Porter </PERSON> said. `` This will give the <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> people a benchmark with which to grade the quality of each candidate's proposals.'' The council presented what it called a `` competitiveness index,'' which it said measured <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s performance against its competitors in global markets. The report said in all four areas it surveyed, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> had lost ground compared with the world's six other large industrial democracies _ <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. These nations and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> meet annually for economic summits, including an upcoming session this month in <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION>. Among the report's conclusions: _ Since 1972, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> standard of living has grown only one-fourth as fast as the average standard of living of the other summit countries When compared with <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s two biggest competitors, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, the difference is even more striking. American workers' standard of living has risen only one-half as fast as the average West German and only one-seventh as fast as the average Japanese. Because of these developments, the council's standard of living index dropped to 78.9, which is 21.1 points below its 1972 level of 100. Traditional measures of the standard of living focus on total output divided by the population. However, the council said it divided output by the number of workers to reflect the fact that more and more American families find they must have two incomes to keep up financially. The council's living standard also included the country's trade deficit on the grounds that this represented money borrowed from foreigners that would eventually have to be paid back. _ Despite the boom in <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> export sales last year, <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s share of world exports stood at 10 percent last year, below the 12 percent share the country had in This pushed the trade index down to 82.6 percent of its 1972 base. This was still an improvement from 1986, when the index fell to 74.5, before the weaker dollar began to boost <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> export sales. _ Productivity, the output per worker, showed the most lost ground The council's measure for productivity dropped to 68.7 percent of its 1972 base. Since 1972, manufacturing productivity in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> has increased eight times faster than in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, while average productivity growth in the six summit countries has been more than four times as fast as in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. _ Long-term <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> investment, including spending for research and development, capital equipment and education, came out best in the ranking at 96.2, down only 3.8 percent from the 1972 level
</TEXT>
