<HEAD>Soviet Plant Apparently Discharging Radioactive Clouds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Swedish monitors said Thursday they have detected radiation indicating that a nuclear power plant in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> routinely discharges clouds of radioactive particles. `` The levels are still harmless, but they illustrate a poorer security thinking than we have in <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Lars-Erik </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Geer </PERSON> of the defense research agency FOA. He said a study of wind directions and radiation levels at different monitoring stations pointed to the <LOCATION> Ignalina </LOCATION> plant in <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION> as the source of the radiation. He said the plant 400 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Stockholm </LOCATION> has made four large discharges of radioactive particles every year since it started operations at the end of 1983. Each discharge from <LOCATION> Ignalina </LOCATION> contains 10,000 times more radioactive material than a Swedish nuclear plant discharges over an entire year, he said. `` The guideline in <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> is to discharge as little as possible,'' <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Geer </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. `` We pointed it out to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> nuclear authorities in 1986, but they denied such discharges were made at Ignalina.'' <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> has been on higher alert against radioactivity since the 1986 accident at the <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION> plant, 720 miles southeast of here, sent clouds of contamination over vast areas of northern <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>. The world's worst nuclear accident killed at least 31 people near the plant.
