<HEAD>Gannett Chairman Says Castro, Botha Mistreated By U.S. Reporters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Neuharth </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said Thursday that world leaders such as <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Fidel </PERSON> <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> have been mistreated by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> reporters whom many heads of state now view as the new ugly Americans. <PERSON> Neuharth </PERSON>, answering questions after a speech at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>, said that although he has no sympathy with Cuban communism or with South African racism, leaders such as <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> and <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> have a legitimate complaint. `` <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> and <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> have been mistreated by the press'' because reporters have not let them be heard fairly, he said. All world leaders `` have the right to present their point of view without some reporter, especially a reporter from this country, acting like judge and jury, confronting and convicting and then spreading news of that conviction,'' said the 64-year-old chairman and founder of the internationally circulated newspaper <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Today </ORGANIZATION>. Since February, <PERSON> Neuharth </PERSON> has visited 19 countries and interviewed 15 heads of state in the newspaper's `` JetCapade'' reporting venture. <PERSON> Neuharth </PERSON>, who is midway in the tour with members of his staff who fly aboard a private jetliner, said he believes he has gained access to a wide variety of world leaders, including <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> and <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>, because his newspaper is `` informational rather than confrontational.'' `` In the eyes of some