<BYLINE>By HANK LOWENKRON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Martha </PERSON> <PERSON> Chappel </PERSON>'s sole surviving son has just graduated from high school even though he suffers from the congenital illness that killed his three brothers, becoming the first of her children to live long enough to reach that goal. `` God has not given me children to keep forever,'' she said Thursday. `` He gave them to me to love and care for, they are a loan.'' <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, 18, graduated this week from <ORGANIZATION> Cold </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Spring </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, a public school for mentally and physically handicapped children. One son, <PERSON> Adrian </PERSON>, died when he was 5 in 1976, followed by <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> in 1979 at 15 and <PERSON> Ernie </PERSON> in 1981 at 18. The cause each time was a rare, inherited disorder known as <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON>'s syndrome, which causes mental retardation and physical abnormalities. There is no cure or therapy for the disease, which strikes only males and can cause dwarfism, deafness, heart defects and arthritic joint pain. `` He knew all his brothers and that they died in the hospital and he becomes very upset when we go to a hospital,'' said Mrs. <PERSON> Chappel </PERSON>. The life expectancy of children with <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON>'s is 15 years. <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> is a dwarf and is moderately retarded and deaf in one ear. `` This boy has been so close to death you could almost see it, but he's so strong,'' said his stepfather, <PERSON> Waller </PERSON> <PERSON> Chappel </PERSON>. Mrs. <PERSON> Chappel </PERSON> did n't know her first two boys had Hunter's until after the third, <PERSON> Willie </PERSON>, was born. `` In the beginning, it was like a shock to me. I cried for days,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Chappel </PERSON> said. `` I kept thinking I'll have a girl and I'll tell her not to have children. I've always wanted a lot of kids. That's been my goal since I was little.'' `` There have been times when I've been frustrated, but whenever things got rough I had friends and relatives to help me over the hump,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Chappel </PERSON> said. Because of the disease, <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> has a small esophagus and difficulty breathing. He tires easily and can walk only about a half block at a time. `` For the last six or seven months we've been spending about $ 500-to - $ 600 a month for his medical expenses We have to have oxygen and had to get a wheelchair. We've had to struggle, but the time with <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> and the other boys has been worth it,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Chappel </PERSON> said. The graduation was `` one of the highlights of my life,'' said Mrs. <PERSON> Chappel </PERSON>. `` He's the first to live long enough to accomplish it.'' She hopes to enroll <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> in a day adult program for the handicapped so he can continue associating with other youngsters. `` He knew something exciting was going on -LRB- at the graduation -RRB-, all the people and receiving a certificate. He knew there was some sort of special conglomeration taking place. But, I think he'll be kind of sad when he learns what it means, that he wo n't be seeing the teachers and children every day,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Chappel </PERSON> said. `` He's always looked forward to the bus rides to school.
