<HEAD>Quake Shakes Greek Island</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A strong earthquake shook the western island of Cephalonia Thursday for the third time in two weeks but there were no reports of damage or injuries, police said. The <ORGANIZATION> Athens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seismological </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> said the tremor measured 5 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale. Its epicenter was in the Ionian seabed off <LOCATION> Cephalonia </LOCATION>, about 195 miles from <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION>. `` We felt the tremor around lunchtime but people did n't bother to leave their homes and there were no damage reports,'' said a police officer on Cephalonia, speaking on condition of anoymity. Tremors measuring 5.8 and 5.3 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale shook the island on May 18 and May 21 but caused no damage. Buildings on Cephalonia have been constructed to withstand tremors of 7 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale ever since the Ionian islands off western <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> were hit by a devastating quake in 1953. The <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale is a measure of the energy released by an earthquake as measured by the ground motion recorded on a seismograph. Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase in magnitude. A quake measuring 5 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> quake can cause considerable damage and quake measuring 6 can cause severe damage.
