<HEAD>Third Test in Three Weeks at Nevada Site</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MACY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> conducted its third nuclear test in less than three weeks Thursday, just hours after the conclusion of the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> summit. Nuclear testing was one of the issues addressed in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> formally agreeing to monitor each other's tests this summer in joint verification experiments. The test shook the <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> desert and registered on seismic equipment atop hotels and casinos here, 110 miles from ground zero. The blast measured 5.3 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale of ground motion at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Earthquake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Golden </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION>. Soviet scientists who are setting up monitoring equipment at the <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> Test Site were at Mercury, <LOCATION> Nev. </LOCATION>, 52 miles from ground zero, at the time of Thursday's blast The Soviet scientists also were on hand for two previous tests, May 13 and May 21. The test was the fifth announced blast this year, and the 680th announced test since the program moved to the <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> desert in January 1951. The nuclear device was buried 2,000 feet beneath the surface of <LOCATION> Pahute </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mesa </LOCATION>, a rocky patch of desert in the far northwest corner of the 1,350-square-mile test site. The blast had an explosive force of up to 150 kilotons. The atomic bomb that destroyed <LOCATION> Hiroshima </LOCATION> had an explosive yield of 13 kilotons. All tests are listed as less than 20 kilotons or 20 to 150 kilotons, with advance notice given for tests at or near the upper limits. Such a notice was issued Tuesday. The force of the blast produced a gentle swaying motion at the Regency Towers high-rise condominiums in <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION>, according to <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Yoerg </PERSON>. `` Everything appears normal,'' Ms. <PERSON> Yoerg </PERSON> said as she monitored the blast from a control point 31 miles from ground zero. `` Nothing is coming out of the ground.'' The success of underground tests is measured, in part, by the ability to prevent radiation from leaking into the atmosphere. Ms. <PERSON> Yoerg </PERSON> said she did not feel any ground motion at the control point. DOE personnel monitoring such blasts often experience a rocking motion following detonation. DOE seismic equipment atop the Golden Nugget and Mint hotels in downtown <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION> and the El Rancho Hotel on the <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> recorded the blast `` distinctly,'' according to Ms. <PERSON> Yoerg </PERSON>. A similar reading was obtained at Scotty's Castle in <LOCATION> Death </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, 60 miles from ground zero.
