<HEAD>Unacceptably High Radon Levels Found at AF Academy, Colorado Base</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday a new program of testing its bases for the natural radioactive gas radon had turned up two facilities inside the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and three outside with unacceptably high readings. Both of the bases inside the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> are located near <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION> _ the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Peterson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION>. One of the three bases outside the country is <ORGANIZATION> Andersen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> on the island of Guam. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> said it would not identify the other two overseas bases until it had notified the host country's government. The service said in a statement it was launching a more extensive radon survey of all habitable structures and preparing to take `` quick corrective action'' at the academy and <PERSON> Peterson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Andersen </PERSON> bases because of radon readings above the level of 20 picoCuries per liter of air. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> considers radon levels of four picoCuries or less per liter of air acceptable,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> said. `` For a level of radon -LRB- above 20 picoCuries -RRB-, the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> recommends that corrective action be taken within several months.'' The service said that at 49 other bases around the world, it had discovered one or more structures with radon levels between four and 20 picoCuries per liter. In those cases, every habitable building at the bases will be screened for the next year to determine which ones need repair work to reduce radon levels below the four picoCurie standard. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> said 33 of those 49 bases were located in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The other 16 are located in foreign countries and will be publicly identified `` in the near future following notification of host countries.'' All told, the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> said it had taken 4,404 air samples at 135 major bases and found 211, or 4.8 percent, at a level above four picoCuries. `` The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> has found levels above four picoCuries per liter in 14 percent to 20 percent of the houses they have tested nationwide,'' it added. The service declined to speculate on why the radon levels at the two <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> facilities and on <LOCATION> Guam </LOCATION> were unacceptably high. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> became the first of the military services last December to launch a test program for radon. The Army has since followed suit and the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> are considering such a move. Radon is a colorless, odorless natural product of decaying uranium in the soil. Medical research has indicated that exposure to high levels of radon over extended periods may increase the risk of lung cancer. `` Results of commercial testing in communities throughout the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, coupled with concern about the health of <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> members and their families, prompted the decision to test,'' the service said last year in announcing the program. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> has said it will launch a `` mitigation program'' for those buildings where radon levels exceed the recommended <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> standards, sealing foundation cracks or installing new ventilation systems. The service estimated last year it would spend up to $ 2.6 million on the testing and up to $ 30 million on repair work. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday it now appeared those figures would be overstated, but added it did not have new estimates available.
