<HEAD>Boeing Spokesman Says Company Would Oppose Mandatory Airplane
Retirement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commercial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airplanes </ORGANIZATION> would oppose any effort to set a mandatory retirement age for jetliners even though such a requirement could boost sales of new planes, a company spokesman said Thursday. `` It would be arbitrary and we do n't think it would be necessary,'' <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Gamble </PERSON>, a spokesman for the Seattle-based aerospace company, said during a break in a <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration-sponsored </ORGANIZATION> conference on aging aircraft. On Wednesday, <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> Administrator <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> McArtor </PERSON> raised the possibility of mandatory airplane retirement. But Gamble said <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> and other aircraft manufacturers have found nothing to suggest that jetliners ca n't fly safely for years if they are properly maintained. `` We could be selfish and say it would be good for us,'' <PERSON> Gamble </PERSON> said of mandatory aircraft retirement. `` But it is good equipment.'' `` Mandatory retirement just would n't make any sense,'' he said. The average age of the world airline fleet has increased from eight years in 1980 to nearly 12 years in 1988, said Gamble. By 2005 the average age of jetliners is expected to be 15 years. <PERSON> Gamble </PERSON> said that <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION>'s commercial planes are built to provide at least 20 years of `` economical'' service. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> called the three-day conference as a result of increased concern about the safety of older jetliners since the in-flight breakup of a 19-year-old <ORGANIZATION> Aloha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737 in April. A 20-foot section of the plane tore away and a flight attendant was swept to her death, although pilots were able to land the aircraft safely. Gamble said that even before the <LOCATION> Aloha </LOCATION> incident there was increasing industry interest in aging plans and that <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> began looking at the problems as early as 1983. Since January 1987, <PERSON> Gamble </PERSON> said, <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> has been conducting an informal survey of 50 of its older planes owned by 33 airlines in 19 countries. `` There have been no surprises,'' he said of a preliminary analysis of the survey. In addition, <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> recently put a 737 it purchased from <ORGANIZATION> Piedmont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> after an accident through an extensive series of tests that simulated more than 200,000 takeoffs and landings. `` We did n't find anything unexpected,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Gamble </ORGANIZATION>, adding that some small cracks were found in the airplane after the test, but they were easily fixed. The Aloha plane involved in the recent accident had undergone about 90,000 landings and takeoffs.
