<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has nominated Brig. Gen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> McDonough </PERSON> to become the next chief of chaplains for the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> and Col. <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Goodwin </PERSON> to become the next chief of the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nurse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday. Assuming <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> confirmation, <PERSON> McDonough </PERSON> will be promoted to the two-star rank of major general and <PERSON> Goodwin </PERSON> to the one-star rank of brigadier general. <PERSON> McDonough </PERSON>, 60, is a native of <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> who is serving as the deputy chief of chaplains. <PERSON> Goodwin </PERSON>, 49, is a native of <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> who is the assistant for nursing services at the <ORGANIZATION> Military </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlift </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday the president also had nominated Col. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Harlin </PERSON> for promotion to brigadier general and a new assignment as the replacement for <PERSON> McDonough </PERSON> in the post of deputy chief of chaplains. <PERSON> Harlin </PERSON>, 52, is a native of <LOCATION> Flushing </LOCATION>, N.Y.
