<HEAD>14 Share Honors As High School Class Valedictorian</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELLEFONTAINE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It's crowded at the top, at least at <ORGANIZATION> Bellefontaine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>. When diplomas are passed out Sunday to 185 seniors, the school will honor 14 valedictorians, each of whom managed a perfect 4.0 grade point average. `` It makes us look like we're grading on a very easy kind of basis. But these are the same standards that we've always had. This is an extremely unusual group of kids who just happen to be in the same class,'' said <PERSON> Principal </PERSON> <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>. <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> said the 14 valedictorians had shown their academic prowess on college admission and scholarship tests as well as in class. They earned more than $ 52,000 in scholarships, and three of them are National Merit Scholarship winners. Average ACT college exam scores for the 14 seniors was 28.6, placing them at the 95-plus percentile of all students taking the exam across the nation. <PERSON> Tammy </PERSON> <PERSON> Watson </PERSON>, class secretary and one of the valedictorians, credits the harmony of the class for its scholastic achievement. `` I think the strength of our class is achieving what we want through a tremendous unity,'' <PERSON> Watson </PERSON> said. `` We work together and help each other to reach higher goals.'' But valedictorian <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Hendershod </PERSON> said she believes competition was critical. `` The fact that there were 13 other candidates helped to motivate us. We would say to ourselves, ` I'm not gon na allow that other person to get it and leave me out. If that person can get it, I can too,' `` she said.
