<HEAD>Italian Journalist Returns Home From Afghan Jail</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: INSERTS 1 graf after 4th `Asked to' with further quotes.
PICKS up 5th pvs bgng, The journalist... </NOTE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An Italian journalist who was jailed in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> for 6 -LCB- months on espionage charges returned home Thursday and said he was whipped after being caught entering <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> with insurgents. <PERSON> Fausto </PERSON> <PERSON> Biloslavo </PERSON>, 26, told reporters he spent three or four months in jail near the Afghan capital of <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> before receiving the first of two letters from his family. <PERSON> Biloslavo </PERSON>, who looked weary but healthy, said he would describe his time in captivity at a news conference on Friday. Asked to confirm news reports that he was whipped after his arrest in November, the journalist said: `` Yes, it happened when I was first taken prisoner about 100 kilometers -LRB- 60 miles -RRB- from <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>.'' `` They put a gun to my head, made me put my hands on my head and an officer whipped me,'' <PERSON> Biloslavo </PERSON> said, then added: `` I will continue to work in this profession, and I will ask for a visa to return to <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>.'' The journalist smiled broadly when he stepped off a special private plane at <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Ciampino </LOCATION> airport after a flight from <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Biloslavo </PERSON>, who worked for the tiny Trieste-based Albatross news agency, was greeted by his mother <PERSON> Grazia </PERSON> who hugged and kissed him. A crowd of well-wishers, including former Socialist Premier <PERSON> Bettino </PERSON> <PERSON> Craxi </PERSON>, welcomed the journalist when he got off the Falcon 50 aircraft. Also present was <PERSON> Bruno </PERSON> <PERSON> Bottai </PERSON>, secretary general of the <LOCATION> Italian </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>, who had delivered a plea for clemency to Afghan President <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> from Italian President <PERSON> Francesco </PERSON> <PERSON> Cossiga </PERSON>. The request was granted on Wednesday. `` I want to thank President <PERSON> Cossiga </PERSON> and Mr. <PERSON> Bottai </PERSON>, who literally came to pull me out of the prison,'' said <PERSON> Biloslavo </PERSON>, who was wearing a blue T-shirt, gray jeans and sneakers. <PERSON> Biloslavo </PERSON> was arrested Nov. 14 while traveling with Moslem guerrillas battling the Soviet-backed Afghan government. He was convicted in March of espionage and sentenced to seven years in prison. He shared a jail cell with <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> free-lance photographer <PERSON> Alain </PERSON> <PERSON> Guillo </PERSON>, who was freed last week after an appeal from <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bilislavo </PERSON> left <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> early Thursday in the company of an <LOCATION> Italian </LOCATION> delegation headed by <PERSON> Bottai </PERSON>. Bilislavo and Guillo were held at <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Pul-I-Charki </LOCATION> prison after being found guilty of spying. Both men denied the charges.
