<HEAD>US Cruiser Watches Iranians Board, Escort Cypriot Vessel</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 8th graf ``There was...'' with one graf to fix typo.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The most powerful <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> warship in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> stood by on Thursday when <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s navy stopped, boarded and escorted away a Cypriot freighter apparently suspected of carrying war-related cargo for <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> officials said the guided missile cruiser <LOCATION> Vincennes </LOCATION> was two miles away and did not get an appeal for aid that could have caused the first direct confrontation with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> since April 18. Six Iranian vessels were knocked out that day, including two sister ships of the frigate involved in Thursday's incident. It also was the closest brush since the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> adopted a new policy allowing <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> ships to intervene in attacks on neutral commercial ships flying flags of other nations. The rule requires a victim to be a non-belligerent in international waters that requests assistance. Lt. Cmdr. <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Dyke </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, said the Iranian ship was tentatively identified as the 1,540-ton frigate <LOCATION> Alborz </LOCATION> and acted within maritime law that allows for `` visit and search'' in international waters. It halted the Cypriot motor vessel <LOCATION> Vevey </LOCATION> in the southern gulf at about 9:30 a.m. <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Dyke </PERSON> said the Cypriot ship `` did not request assistance and did not appear to be in any distress.'' He said the 9,400-ton <LOCATION> Vincennes </LOCATION> remained two miles away and had no radio exchanges with either vessel. `` The <LOCATION> Vincennes </LOCATION> had the others in view as the Iranian frigate stopped the <LOCATION> Cypriot </LOCATION> ship, launched a small boat that put a search party on board and then escorted her off in a northeasterly direction,'' <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Dyke </PERSON> said. There was `` no communication between the merchant and the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> warship'' and no indication the <LOCATION> Vevey </LOCATION> tried to make contact during the incident 25 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Dubai </LOCATION>, he said. <ORGANIZATION> Lloyd </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shipping </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unit </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> said eight Iranian naval personnel boarded the 10,000-ton freighter and it was taken to the Iranian port and naval base at <PERSON> Bandar </PERSON> <PERSON> Abbas </PERSON> in the Strait of <LOCATION> Hormuz </LOCATION>. Its listed cargo was Italian marble chips and powder, bound for <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>, the report said. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> considers <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> to be allies of <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, with which <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s regime has been at war since September 1980. Most commercial ships it has attacked were traveling to or from those countries. Iranian gunboats regularly stop and search merchant vessels to search for war-related cargo that could be bound for <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> Vincennes </LOCATION>, based in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>, arrived in the gulf last weekend on the first assignment to the gulf of an Aegis-type cruiser, equipped with advanced long range radar surveillance and missile systems. Three other <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> warships left the gulf Thursday home ports on the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>. The missile cruiser <PERSON> Wainwright </PERSON> and missile frigates <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> and <PERSON> Simpson </PERSON> all played prominent roles in `` Operation Praying Mantis'' April 18. Staying behind in a <LOCATION> Dubai </LOCATION> drydock is the missile frigate <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON>, which struck a mine April 14. That incident led to the retaliation four days later. The Iranian frigate involved in Thursday's incident was one of two believed operational after the April 18 encounters. The frigate Sahand was sunk by American bombs and missiles and the fourth, <PERSON> Sabalan </PERSON>, was severely damaged.
