<HEAD>Jumbo Jet Aborts Takeoff, Captain Praised for Precautionary
Measure</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout with pilot aborting takeoff because he thought a
just-landed plane was still on the runway, although FAA says jet
was on taxiway. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> DC-10 aborted its takeoff at <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> Thursday because the pilot thought a just-landed jet had not cleared the runway, officials said. The DC-10's tires automatically deflated but no one was hurt when <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> Flight 43 to <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION>, carrying 148 passengers and about 15 crewmembers, came to a stop, said airline spokesman <PERSON> Ned </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> said the pilot felt a <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION> jet had n't adequately cleared the runway, but <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Elly </PERSON> <PERSON> Brekke </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> plane was off the runway and had come to a stop on a taxiway Ms. <PERSON> Brekke </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> pilot `` took the extra margin of safety'' in the 9:55 a.m. incident. Passengers deplaned on a taxiway but did not use emergency exits or equipment. Neither Walker nor Ms. <PERSON> Brekke </PERSON> knew how far into the takeoff the airliner had gotten before the abort, but the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman said the jet had reached at least 100 knots, or 115 mph. They did not know the actual distance between the planes. `` Captain did a good job in reacting quickly when he saw the other aircraft,'' said <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>, who would not release the names of the crew. Ms. <PERSON> Brekke </PERSON> initially reported that four of the DC-10's tires blew after the abort, but later she and <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> explained that the tires have a safety plug that melts when heated to a certain temperature, letting the tires deflate rather than explode.
