<HEAD>With AM-Air Force-Radon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The following is a list of the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> bases in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> at which one or more readings for radon gas were found to exceed the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>'s recommended standard of 4 picocuries per liter or air Any reading above 20 picocuries per liter is considered sufficient to trigger detailed 30-day and one-year testing of all habitable structures at a base and immediate repair work. Any reading of 4 to 20 picocuries per liter triggers a one-year detailed sampling of all habitable structures, followed by repair work as required. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday that sampling at five bases had produced readings above 20 picocuries per liter, while sampling at 49 bases had produced readings of 4 to 20 picocuries. Of the bases with readings above 20 picocuries, three of the bases are in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> or a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> territory and two are in foreign countries. Of those with readings of 4 to 20 picocuries, 33 bases are in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and 16 in foreign countries. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> said it would not identify any of the bases overseas until the host country's government is notified, the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> said.
