<FIRST>r a AM-ComputerCo-pilot     06-02 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Computer Co-pilot,0540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Artificial Intelligence in the Cockpit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MARIETTA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It would n't have the lovable personality of R2D2, but an artificial intelligence system being developed for the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> would perform many of its tasks, including alerting a pilot to key points in an air battle. The `` pilot's associate'' program, a version of which was demonstrated Thursday at <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, was initiated by the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> because of the proliferation of high-speed, high-tech weapons and aircraft systems, said Maj. <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Der </PERSON> <PERSON> Weert </PERSON>, director of the program. Today's pilot is inundated with information about his plane, other planes, radar installations hoping to hit him with surface-to-air missiles and other threats. `` In the heat of battle, there's a tendency to get overloaded with everything that's taking place,'' said <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Der </PERSON> <PERSON> Weert </PERSON>, a graduate of the <ORGANIZATION> Flight </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weapons </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> version of the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Top Gun'' school. <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aircraft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, working independently under <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> contracts, hope to take advantage of advances in artificial intelligence to produce a computer that would focus the pilot's attention on the most critical decisions while handling lower priority matters itself, like the vacuum cleaner-shaped sidekick of `` Star Wars'' hero <PERSON> Luke </PERSON> <PERSON> Skywalker </PERSON>. For example, in a Central European battle scenario demonstrated Thursday, the `` pilot's associate'' copes with an overheating radar system while the pilot is firing missiles at an enemy bomber. All the while, the computer is giving the pilot a display of the missile ranges of the most threatening enemy fighters. Major new threats prompt the computer to talk aloud _ <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION>'s model, in fact, sounds like a woman with a Southern accent The ability to pick out the biggest threats is made possible by artificial intelligence. The computer considers the pilot's planned flight path and the capabilities and behavior of enemy aircraft and draws conclusions. It may suggest avoiding some planes or attacking them, depending on the orders for each mission. And instead of merely telling the pilot that fuel has been lost, the computer would indicate whether the plane has enough to carry out the original mission and suggest a new flight path if necessary. That flight path would take into account the delicate task of weaving among enemy ground radars to prevent them from gaining a good enough fix to launch a missile. <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Der </PERSON> <PERSON> Weert </PERSON> said that would replace educated guesswork by the pilot. But <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Der </PERSON> <PERSON> Weert </PERSON> emphasized the `` pilot's associate'' would replace neither the pilot nor, on two-seat planes, the navigator. The pilot could overrule any action proposed by the computer, in some cases simply by ignoring it. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Broadwell </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION>'s program manager, noted that the computer would adjust to the pilot's rejection, going to work on new proposals consistent with the pilot's decisions As smart as the new system is, it must overcome the `` notoriously slow'' characteristics of artificial intelligence computers, said <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> program manager <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Barnette </PERSON>. The 30-minute simulated flight replayed on video monitors for reporters Thursday actually took nearly three hours for the system to process, but <PERSON> Broadwell </PERSON> said that meets the goal for this point in the system's development.
</TEXT>
