<HEAD>Education Department's Research Budget Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Education Department's budget for research and development fell by 33 percent after inflation between 1980 and 1987, the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday. At the same time, the federal government's overall spending on research and development rose 24 percent, the agency said in a report to a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> education subcommittee. But most of the growth was in the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> budget, where R & amp; D expenditures shot up 81 percent during the 1980s, the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said. The Education Department spent $ 132 million on research and development in 1980 and $ 124 million in 1987. The latter figure, taking inflation into account, was the equivalent of $ 88 million in 1980 dollars, the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said. Defense expenditures on R & amp; D rose from $ 13.9 billion to $ 36.1 billion. The 1987 figure was the equivalent of $ 25.2 billion in 1980 dollars. The government's overall R & amp; D spending rose from $ 31.7 billion in 1980 to $ 56.1 billion in 1987, or in terms of 1980 dollars, to $ 39.4 billion, the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said. Such departments and agencies as <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> registered real increases, but <ORGANIZATION> R </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; D spending fell at the departments of Agriculture -LRB- down 2 percent -RRB-, <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- down 16 percent -RRB-, Energy -LRB- down 29 percent -RRB-, <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- down 35 percent -RRB-, and <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- down 39 percent -RRB- as well as the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- down 47 percent -RRB-. The report said that <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistics </ORGANIZATION> has experienced a cut of 34 percent in constant dollars since 1980 and more than 50 percent since 1978. The report was prepared at the request of Rep. <PERSON> Major </PERSON> <PERSON> Owens </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on select education.
