<HEAD>Pilot Program Finds And Helps Homeless Vets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YAKIMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Clare </PERSON> <PERSON> Brower </PERSON> remembers finding a veteran with frostbitten feet living in a <LOCATION> Yakima </LOCATION> garbage can last winter. He was treated at a hospital and is now working. Then there was the drunken 54-year-old Korean War veteran in <LOCATION> Walla </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Walla </LOCATION> who had n't held a steady job since 1953. When he sobered up, doctors found he was a schizophrenic. Or the former <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> typist with psychiatric problems who'd been living on the streets since her discharge in 1982. The three are among thousands of homeless, mentally ill veterans located and helped under a two-year, $ 10 million pilot program launched in 43 communities around the nation by the <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> last year. About 240 of those people have been located by the <LOCATION> Yakima </LOCATION> office, the only one in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Brower </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> veteran who runs the office. `` The reason they're homeless is the same reason as anyone else, for alcohol and substance abuse,'' he said recently. Causes could be anything from pre-existing mental illness to delayed stress syndrome brought on by war experiences, he said. `` The single male in general has fallen though the cracks in all health projects in the past,'' <PERSON> Brower </PERSON> said. `` You send a single male to -LRB- social agencies -RRB-, and unless they're disabled they tell him to go to unemployment and find work. `` What he needs is food in the belly and a place to stay,'' he said. So <PERSON> Brower </PERSON> searches the alleys, the rescue missions, the drunk tanks, under bridges, old rail cars and other collecting grounds for the homeless and mentally ill. Those who are veterans are steered into a variety of VA and community programs Non-veterans are referred only to community programs, <PERSON> Brower </PERSON> said. `` A lot of veterans are eligible for benefits that other homeless may not be,'' said <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Walla </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Walla </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> hospital. Among the programs are medical care, housing and welfare assistance, education programs and job training. In the first seven months of the pilot program, there were contacts with about 10,000 veterans nationwide, said <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>, of the <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> Of the 7,800 veterans who received formal assessments of their cases, 86 percent showed symptoms of mental illness, he said. `` A lot of studies indicated a significant portion of the homeless population are veterans and a significant number of them may be emotionally disturbed,'' <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> said. `` I do n't think we've gotten all of them,'' he said. The goal is to get them back on their feet. `` If a veteran is willing to work, I can get him a job now,'' <PERSON> Brower </PERSON> said. `` No ifs, ands or buts.'' The homeless vet with the frostbitten feet, who had been stationed in <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> during the 1960s, was found to have a drug problem, was hospitalized and is now working, <PERSON> Brower </PERSON> said. The 31-year old former <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> typist is hospitalized wih multiple psychiatric problems, which may have been aggravated by her service stint, <PERSON> Brower </PERSON> said. The vet suffering from schizophrenia qualified for some back pay, and has moved to <LOCATION> Tacoma </LOCATION> for treatment at a veterans hospital. <PERSON> Brower </PERSON>, 44, who served in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> in 1968-69, said 90 percent of the homeless vets suffer alcohol or drug problems, which can be a self-medication for delayed stress syndrome. `` To get rid of nightmares and flashbacks, the greatest medicine is alcohol, and it's readily available,'' <PERSON> Brower </PERSON> said.
