 Two groups announced Thursday they are filing suit to force the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> to disclose information about a program using librarians to monitor suspicious library users. A spokesman for one of the groups, the liberal People for the American Way, said the suit follows unsuccessful attempts to get information about the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>'s Library Awareness Program through the Freedom of Information Act. <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kropp </PERSON>, president of People for the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Way </ORGANIZATION>, said the suit was being filed by his group and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Archive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> in </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` We believe that information is the currency of democracy,'' said <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> reporter who now heads the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Archive </ORGANIZATION>. `` Therefore, anything that constrains the flow of this valuable information damages the liquidity of the marketplace of ideas and thus damages democracy itself.'' The <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> contends the program is an essential counterintelligence effort. In a report released last month, the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> said Soviet intelligence agents seeking sensitive technological information are among the most enthusiastic users of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> libraries. But <PERSON> Kropp </PERSON> maintained that the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> uses techniques of intimidation to enlist library officials. <PERSON> Kropp </PERSON