<HEAD>House Approves NASA Authorization Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> gave overwhelming approval Thursday to an $ 11.5 billion <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> authorization bill that includes nearly $ 1 billion for the start on a space station but nothing for a free-flying, unmanned, factory in space. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> is not likely to go along with authorizing anything near that amount. Some senators have expressed an inclination to vote for no more than $ 10.2 billion for the fiscal year that begins Oct. 1, an amount that could kill the space station project. For the first time, the House authorization bill puts a cap of $ 24.2 billion on the total cost of the space station, which is planned to be in orbit around <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> and occupied by astronauts at the end of 1996. A year before that it would be available for periodic visits by astronauts. Also, for the first time, the bill authorizes spending for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> for three years _ $ 11.5 billion in 1989, $ 14.4 billion in 1990 and $ 15.7 billion in 1991. The amount for 1989 is what President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> asked for and represents an increase of 29 percent over the $ 8.9 billion authorized for this year. The vote was 360 to 26. The bill authorizes no funds for the mini-space station that would be carried into orbit by the space shuttle, then leased by <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> from its developers for $ 700 million over five years. It allows the space agency to request proposals for such a facility but specifically bans the awarding of any contracts, except for studies by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. Under the House bill, a 12-member `` <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mars </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>'' would be established to prepare a detailed proposal for a joint manned mission to <LOCATION> Mars </LOCATION> with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. Development of the <ORGANIZATION> Advanced </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Satellite </ORGANIZATION>, which is opposed by the <ORGANIZATION> Reagan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, is authorized by the bill. And the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> calls for a flight demonstration for a hypersonic space plane _ one capable of flying at least five times the speed of sound _ by 1995.
