<HEAD>Major Colombian Drug Figure Gets 60 Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Colombian cocaine dealer whose arrest prosecutors called second only to drug kingpin <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON> <PERSON> Rivas </PERSON>' in importance was sentenced to 60 years in prison Thursday. <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Auli </PERSON> <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON> <PERSON> Chacon </PERSON>, 38, ran a Bogota-based drug trafficking ring that smuggled $ 32.5 million worth of cocaine to cities across the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, according to his indictment. He was snared in a sting federal agents had dubbed Operation Pisces. `` We do n't usually catch people of your caliber,'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Lenore </PERSON> <PERSON> Nesbitt </PERSON> said as she imposed the 60-year sentence for one count of operating a continuing criminal enterprise. <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON> pleaded guilty to the charge in a plea bargain, escaping the maximum life sentence possible under the law. But <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosenthal </PERSON>, said his client probably would spend the rest of his life behind bars `` The 60-year sentence is a functional life term,'' said <PERSON> Rosenthal </PERSON>. `` He has to serve at least 40 years without parole.'' <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON> was indicted in the Drug Enforcement Administration money-laundering sting Operation Pisces, along with top <ORGANIZATION> Medellin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cartel </ORGANIZATION> figures <PERSON> Pablo </PERSON> <PERSON> Emilio </PERSON> <PERSON> Escobar </PERSON> <PERSON> Gaviria </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jorge </PERSON> <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Ochoa </PERSON> <PERSON> Vasquez </PERSON>, who have escaped custody. <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON> apparently kept his operation separate from the cartel's, but special <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> prosecutor <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilkinson </PERSON> said he was sec