<HEAD>Some Miners Survived Explosion But Suffocated in Shaft</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with more quotes, official
changes number of bodies brought out to 11. PICKS up 5th `Fourteen
of'; INSERTS 3 grafs after 11th `He said' with detail. PICKS up
12th `Stefan Walscher' and EDITS last graf `About 170' to conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BORKEN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Some of the 57 men killed in the Stolzenbach coal mine survived a devastating gas explosion but suffocated when their emergency masks ran out of oxygen, officials said Thursday. Among the dead was an 18-year-old who was on his first shift as a miner when the explosion occurred Wednesday afternoon in what an official described as `` one of the most modern and best-equipped lignite coal mines around.'' The young man had `` graduated from school last Friday and wanted to earn some money before continuing his education,'' Mayor <PERSON> Bernd </PERSON> <PERSON> Hessler </PERSON> told reporters. <PERSON> Hessler </PERSON> would not give the young man's name, honoring the family's wishes Rescue workers brought the first 11 bodies to the surface Thursday afternoon and took them to a temporary mortuary in metal caskets. <PERSON> Gottfried </PERSON> <PERSON> Milde </PERSON>, <PERSON> Hesse </PERSON> state interior minister, said 36 bodies had been found and the others were scattered over a wide area underground. <PERSON> Milde </PERSON> said earlier Thursday that 12 bodies had been taken from the mine, but changed the number after talking with rescue workers. Fourteen of the dead miners were Turkish immigrants. Families and friends _ Germans and Turks together _ clung to each other at the mine 70 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>, eyes red and swollen from tears and lack of sleep. Around them, men with with grim faces black with coal dust and soot moved to and from the mine intent on retrieving all the bodies. `` My son <PERSON> Dieter </PERSON> is down there. He's been a miner for 20 years,'' said <PERSON> Werner </PERSON> <PERSON> Henke </PERSON>, who waited at his son's house. `` God, let him be alive. He has two small children.'' <PERSON> Wulf </PERSON> <PERSON> Boettcher </PERSON>, a state mining official, said: `` The chances of finding any survivors have sunk to zero.'' Rescue workers broke through tons of debris and battled rising water in the effort to retrieve the bodies of all 57 victims of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s worst mining accident since 1962. `` Some of the dead were found with their miners' breathing masks on,'' said <PERSON> Erwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Braun </PERSON>, head of the Hesse state mining board. `` That means they survived the blast and apparently ran out of air.'' He said the emergency masks had about three hours of oxygen, but <PERSON> Boettcher </PERSON> put the time at about 45 minutes. <PERSON> Braun </PERSON> said the explosion was caused by a buildup of methane gas. A report on the <ORGANIZATION> ZDF </ORGANIZATION> television network said investigators were speculating that a short-circuit from a power tool may have started a chain reaction of explosions inside the mine. <PERSON> Braun </PERSON> said that was possible, because `` coal dust can become dangerous if it gets mixed with methane gas and there is suddenly a spark.'' About Stolzenbach, he said: `` This is one of the most modern and best-equipped lignite coal mines around and it has been inspected many times, including recently.'' <PERSON> Stefan </PERSON> <PERSON> Walscher </PERSON>, the local prosecutor investigating the disaster, told reporters it could be several days before all the bodies are located and brought out. `` The water is rising in several places, hampering the attempts to get the bodies out,'' he said, and workers were pumping fresh air into the mine to minimize the risk of another gas explosion. <PERSON> Braun </PERSON> said the danger of another methane buildup persisted and `` Rescue work is being hindered by heavy damage. ... Teams can proceed only with oxygen masks.'' <PERSON> Braun </PERSON> said carbon monoxide levels inside the mine had receded, but still were severe. <PERSON> Milde </PERSON> said officials planned Roman Catholic, Lutheran and Moslem religious services at a local school where the bodies were to be taken and where relatives assembled earlier Thursday. Turkish consulate representatives also were at the scene. They said state officials had confirmed that the total number of Turkish victims was 14. Some of those killed will be taken back to <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> for burial, they added. Wednesday's explosion blew the roofs off at least three buildings at the mine, knocked down sheds and shattered windows and sent debris flying that seriously injured eight miners on the surface. The mine is in a field, with the nearest homes about 500 yards away. The explosion was the worst mining accident in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> since February 1962, when 299 miners were killed at <LOCATION> Voelklingen </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Saarland </LOCATION> state. About 170 people have been employed in the <LOCATION> Stolzenbach </LOCATION> mine, which is owned by <ORGANIZATION> Preussen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elektra </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Hanover </LOCATION>, one of the largest West German utility companies.
