<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> dropped `` The Slap Maxwell Story'' after its star, <PERSON> Dabney </PERSON> <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON>, and producer and creator, <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Tarses </PERSON>, refused to continue working together, the president of <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Entertainment </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday. `` We never really had an opportunity to renew the show or cancel it,'' <PERSON> Brandon </PERSON> <PERSON> Stoddard </PERSON> said at an informal meeting with newsmen in his office. `` The way it was presented to us was that if <PERSON> Dabney </PERSON> continued with the show, <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> would n't do it. And if <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> stayed with the show, <PERSON> Dabney </PERSON> would n't do it. It just went its way.'' <PERSON> Stoddard </PERSON> said he did not know what caused the conflict between <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Tarses </PERSON>, neither of whom was available for comment. <PERSON> Tarses </PERSON> was in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON> was working on a movie for <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> called `` Sooner or Later.'' The show, with <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON> as an acerbic sports writer, did poorly in the ratings and had particular trouble reaching women viewers. <PERSON> Stoddard </PERSON> said he felt it was essentially a variation of `` Buffalo Bill,'' which <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Tarses </PERSON> did for <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> several years ago. `` We felt the show had problems with women,'' said <PERSON> Stoddard </PERSON>. `` They had trouble caring about that character. But <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> runs his show, very clearly. We talked to him and made suggestions, but he does what he wants to do.'' <PERSON> Tarses </PERSON> was also the creator and producer of `` Days and Nights of <PERSON> Molly </PERSON> <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON>,'' which was canceled by <ORGANIZATION