<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The chief minister of <LOCATION> Malacca </LOCATION> state spoke Thursday of plans to salvage a fortune in precious gems, jewelry and artifacts from a Portuguese treasure ship that sank in the Straits of <LOCATION> Malacca </LOCATION> in 1512. The national news agency <ORGANIZATION> Bernama </ORGANIZATION> quoted Chief Minister <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> <PERSON> Rahim </PERSON> <PERSON> Thamby </PERSON> <PERSON> Chik </PERSON> as saying talks between the state and the federal government `` will be carried out as soon as possible to enable salvage operations -LRB- to begin -RRB- and to recover the treasures.'' <PERSON> Rahim </PERSON> said the wreckage of the Flora de la Mar was discovered in the Straits of <LOCATION> Malacca </LOCATION> near <LOCATION> Indonesian </LOCATION> waters by a salvage team which conducted a three-year study of the sinking, the agency reported. History records indicate the Flora de la Mar was used to ferry treasures seized after the Portuguese conquered <LOCATION> Malacca </LOCATION> in 1511. The ship was on its way to <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Malacca </LOCATION> when it struck a coral reef during a storm and capsized in January 1512. <PERSON> Rahim </PERSON> was quoted as saying that several precious items were believed to have been saved by Portuguese naval commander <PERSON> Alfonso </PERSON> <PERSON> D'Albuquerque </PERSON>, who was aboard the <LOCATION> Flora </LOCATION> de la Mar when it sank and was rescued by another ship. The items _ including a gold sword, rubies, gold bangles and a gold ring _ were gifts of the King of <LOCATION> Siam </LOCATION> to King <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> and Queen <PERSON> Donna </PERSON> <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Rahim </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Bernama </ORGANIZATION> quoted <PERSON> Rahim </PERSON> as telling the agency in an interview in <LOCATION> Malacca </LOCATION>, 72 miles south of <LOCATION> Kuala </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lump