<FIRST>r a AM-TransplantBias     06-02 0610</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Transplant Bias,0628</SECOND>
<HEAD>Disparity in Kidney Transplant Rates Found, Report Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH SHOGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 White men suffering from kidney failure are more likely to get a kidney transplant than are women or minorities, a new study says, but an transplant expert says that the statistical differences are n't the result of bias on the part of doctors. A study in the June issue of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Archives </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION> showed 31 percent of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> men who had undergone long-term dialysis received a transplant, compared with 21 percent of the women Among minority patients, 20 percent received a transplant after long-term dialysis compared with 30 percent of white patients, said the report, based on national statistics dating to 1983. Dr. <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kjellstrand </PERSON> said the imbalance his report found does not prove `` actual bias.'' `` However, the most favored recipient of a transplant is similar to the physicians who make the final decision: a young, white man,'' said <PERSON> Kjellstrand </PERSON>, a Swedish doctor who spent several years doing research in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. In certain age groups, the difference in transplant rates between races or sexes was even greater than the 3-to-2 ratio found overall. Minority long-term dialysis patients age 21 to 45 were half as likely to undergo the surgery as white patients of the same age and sex. And women of any race age 46 to 60 were less than half as likely to receiving a donor kidney as men of the same race and age, according to the report. Dr. <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunsicker </PERSON>, former president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transplant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Physicians </ORGANIZATION>, said that for various reasons, white men are more likely to seek transplants. A recent change in the method used to allocate donor kidneys to people on waiting lists, ordered by the government, ensures against bias based on age, sex or race, he said. But women and non-whites who have had kidney failures are much less likely to be on those lists than white men, <PERSON> Hunsicker </PERSON> said in a telephone interview Thursday. <PERSON> Hunsicker </PERSON> said blacks might be less eager than whites for transplants, because they typically do not do as well after receiving a donor kidney. But they also do not do as well on dialysis because of specialized health problems, he said. `` To get a kidney transplant, your doctors or you must get you on the list, and black patients -LRB- and doctors -RRB- may not take the initiative,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Matas </PERSON>, a kidney-transplant surgeon at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION>. About 5 percent of the women who qualify for kidney transplants may have trouble being matched to a donor organ, <PERSON> Hunsicker </PERSON> said. Women who have been pregnant several times can develop antibodies that would reject the organ, a problem that can be detected in pre-transplant tests, he said. But that 5 percent does not nearly justify the disparity between the number of women and men on dialysis who receive transplants, he said. <PERSON> Hunsicker </PERSON> also said women may hesitate to get transplants because `` by and large, in our society, men tend to be more aggressive and risk-taking.'' In November 1987, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> instituted a new policy for allocating donor kidneys based on objective criteria, <PERSON> Hunsicker </PERSON> said. The government enforces the system by denying hospitals Medicare if they fail to report all patients on waiting lists, all donor kidneys and all recipients. Even before the law was passed, <PERSON> Hunsicker </PERSON> said, `` there is no reason to believe there was any bias anywhere with regards to race or sex. Age is a different matter.'' He said some hospitals may have used age as a criterion before the new policy was instituted.
</TEXT>
