<SECOND>AM-SAfrica-Protest,0565</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black Labor Unions Reject Request To Scuttle Protest Plans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Representatives of big business failed to persuade black labor unions on Thursday to abandon a three-day protest next week that is expected to take the form of a general strike. The two largest black labor federations have called for a peaceful, nationwide protest June 6-8 to express opposition to government crackdowns on anti-apartheid groups and to a proposed labor bill that would curtail unions' ability to hold legal strikes. The federations can not legally endorse a general strike, but their previous calls for national protests have resulted in widespread work stoppages. Leading anti-apartheid clergymen have endorsed the federations' latest appeal. Leaders of the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> African Trade Unions, the largest union federation, met Thursday with a committee representing major employer organizations and headed by <PERSON> Bobby </PERSON> <PERSON> Godsell </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Anglo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. The federation's general secretary, <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Naidoo </PERSON>, told reporters the protest will go ahead as planned because the business officials failed to ease union concerns about the proposed labor legislation. `` We maintain that the bill represents a major rollback of the rights of workers,'' <PERSON> Naidoo </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Godsell </PERSON> said the bill is not `` union-bashing'' legislation. He also said the federation officials refused to promise him that next week's protest would not include stayaways. Federation leaders arranged a meeting Thursday with the <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Africa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Consultative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION>, which represents major employer organizations. The talks included management representatives from the country's leading industries, such as mining, metals and manufacturing. Officials of the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> African Trade Unions met Wednesday with the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unions </ORGANIZATION>, the second largest labor federation. The two groups, which have differed over political ideology, agreed to cooperate in promoting the protest. The <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> says it has 691,000 dues-paying members. The Council claims more than 400,000 members. Police officials said the union groups are being monitored to see if they violated state-of-emergency prohibitions on promotion of political strikes and boycotts. Some employers have threatened to dock wages, take disciplinary action and withdraw from wage negotiations if workers take part in a stayaway. In February the government banned the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> African Trade Unions and 17 other anti-apartheid organizations from taking part in politics. A main federation target is the proposed Labor Relations Amendment, which would make it harder for unions to strike, outlaw sympathy strikes and hold unions liable for losses suffered by employers during an illegal strike. Unions charge that major businesses have not used their influence to oppose the measure, now before <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>. At the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witwatersrand </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>, police fired rubber bullets into the air Thursday to disperse hundreds of college students demonstrating against government detentions of anti-apartheid activists. There were no injuries or arrests, Vice Chancellor <PERSON> Mervyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Shear </PERSON> said. He said that the students had engaged in a `` perfectly peaceful protest.'' An estimated 30,000 people have been detained for varying lengths of time since the government declared a state of emergency in June 1986 following anti-apartheid violence. By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
