hat a meeting had been arranged later in the day at City Hall for himself, gang members Mayor <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> and other officials. Initially, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s schedule included an afternoon debate with front-runner <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, but <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> canceled it Thursday morning because his wife was to undergo surgery on Friday. He flew back to <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> to be with her. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said the City Hall meeting would include discussion of ways to more effectively target resources, social programs and job efforts in the communities plauged by gang and drug problems. He described gangs as groups of people `` who form a reaction of desperation to hopelessness.'' It was unclear what else was acheieved at the morning meeting which was closed to reporters. Some local residents _ many of whom have lost friends and relatives to gang shootings _ expressed hope at the attention <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> brought to their concerns, but also skepticism that any changes could be achieved. `` I do n't know, I doubt it,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Tapla </PERSON>, 17, who described himself as aa <PERSON> Bounty </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON> `` marked'' by rival gangs. `` You ca n't go nowhere without somebody wanting to beat you down or shoot you. I lost three close friends'' to gang violence, he said. `` I'm tired of it. It's time for this to stop.'' Another youth, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, 25, said he once shot someone in a gang feud and did n't stay around to see if the person died. `` It's no big deal. Life in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> LA </LOCATION> is tough,'' he said. But he said `` deep down inside'' many gang members do n't want to be involved in violence. He and others said virtually everyone in their community has a gun. `` It's better to be caught by the police with it, than by some other fool without it,'' said <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, 25. Later Thursday, at City Hall, before <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> met with several county and city representatives and six gang members, <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> praised <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s `` thoroughly remarkable campaign.'' `` I commend you for what you have done in showing what is possible for this country,'' the mayor told the candidate. However, when questioned by reporters, he declined to directly endorse <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. `` <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> has n't needed anybody to endorse him. He's done it on his own,'' <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> said. He credited <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> with `` energizing millions of people across the country.'' When the two emerged from a private meeting, <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> turned aside questions as to why it took a <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> visit to spark the meeting between officials and gang members. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> `` in his most unique way has been able to make an appeal'' to gang members, the mayor said.
