<HEAD>Judge Sees `No Smoking Gun' In Sex Discrimination Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 There is no `` smoking gun'' in the <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> faculty's vote for a former professor who claims she was denied tenure at the school because of her sex, a federal judge said Thursday. Whether <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Bund </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> should become the fifth tenured woman in the school's 80-year history hinges on whether the evidence showed discrimination when she was denied tenure in 1981 and 1983, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Woodlock </PERSON> said Thursday. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, 44, now a private marketing consultant, began teaching at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> in 1973. She was promoted to associate professor in 1977 and applied for tenure in 1981. She sued the university in 1984. The judge, who is expected to rule in the case next week, heard closing arguments in the eight-day trial came after attorney <PERSON> Evan </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> refused the judge's recommendation to suspend the trial to question 56 professors involved a key 1981 faculty vote. <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> said he did not have the resources to embark on `` an extremely complicated and lengthy procedure.'' `` I think you will concede that there is no smoking gun here,'' <PERSON> Woodlock </PERSON> said. `` What I'm interested in finding out is not whether or not her tenure review case was unfair but whether it was unfair because she is a woman.'' In closing arguments, <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> maintained he had compiled `` a multiplicity of little things that put together add up to an evil.'' <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> attorney <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> maintained `` not one shred of evidence'' linked <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s tenure denial to sex bias. During testimony, <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> admitted that documents existed showing the school's faculty voted 47-7 to support <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s tenure bid but two days later backed her by 29-27. But <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> said there was no evidence that <PERSON> McArthur </PERSON> used <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s sex in lobbying professors to switch their votes in 1981. Tenure decisions at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> are submitted to the faculty to gauge support for the professor; the actual decision rests with the university president. <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON>'s argument cited a number of factors which he contends prove that <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> was a victim of sex discrimination, including: _ Business school dean <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> McArthur </PERSON>, a co-defendant with the university, once said the only way to get more women on the school's faculty would be to impose quotas _ At least four men who had less favorable reviews and faculty support than <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> received tenure from 1977 to 1984 _ A marketing expert from outside <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> who backed <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> was specifically asked whether his recommendation had anything to do with affirmative action <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> claimed the school's tenure standards were applied unfairly to <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, who after being denied tenure in 1981 was given a three-year extension and asked to demonstrate excellence in marketing. <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> contended that <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s case was `` a long train of perceived slights ... but it is wholly bereft of any evidence that a man would have been treated any differently than her.''
