<HEAD>France To Keep Up Nuclear Tests; China Warns of Nuclear Technology</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> said Thursday it will continue nuclear tests in the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> and rebuffed a Third World campaign for nuclear disarmament, saying that fighting poverty and hunger are just as important. <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> told the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> special session on disarmament not to adopt Utopian declarations on total nuclear disarmament. It called for realistic measures to reduce conventional arms, especially in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, and a ban on chemical weapons. Foreign Minister <PERSON> Roland </PERSON> <PERSON> Dumas </PERSON> told the 159-member <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> it was paradoxical `` to lavish so much effort on disarmament talks while displaying only resignation and sometimes even indifference when tragic problems of poverty, hunger and debt are broached.'' <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s minister of foreign affairs, <PERSON> Qian </PERSON> <PERSON> Quichen </PERSON>, congratulated the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> for recognizing their special responsibility to reduce their enormous nuclear arsenals, and on their treaty to scrap medium - and shorter-range nuclear missiles He called on the superpowers to cut their arsenals further, while cautioning against false complacency: <PERSON> Qian </PERSON> said that `` even if they do cut by half the number of their nuclear weapons, their nuclear arsenals will still account for approximately 90 percent of the world's total ... sufficient to destroy all life on earth many times over.'' He said `` people should be on guard against an important change which is taking place in the superpower arms race.'' Even with a reduction in the number of nuclear weapons, he asked, `` will qualitative development of more and newer types of armaments make the world safer and peace more secure?'' President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Vassiliou </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> called again for demilitarization of his divided <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> island, saying the money saved could promote economic development of Turkish Cypriots. <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> has been divided into <LOCATION> Greek </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cypriot </LOCATION> and Turkish Cypriot areas since <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> invaded the island in 1974, saying it was to protect the Turkish Cypriot minority after a brief but unsuccessful coup there fostered by the <LOCATION> Greek </LOCATION> military government then in power. <PERSON> Vassiliou </PERSON> said `` no lasting solution is attainable unless Turkish occupation forces and settlers are withdrawn from the island.'' The special session meets through June 25. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and its Western allies hope for a concrete, modest <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> document on disarmament that will not impose on national defense policies and bilateral disarmament efforts. Most of the 12 speakers at the opening session Wednesday issued sweeping calls for total disarmament, a comprehensive nuclear test ban and a supervisory, verification and monitoring role for the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is mainly opposed to the measures. <PERSON> Dumas </PERSON> said Thursday that <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> will not stop nuclear testing in the <ORGANIZATION> Mururoa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atoll </ORGANIZATION> in the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> but announced that the government for the first time would make an annual statement on the number of tests in the preceding 12 months. <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> refuses to ratify the Rarotonga Treaty instituting a nuclear-free zone in the region and <PERSON> Dumas </PERSON> reaffirmed that decision.
