<FIRST>a a PM-BlackMormons-Overseas Adv06   06-02 0749</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Black Mormons-Overseas, Adv 06,0766</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv06</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon PMs, June 6, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Priesthood Revelation Sparks Growth in Africa, Caribbean</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Black Mormons</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The first Mormon missionaries to <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ghana </LOCATION> were greeted by whole congregations of converts awaiting baptism into a church that for more than a century had refused to ordain blacks to its priesthood. `` They came to us,'' said former missionary <PERSON> Reed </PERSON> <PERSON> Clegg </PERSON>. `` We could have baptized thousands. They were living the gospel, paying tithing, holding meetings, before we arrived.'' When the late <ORGANIZATION> Mormon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kimball </PERSON> ended the 130-year exclusion of blacks from the church's all-male priesthood on June 9, 1978, he paved the way for one of the most extraordinary episodes in the faith's long history of missionary work. Blacks have also converted by the thousands in many predominantly black <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> countries and in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, where many of the church's 250,000 members claim black ancestors. But the story of Mormon growth in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> stands apart. For decades, thousands in <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ghana </LOCATION> who had read Mormon books and tracts implored the church to send missionaries to baptize them. But it was n't until the doctrine forbidding black priests was abolished that African governments would grant visas to Mormon missionaries. In one year, the first missionaries _ two elderly couples _ baptized nearly 2,000 converts. A decade later, <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION> has 8,500 church members, <LOCATION> Ghana </LOCATION> 5,000, with membership growing by about 4,000 a year in the two combined. Missionaries returning from African service tell of villagers walking more than 50 miles round trip to attend church meetings, of baptismal services lasting for hours to accommodate all the converts and communities where religion in general was of urgent concern. Church leaders assert they could multiply by many times the rate of growth in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> if they wished. But they are moving slowly to build a solid base of black leadership, and they say the strategy is paying off. In May, visiting officials from <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> ordained the first black African stake president, a lay leader who presides over several congregations, in the Nigerian city of <LOCATION> Aba </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, controlled by the apartheid system of racial separation, the number of black converts is also on the rise. The church could not estimate their number because its membership records do not note race, but blacks attend Sunday meetings and worship in the <ORGANIZATION> Johannesburg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION> alongside whites, said <PERSON> Elder </PERSON> <PERSON> Neal </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Maxwell </PERSON>, who supervises church activities in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. Black Africans are aware of the church's old policy of denying priesthood membership to blacks, but it appears to have made little difference to them. `` They are not as interested in it as we are. For them, that's that They are grateful for -LRB- the change -RRB-, but their eyes are on the future and they do n't seem quite as caught up in it. It's not a big thing for them,'' said <PERSON> Maxwell </PERSON>. Despite the success, prosyletizing in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> has raised new challenges to a church long acquainted with missionary work in far-away places. Among the more difficult is the popular tradition of polygamy. Scores of potential converts have been denied baptism because of plural marriage, a practice the Mormons themselves once embraced but officially dropped in 1890 as a prerequisite to statehood for <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Rendell </PERSON> <PERSON> Mabey </PERSON>, who led the first missionary contingent, said the problem arose on a grand scale in a congregation organized years before the missionaries arrived. When <PERSON> Mabey </PERSON> went to the village to baptize the people, he learned about half were polygamists. The monogamists initially refused to be baptized unless the others could be as well. But after meeting privately, local leaders decided that those who were monogamous would be baptized and the polygamists would continue to attend as non-members. A cultural barrier of a different type _ the practice of voodoo _ confronts missionaries in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Indies </LOCATION>. A folk religion with African origins, voodoo involves the belief that the dead live in a spirit world from which they can be recalled to bless or curse the living. Those who practice it are refused baptism, said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>, a former <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> congressman who now directs the church's missionary effort in <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION>. But <PERSON> King </PERSON> said adherents usually are not attracted to Mormonism. `` I rarely hear it discussed, although I'm aware it is very much a part of the Haitian culture,'' <PERSON> King </PERSON> said. `` We can hear the voodoo drums going into the night.'' End Adv for Mon PMs, June 6
