<HEAD>Mormon Ward Struggles to Accommodate Black Culture</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Cleeretta is cq in 1st graf</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Black Mormons</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Cleeretta </PERSON> <PERSON> Smiley </PERSON> says she's `` free at last'' in the <ORGANIZATION> Mormon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>'s new <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Second </PERSON> <PERSON> Ward </PERSON>, but her 25-year-old son, a Sunday School teacher, wishes the church had more appeal for young blacks. A decade after the church began admitting blacks to priesthood, the sole urban Mormon congregation in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, which is 70 percent black, is mostly white and struggling to convert and keep black members. <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> leaders could think of only two black families who attend church together. Most members are singles or couples and few stay in the ward long. The 400-member congregation is about 40 percent black, but at a recent Sunday service with 100 people, only about one-fourth were black. Yet officials of the Church of <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> <PERSON> Christ </PERSON> of Latter-day Saints say some of the black members, particularly more-recent immigrants, are faithful members, and they are having a subtle impact on traditional Mormon services. A former <LOCATION> Nigerian </LOCATION> legislator, <PERSON> Rufus </PERSON> <PERSON> Olumba </PERSON>, teaches in his native `` agbada'' robes and headdress to a mostly white priesthood class. The lessons are out of the church manual, but <PERSON> Olumba </PERSON> adds unique phraseology and experience to Mormon doctrine. Mrs. <PERSON> Smiley </PERSON>, the ward's public communications director, has heard the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. quoted in church. `` What this church has given me is such a high level of freedom. I'm free, I'm free at last in that ward,'' she said, consciously echoing <PERSON> King </PERSON>'s words. Mrs. <PERSON> Smiley </PERSON>, whose husband left her and won custody of two of their four children after she joined the church three years before the ban on black priests was lifted, said she and other black Mormons tried for years to get an inner-city ward, which was finally established in May 1987. Before that, the city had been divided like a wagon wheel, with its wards radiating out into the suburbs along the lines of the spokes. That scattered the few black members among the suburban wards. <PERSON> Beverly </PERSON> <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON>, a Washington-based church spokeswoman, said the church earlier avoided having a city ward because it did n't want the appearance of segregating church members Now, although the gleaming Mormon temple in <LOCATION> Kensington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, is a suburban landmark, the city's Mormons have no chapel. On Sundays, the church leases part of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>, turning the modern downtown center into a not-so-typical Mormon wardhouse, with bishops conferences in a 13th-floor lounge overlooking the city, <ORGANIZATION> Sunday </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> classes in rooms named for famous journalists and sacrament services in a hall where the nation's newsmakers address the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> press. <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON> acknowledged the church faces a challenge in attracting black Americans. `` The gospel is ever true and ever the same. It does not change,'' she said. `` And yet, the people of other cultures must feel a spiritual and emotional binding with the spiritual message. That is sometimes missing.'' But in a church that now prides itself in attracting all races and nationalities, there are n't enough active black members to raise the issue of segregation. Mrs. <PERSON> Smiley </PERSON>'s son <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> said the church has little appeal to inner-city blacks, who still view it as a white, racist institution. `` The church has the basic principles,'' he said, `` but it has to change with the times.'' A graduate in industrial technology, he said one of his major complaints about the church is the dullness of its music. At a recent service, the congregation sang several traditional, slow Mormon hymns _ a sharp contrast to the lively gospel music of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s predominantly black Protestant churches. A member of the bishopric, <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Sykes </PERSON>, said he knew of no incidents of racial prejudice among Mormons in the area but pointed to other problems. Church members assigned to make monthly visits to members' homes have been mugged in tough inner-city neighborhoods, he said. <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> leaders try hard to make black members more active in the congregation and to make them leaders, he said, but many are from homes where they are the only Mormons. They face pressure to leave the church from their families and friends and from actively anti-Mormon Protestant ministers, he said. <PERSON> Sykes </PERSON>, a 26-year-old financial analyst with the <ORGANIZATION> Marriott </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, said he believes full acceptance of the church by blacks may have to come with the generation who are now children. `` The children ... should be able to reconcile their black heritage and their Mormon heritage,'' he said. `` Maybe only then can there be a happy marriage of Mormonism and the black American.'' End Adv for Mon PMs, June 6
