<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> has rejected an appeal against back taxes and penalties by the <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Scientology </ORGANIZATION>, leaving in place the 1967 revocation of its tax exemption. The high court declined to review lower court decisions penalizing the group for tax deficiencies in 1970, 1971 and 1972, holding that large amounts of its monies claimed as tax-exempt went for private enrichment of Scientology's late founder <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Hubbard </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Sue </PERSON> <PERSON> Hubbard </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tax </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> had ruled that $ 3.5 million was deposited in Swiss banks through a bogus trust in those years, much of it later removed to a safe on a yacht, Apollo, on which the <ORGANIZATION> Hubbards </ORGANIZATION> had taken up residence in the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION>. He died in 1986. However, the group continues to function, pressing lawsuits claiming its `` E-meter'' auditing is religious and exempt from taxes levied against its income. End Adv Fri PMs June 3
