<FIRST>a a PM-AnotherLook:AfterIBM Adv06   06-02 0969</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Another Look: After IBM, Adv 06,0991</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv06</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon PMs, June 6, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Town Survives On Planning, Good Fortune after 1,000-Job Pullout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEN KUSMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREENCASTLE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Eighteen months ago when <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> suddenly shut down its <LOCATION> Greencastle </LOCATION> operation and took away nearly 1,000 jobs, it left behind a lot of `` ducks,'' local merchant <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Lane </PERSON> likes to say. `` Very calm on the surface, but paddling furiously underneath.'' That's how she describes the approach this quiet college town has taken from the day of <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s bad news _ using careful planning, good fortune and hard work to bring in six new employers and 1,000 replacement jobs in the short term, as many as 2,000 five years from now. Long before <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said it would close its parts distribution center after 33 years, <LOCATION> Greencastle </LOCATION> had laid the foundation to deal with the shock of losing 8 percent of the jobs in <LOCATION> Putnam </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> made the announcement without warning Nov. 11, 1986, and by the following March, about half of the employees had transferred to other sites, the rest had taken early retirement. `` The fact that <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> closed could have been devastating. It was n't,'' said banker <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Marley </PERSON>. `` The framework was there, we were ready to go.'' In 1983 an economic development review had identified the strengths and weaknesses of the town of 8,400; the importance, for example, of revitalizing the courthouse square, which had just been designated a national historic district. A needed hotel, the Walden Inn, was planned for the edge of the <ORGANIZATION> DePauw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> campus. Two years later a planning group examined the town's economic future, leading to the incorporation of the <ORGANIZATION> Greencastle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in September 1986. `` We were fortunate this community had started planning for the future three years ahead of time,'' said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Hutchings </PERSON>, chairman of the mayor's economic development commission. Despite an initial dark mood in town, residents projected only optimism to reporters who came to record the changes <LOCATION> Greencastle </LOCATION> was going through. `` Everytime any media came around, the word would get around and the cheerleading would begin. I think that's what won all the industry,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Lane </PERSON>, who chairs the group that has led the rehabilitation of the Victorian buildings along the courthouse square. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Preston </PERSON>, who helps the state recruit new industry through the <ORGANIZATION> Indiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION>, said, `` I think they benefited from a lot of exposure when <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> left and the legacy <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> left.'' No one has a harsh word for <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>. The company gave $ 1.7 million to local government to smooth the transition of its loss and continued its <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Way </ORGANIZATION> contribution of more than $ 120,000 for three years. It also turned over $ 700,000 from the sale of `` Big Blue,'' its 350,000-square-foot complex. Just as importantly, <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> bought the more than 300 homes being sold by transferred employees and hired <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> to market them. Fewer than 10 remain unsold. Fortunate timing helped <LOCATION> Greencastle </LOCATION>. Just days before the <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> announcement, bonds were sold for a $ 13 million expansion of the high school and construction of the middle school. A week later and the bonds might not have been sold. They've made the schools more attractive to companies scouting new locations. A day before the announcement, scouts for <ORGANIZATION> Automotive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION>, which produces auto trim, had been in the area discussing possible locations. A few days afterward, they were inspecting the <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> site. That January, just 72 days after <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s announcement, <ORGANIZATION> Automotive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> became the first new industry to come to <LOCATION> Greencastle </LOCATION> in 15 years. It built a plant under the <ORGANIZATION> Shenandoah </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> name that might employ as many 700 workers in five years. `` It was the boost we needed. It was a confirmation to our optimism,'' said <PERSON> Joyce </PERSON> <PERSON> Hanlon </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Greencastle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Merchants </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. Banker <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Doan </PERSON> recalled the time he and others were in his office after midnight negotiating with an officer from Charming Shoppes in <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> on one phone and one from <PERSON> Shigeru </PERSON> <PERSON> K.K </PERSON>. in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> on another. Charming will move into `` Big Blue'' and employ 300 by early next year in a warehouse for its women's fashion outlets. More than 600 eventually might work there. <PERSON> Shigeru </PERSON>, which like <ORGANIZATION> Shenandoah </ORGANIZATION> will supply auto trim to Japanese auto plants being built in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>, will employ 100 in a company called <ORGANIZATION> Heartland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Automotive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> by the end of next year. Three other companies _ two automobile parts suppliers and <ORGANIZATION> Sherwin-Williams </ORGANIZATION>, which is setting up a distributing center for automotive paint _ also are developing facilities in an industrial park where once only <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> stood. The new companies, however, wo n't replace <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s payroll, which was $ 38 million, or roughly $ 38,000 per year per employee. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Andis </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s former head of strategic planning who took early retirement to run the development center, said new employers will create an initial payroll of about $ 20 million. He and other retirees will bring in an additional $ 9 million in income. <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Carney </PERSON>, a local car dealer, said <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> people represented sales of at least a car per day for him. After <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> left, his volume has dropped from more than 80 cars per month to about 20. He laid off 19 of his 45 employees. The Rev. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Barber </PERSON>, pastor of the <ORGANIZATION> Peace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lutheran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>, said <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s departure meant losing a fifth of his congregation of 216, plus 31 percent of the donations. But now his congregation is back over 200 again. `` The Lord was very gracious with us,'' <PERSON> Barber </PERSON> said. Mayor <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Harmless </PERSON>, a 38-year-old <LOCATION> Greencastle </LOCATION> native elected last November, points out the new industry will create entry-level jobs for local high-school graduates. But until all the companies get going, he acknowledges, `` these are going to be lean years for the community.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon PMs, June 6</NOTE>
