<SECOND>PM-Surfing Pets, Adv 10,0810</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv10</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri PMs, June 10, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Pet Peeve of Hawaiian Humane Society: Surfing Animals</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Professional surfer <PERSON> Rell </PERSON> <PERSON> Kapoliokaehukai </PERSON> <PERSON> Sunn </PERSON> figured she and her dog, <PERSON> Shane </PERSON>, had the `` Wet Pet'' division of a recent surfing contest all wrapped up. Then the pig with the sunscreen showed up. <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Keaulana </PERSON>, another pro surfer, and his 4-month-old pig `` Chop Chop'' sent the 2,000 spectators and five judges at <LOCATION> Makaha </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> on <LOCATION> Leeward </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Oahu </LOCATION> hog wild, beating a dozen other human competitors who rode their boards tandem with everything from a baby goose to saltwater fish in a bowl. `` <PERSON> Shane </PERSON> is the surfing dog of <LOCATION> Makaha </LOCATION>, the kids love him,'' <PERSON> Sunn </PERSON> said of her 2-year-old mutt. `` But <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> really did some moves on the board with that pig, Chop Chop. <PERSON> Shane </PERSON> just sort of sits there.'' But <PERSON> Sunn </PERSON>, who is 37 and works as a lifeguard, said winning was not important. She was happy that the first `` Wet Pet'' contest, part of the 11th Annual <ORGANIZATION> Rell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sunn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Menehune </ORGANIZATION> Surfing Championships, was a hit. `` The kids out there were going crazy. Everybody just loved it,'' she said. Not everybody. The <ORGANIZATION> Hawaiian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Humane </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> received numerous phone calls protesting the event and wants to prevent similar contests in the future, according to <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON>, public relations and fund development director. The society is not impressed by surfing animals. `` We are against putting animals in unnatural or dangerous situations,'' <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON> said. `` And there is nothing more unnatural than a pig on a surfboard.'' Further, <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON> said, delicate pink pig skin is prone to sunburn, and not all owners are as considerate at <PERSON> Keaulana </PERSON>, who covered Chop Chop's ears and snout with multicolored zinc oxide. `` People thought the pig was in distress because it was green,'' <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON> said. `` They did n't know it was covered with colored suntan lotion.'' <PERSON> Sunn </PERSON>'s `` Wet Pet'' contest is the first one <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON> has heard of in the islands, but he's worried the idea might catch on. `` It might look fun, but whose entertainment is it?'' he asked. `` It's certainly not entertaining or fun for the animals.'' <PERSON> Sunn </PERSON> disagreed, but acknowledged <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON> had a point. `` <PERSON> Shane </PERSON> loves being in the water. He loves to surf and he loves the attention,'' she said. `` But some animals might not like it, and their owners should n't push them just to show off.'' <PERSON> Sunn </PERSON> said she refused to let one inexperienced surfer enter the `` Wet Pet'' competition after she saw the woman practicing with her dog. `` She wiped out and had attached the dog's leash to the board so it really got knocked around in the waves. That dog could have drowned or broken its neck,'' <PERSON> Sunn </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Humane </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> `` is n't declaring war on these people, we just want to educate them,'' noting that animals are prohibited on state beaches, and that regulation could be more strictly enforced. <PERSON> Sunn </PERSON> said she plans to hold the competition again next year, but will regulate who can enter. `` We're only going to have people who we know surf with their animals, who we've seen out before,'' she said. Meanwhile, she says she'll keep surfing with <PERSON> Shane </PERSON>. `` He loves it and I do n't think anybody should tell me what to do with my dog,'' she said. `` I do n't force him. I just put the board on the beach, he jumps on the nose and we paddle out together.'' `` I only take him out in gentle surf. He likes small waves, nothing bigger than 5 feet.'' <PERSON> Rob </PERSON> <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> agreed: `` You know how certain dogs really like to hang their heads out of car windows? Well, it's like that, some pets just really take to the waves.'' <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> owns <ORGANIZATION> Local </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motion </ORGANIZATION>, a Honolulu-based water sports equipment and clothing store with nationwide distribution, which sponsored a surfing contest in the waves off <LOCATION> Waikiki </LOCATION> on Memorial Day and wanted to include a `` Wet Pet'' division this year. `` I've heard of pigs out in Waianae that bodysurf all by themselves and one gal has a pet rabbit that follows her to the beach,'' he said. But after talking it over with the <ORGANIZATION> Humane </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> scrapped his plan. `` They let us know they were against it and that is was illegal to have animals on the beach,'' <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> said. `` It looked like it was going to cause a big stink, when it was supposed to be all in fun, so we just decided to drop it.'' <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> `` was very sensible about it and understood our point of view,'' said <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON>. `` Some people are n't so sensible. Those are the ones we're worried about.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri PMs, June 10</NOTE>
