<HEAD>Christians Flock To Atheist Land To Salute Faith</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 By some odd twists of place and history, church leaders of the world converge next week in a land of official atheism to celebrate the original flowering there of Christianity. It's a peculiar combination. In the seemingly incompatible setting of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, whose government disavows existence of God, an enduring faith marks its 1,000 th birthday Taking part there in June 5-16 celebrations are prominent church figures from many countries, ranging from top <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> officers to evangelist <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> to the Archbishop of <LOCATION> Canterbury </LOCATION>. To a curious extent, the occasion brings together chieftains of belief in a climate against it, where the Communist government's efforts to stamp it out have gone on for 70 years But signs of change circulated and the Rev. <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Rigdon </PERSON>, a Presbyterian scholar of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> and specialist on Soviet church life, says `` all kinds of amazing things are happening'' to improve religious conditions. `` We want to show our solidarity with churches there, to express our hopes for them and let the government know that they're not isolated and alone but part of a worldwide community that holds them in esteem and cares for them.'' The Rev. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilkes </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Baptist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, also among those attending, says, `` This worldwide gathering can be helpful in overcoming barriers to Christianity and making it better understood.'' The affair comes at a time of moderations in Soviet domestic policies, including opening of additional churches, large-scale printing and importing of Bibles and promised easing of religious restrictions. Some even see latent religious potentialities in Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, reportedly raised in a Russian Orthodox family and who says laws are being revised to recognize religious concerns. `` We are praying that he will become a Christian and, if possible, a Methodist,'' the Rev. Olay Parnaments, a <ORGANIZATION> Methodist </ORGANIZATION> pastor in <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION> told the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Methodist </ORGANIZATION> general conference in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> in May. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> in April met with Patriarch <PERSON> Pimen </PERSON> in the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> and called for more tolerant attitudes toward religion, the first such meeting between top church and government leaders in 40 years. <PERSON> Bishop </PERSON> <PERSON> Clement </PERSON>, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> representative of Russian Orthodoxy, says about 450 foreign church leaders are attending the celebrations there, including about 60 from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Roman Cathoilicism is sending a high-level, 10-member delegation, headed by the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> Secretary of <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION>, Cardinal <PERSON> Agostino </PERSON> <PERSON> Casaroli </PERSON>, the <PERSON> pope </PERSON>'s top aide. He and Archbishop of Canterbury <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Runcie </PERSON>, leader of the world-wide Anglican communion, including <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Episcopalians, are among speakers for special `` Jubilee'' ceremonies June 10 at Resurrection Church of the newly restored St. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Monastery </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. Other speakers at that time are to include <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> and Rabbi <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Schneier </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, president of the interfaith <ORGANIZATION> Appeal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conscience </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, which works internationally to promote religious freedom. Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> issued a pastoral letter on the rise and endurance of Christianity in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, expressing hopes for `` full communion in Christ with these sister churches.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Lutheran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> hailed the Russian church for its creative influence in the country's history. Among American church leaders attending: The Rev. <PERSON> Avery </PERSON> <PERSON> Post </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christ </ORGANIZATION>; the Rev. <PERSON> Arie </PERSON> <PERSON> Brouwer </PERSON>, chief executive of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Churches </ORGANIZATION>; Metropolitan Theodosius, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Orthodox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>; Roman Catholic Cardinal <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>; the Rev. <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Hale </PERSON>, general secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Methodist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Bishop </PERSON> <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Chilstrom </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Evangelical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lutheran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>; Episcopal Bishop <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Reed </PERSON> of <LOC