<HEAD>Prepared for Earthquake, He Orchestrated Recovery from High-Rise
Fire</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Cole <PERSON> Emerson </PERSON> has known for two years that when the big earthquake hits <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, it will be his job to get <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interstate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> back into business. When the city's worst high-rise fire swept the bank's headquarters last month, <PERSON> Emerson </PERSON> saw his disaster plans put to the test, and by all accounts, they passed The inferno broke out at 10:30 p.m. May 4, gutting 4 -LCB- floors of the 62-story building, killing one maintenance man and closing the state's tallest building for an indefinite time. But by the start of banking hours the next day, the vital business of the <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interstate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bancorp </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's ninth-biggest bank holding company, was proceeding And only one of the company's 320 <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> branches was closed _ the one on the building's ground floor. `` Because of the planning process, because of the group of people that was there, the team, and our instant communications with our customers, we did n't miss a beat,'' said <PERSON> Emerson </PERSON>, the bank's vice president for information management. <PERSON> Emerson </PERSON>, 42, is in charge of contingency planning and computer security. He is assigned to the <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interstate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION>, although in the headquarters fire, his plan and staff also helped restart the parent company, which owns banks in 13 states and franchises in 10 others. A former criminal investigator for the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Emerson </PERSON> moved into corporate security in 1977. He began his tenure at <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interstate </ORGANIZATION> in 1986 after stints with various other firms including <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Carter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hawley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. His straightforward, almost deadpan description of First Interstate's recovery from the fire is typical of his lawman's approach to the task of disaster He recalled that shortly after the fire broke out, his five-member `` business resumption group'' and a parallel group that deals with staff safety opened the bank's new emergency center, which is in a computer operations building seven blocks from the downtown headquarters. As damage reports came in, <PERSON> Emerson </PERSON>'s group orchestrated moves for the vital groups that work in the headquarters: _ They saw the securities trading department dispersed, with traders flying to company offices in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, as well as taking borrowed space in town They were prepared, since the disaster plan calls for traders and a few other key employees to carry home diskettes bearing vital records from their personal computers. _ They arranged the rental of hundreds of telephones, switched numbers and lines, and organized the flow of 125,000 incoming and 8,000 outgoing pieces of mail each day _ As the week wore on, they found office space for 1,500 displaced workers in First Interstate buildings and branches throughout <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and in offices rented or borrowed on short notice The main computers handling the bank's daily rush of consumer and business transactions were n't in the headquarters, but if they had been knocked out, they would have been backed up in <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Emerson </PERSON> noted. `` Those in banking that were aware of First Interstate's -LRB- disaster -RRB- plan said that it was among the best in the industry,'' said <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheppard </PERSON>, spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bankers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> `` Cole is a very well-organized person, a very non-excitable type person,'' said <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Pistey </PERSON>, a co-worker in charge of the bank's physical security `` That's something that's very important in any crisis ... And if your planning has gone well, that's something that's not all facade.'' <PERSON> J.J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinola </PERSON>, chairman of the holding company, credits planners with foreseeing the necessary moves, but, like <PERSON> Emerson </PERSON>, praises the employees who made the plans work and continue to work in sometimes cramped quarters. `` I think the heroes are there,'' <PERSON> Pinola </PERSON> said, `` -LRB- but -RRB- in this case every single member of the organization feels good about their part in getting us out of this mess.'' The disaster plan actually was developed to deal with a great earthquake. The state <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Emergency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> say odds are better than 50 percent that such a quake will hit the region in the next 25 years. `` An earthquake is real, and it's catastrophic, and it's going to happen,'' <PERSON> Emerson </PERSON> said. `` There's nobody in my position in any of the banks who's going to say ` if.' It's always ` when it's going to happen.' I feel even more confident right now that we're well on the way to being prepared for that.'' In <PERSON> Emerson </PERSON>'s office, a hardhat hangs from the coatrack and a portable telephone sits on a chair. The view out the window is of a white circus tent pitched to shelter hundreds of cardboard cartons holding business documents and personal belongings salvaged from the building. Preliminary engineering reports indicate the building will be safe to reoccupy, but <PERSON> Pinola </PERSON> says estimates of when are guesses at best. An electrical fault is believed to have caused the fire, but the investigation is n't complete. There still is n't a firm dollar estimate of the damage. For <PERSON> Emerson </PERSON> and his team, the recovery is both a victory and a base on which to build. `` It's funny, it's almost addictive _ planning alternates,'' <PERSON> Emerson </PERSON> said. `` Even planning a trip you find yourself saying, ` If I ca n't go this way and catch this plane at this schedule, then I have this back-up.' It just becomes a normal part of your thinking.''
