<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 From Cajun food to cable television, the journalists, Kremlinologists, presidential aides and party functionaries involved in the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> summit got a glimpse of capitalism in the core of communist power. While the summit was short on substance, it broke down some of the stereotypes the two leaders had on life in the other superpower, stirring up a `` feel-good'' atmosphere that was visible on the streets and sidewalks of this infamously grim city. Media madness and commercial hype are unfamiliar experiences in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, and for the most part Soviet citizens were excluded from the fray that unfolded at the summit media center. Roadblocks set up a half-mile from the site at the International Hotel steered away all without special passes. But for the Westerners in town for the meetings between <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, a few touches of home made their stay more comfortable and in conformance with similar events held abroad. The island of consumerism established at the hotel, known as the `` Mezh'' among the foreign community here, drew dozens of prominent Soviet pundits and politicians. Instant coffee and caviar sandwiches were sold from linen-spread tables in the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hall </ORGANIZATION>, alongside kiosks selling <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s book `` Perestroika'' and stacks of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> postcards Officials in the vanguard of the glasnost and perestroika campaigns milled around the cavernous press room, where many of the 5,000 journalists covering the event set up telephones, typewriters and portable computers. They gave impromptu interviews, surveyed the souvenirs and watched the live <ORGANIZATION> Cable </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION> feed on huge television monitors set up throughout the center. The White House press center issued texts of the president's speeches and comments, and the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> responded with summit briefing packets and a desk that took applications for private interviews with Soviet officials <ORGANIZATION> CNN </ORGANIZATION> beamed its 24-hour service into central <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> for the summit, but only foreign-made televisions like those at the <LOCATION> Mezh </LOCATION> were able to tune in the American programming. A mobile pizza van brought in to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> two months ago parked along the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> embankment across from the hotel and did a whopping business with the busy journalists. A <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> chef, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Folse </PERSON>, shipped his Cajun cooking operation _ lock, stock and catfish _ to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> for the summit, taking over the Mercury restaurant at the Mezh in a weeklong joint-venture that hit some snags. The restaurant gave out free hamburgers and fries to the working press as a means of eating up some of its profits that could not be taken out of the country. Rival T-shirt and souvenir kiosks sprung up at the press center, dispensing `` <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> Summit-88'' memorabilia for hard currency. Even the official <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency got in on the act, producing shirts, buttons, records and tapes with the help of an American marketing firm. Summit spinoffs that reached the general public were at times more hindrance than help. Roadblocks were set up at intersections leading to all summit sights _ the press center, the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> ambassador's residence where the <ORGANIZATION> Reagans </ORGANIZATION> stayed and along motorcade routes. The traffic diversions frustrated some Soviets trying to get to home or work in areas around the president's path. But the spruced-up city and the excitement of a visit by the American president who once called the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> an `` evil empire'' made Muscovites proud and brought them out in droves for walks about the summit showcase. American and Soviet flags stemmed from light poles along the motorcade routes and Red Square, with its famous and garish landmarks, was floodlit throughout the summit for the benefit of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> television viewers who saw the historic setting as the backdrop on evening news programs. The Arbat pedestrian mall, always thronged with street artists and strollers, took on a more political focus with murals depicting abstract concepts of superpower relations and buttons commemorating the five-day event. But almost simultaneously with the takeoff of the presidential plane, the barriers came down and the power plugs were pulled. Some summit preparations may have longer term effects, like the frenetic painting and repaving done before the event. But for most Muscovites, the signs of the superpower conference were a memory before <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s plane crossed out of Soviet airspace.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> has been a correspondent for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> since July 1984
</TEXT>
