<HEAD>Advance for Weekend Editions, June 11-12, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Ford's Probe Makes Heads Turn</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto and LaserGraphic</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANN M. JOB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>For The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The 1989 Ford Probe can be hazardous to drive. The problem is not with the car, but with other folks who want to get a good look at it. During the time I had a Probe GL test car, I was chased at 80 mph down a freeway by two guys in a spanking new-looking Pontiac Grand Prix who wanted to check out the Probe. Their Grand Prix just made its debut this model year. I also encountered an older fellow who nearly stopped in the middle of intersection so he could get a gander at my Probe. Traffic in my neighborhood picked up one Sunday as people came back around the block to get second and third looks at the Probe. And the Probe was immediately surrounded by curious sales people at a <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> dealership I visited. It sure seems that <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> has an attention-getter with this aerodynamic, fun-to-drive, small specialty car that was unveiled in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> in February and went on sale in May. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> already has 70,000 orders, which amounts to this year's full production at the <LOCATION> Flat </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rock </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, plant where the car is built. Eventual plant capacity could reach 150,000 annually. The front-drive Probe is unique in a couple ways. Though sold in <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> showrooms, the car was designed with the help of <ORGANIZATION> Mazda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and is being produced at the <ORGANIZATION> Mazda </ORGANIZATION> plant in Flat Rock by <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> members. The plant, the first <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> assembly plant operated by a Japanese automaker to be organized by the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION>, also builds the <ORGANIZATION> Mazda </ORGANIZATION> version of the Probe, called the <ORGANIZATION> Mazda </ORGANIZATION> MX-6 which shares many components with the Probe. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>, by the way, owns 25 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Mazda </ORGANIZATION>. But the Probe differs from the MX-6 in appearance inside and out, conveying a more modern, sleek image. And for all the attention it gets, it does n't cost a mint. Base price for the GL, the lowest-priced version of the Probe, was $ 10,459. The test car, with optional premium sound system, cast aluminum wheels, air conditioning and automatic transmission totaled $ 13,186. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> also offers an upscale LX model which starts at around $ 11,400, and a top-of-the-line performance GT, which sports a spoiler, fog lamps and turbocharged engine and starts at around $ 13,600. Those prices put the Probe squarely in contention with its Japanese competitors _ the <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> Prelude, which starts around $ 14,000, and the Toyota Celica, which starts around $ 12,000. The test car, the low-end Probe GL, had commendable suspension and good handling. However, the standard engine _ a 2.2-liter electronic fuel-injected four-cylinder _ did n't quite seem to deliver the power one would want in such a sleek, sassy-looking car. Cloth front bucket seats were comfortable enough. But leg room in the back was a problem. Fit and finish inside and out was admirable, and the tilt steering was different, causing the whole steering module, including instrument cluster, to move up and down. It was a nice touch, considering the feature meant never having to worry about a steering wheel adjustment obscuring the view of one of the gauges. It took some getting used to the blinker. It was n't a stalk on the side of the steering column. Rather, it was a small lever attached to the dash. Likewise, the headlights were not activated by the traditional push-pull knob on the dash nor the turn of a switch at the end of a blinker stalk. Instead, the retractable headlights came out and on when a large dial on the side of the instrument cluster was turned. The rear cargo area was deep and roomy, but items had to be lifted up and over the rear of the car. The Probe is aimed at young, career-oriented buyers, a <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> statement said. Specifically, targeted buyers have a median age of 30, 55 percent are single, half are male, and they have a median annual income of $ 33,000, said <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> analyst <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Windecker </PERSON>. The major occupations expected to be represented among Probe drivers include professional-technical workers and managers, he added. There have been several reports that the Probe is designed to replace the <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mustang </ORGANIZATION>, which has been around since the 1960s. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> says the two cars will be sold side-by-side in showrooms, and the <PERSON> Mustang </PERSON> will remain as long as there is consumer demand. Because the Probe is just arriving on the market, there are no reliability reports.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Job </PERSON>, executive business editor of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>, writes biweekly automobile reviews for The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. She has covered the automobile industry for six years.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, June 11-12</NOTE>
