<HEAD>Germans Rushing To Boost Trade With Soviets; Washington Concerned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 West German businesses, lured in part by promises of economic reform in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, are rushing to boost their trade with the Kremlin. They range from the mighty <ORGANIZATION> Deutsche </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, which recently arranged a $ 2 billion line of credit for the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION>, to the sporting goods company <ORGANIZATION> Adidas </ORGANIZATION>, which already is making products in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> but is looking to expand. While a string of new collaborations were announced in May, the growing trend has sparked some criticism from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Sen. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Sasser </PERSON>, D-Tenn., without referring by name to <ORGANIZATION> Deutsche </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, said the Soviets `` are using these loans to finance military mischief, I fear, around the world. But Soviet economists say that is unlikely. `` Soviet consumers want better products,'' said <PERSON> Helmut </PERSON> <PERSON> Giesecke </PERSON>, an economist with the <ORGANIZATION> Bonn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> and Trade Conference office. `` Once they have them, they're not going back to the old ways.'' Still, <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON>, who appeared with <PERSON> Sasser </PERSON> at a recent senate committee hearing, said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> defense officials had discussed the situation `` in general terms because they put an added defense burden on the <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> allies.'' The allies, however, could also complain about <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade with the Soviets, <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> noted. <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, which serves as <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>'s front line of defense against the Soviet-led <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> pact, has seen its trade with the Soviets decline for the past three years. West German imports from the Soviets have nearly halved to $ 4.27 billion since 1984, and exports to the Soviets are down to $ 4.6 billion, from $ 6.3 billion three years ago. Seventy percent of Soviet exports to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> are natural gas and oil products, which are purchased with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollars. But a low dollar and cheap oil prices have taken their toll, cutting into the foreign currency supplies the Soviets need import goods. Increased ties to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> fit Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s program to improve conditions at home, Soviet economists say. To encourage foreign investment, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has begun allowing Western concerns to own a share of Soviet industries. <ORGANIZATION> Deutsche </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> economist <PERSON> Hans </PERSON> <PERSON> Dettmar </PERSON> said that it is too early to tell how the line of credit will be used by the Soviets, but `` it is intended for light industry consumer products, such as shoes and foodstuffs, and joint venture projects to expand that market with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>.'' Any business deals will be announced by the companies taking part, not the bank. `` We and the other banks involved only make the money available,'' he said. Among the German companies that announced deals last month were: _ Salamander, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s largest shoe producer, which already produces shoes in <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION>, said it would up its production with a new plant in <LOCATION> Vitebsk </LOCATION> _ <ORGANIZATION> Lurgi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> GmbH </ORGANIZATION> said it was heading a consortium of companies awarded a $ 294 million contract to build two new oil and gas plants to expand production in the <LOCATION> Tengiuz </LOCATION> oil fields near the <LOCATION> Caspian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> _ <ORGANIZATION> Adidas </ORGANIZATION> will begin making sports textiles in <LOCATION> Tbilis </LOCATION> by the end of this year The company has been making shoes in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> since 1978 and in <LOCATION> Kiev </LOCATION> since 1984. _ MAN, producer of heavy vehicles, announced a joint venture with the Soviets to produce long-haul trucks To help finance the deals the Soviets are looking West for hard currency. <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> bank sources said the Soviets are planning to sell $ 294 million in Eurobonds in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. That sale would follow a $ 70 million bond the Soviets floated five months ago in <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>.
