<HEAD>Government Rolls Back Some Anti-Alcohol Measures, Newspaper Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government has relaxed curbs on the production of alcohol and lifted some restrictions on the sale of booze in a slackening of <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s anti-drunkenness drive, a weekly newspaper reports. <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> News, which is at the forefront of the Soviet leader's campaign for `` glasnost,'' or openness, did not say what restrictions on sales were removed But the labor newspaper Trud reported last month that <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> city authorities had recently allowed an expansion of the number of stores selling alcoholic beverages to 772. It did not give the previous figure. <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> News, in its Wednesday editions, and Trud gave two reasons for the easing of <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s anti-alcoholism campaign: to try to discourage moonshining and stop a run on sugar. The moonshiners, who <PERSON> Trud </PERSON> said are outproducing the legal alcohol industry, use sugar to make alcohol. Sugar is being rationed in several <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> cities, but <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> said it is not in short supply, adding that sugar supplies were greater in 1988 than last year. Increased sales of alcohol and the stabilization of alcohol production should reduce the use of sugar by moonshiners, <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> said. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s anti-alcohol campaign, his first major initiative after taking power in March 1985, included raising the drinking age, shortening the hours of liquor stores and cutting liquor production. Soviet officials have credited the campaign with increasing the life expectancy and cutting drunkenness on the job. but <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> Shmelev </PERSON>, a prominent economist, told reporters last week <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has been going about trying to reduce alcoholism the wrong way. He said the campaign has encouraged moonshiners and taken revenue from liquor sales away from the government. Instead, said <PERSON> Shmelev </PERSON>, the government should improve consumer supplies `` so a man could use his ruble to buy a bottle of vodka or a good shirt.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> daily <ORGANIZATION> Pravda </ORGANIZATION> reported late last year that more than 4.5 million of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s 284 million people are `` registered alcoholics,'' 1 million of whom require compulsory care.
