<HEAD>Koppers Succumbs To Beazer in $1.7 Billion Deal</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS last graf to show tender offer was extended to June
15 rather than deal expected to close by that date.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After three months of lawsuits, talk of a recapitalization plan and a flurry of political support, <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> succumbed to a $ 1.7 billion takeover bid from British industrialist <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Beazer </PERSON>. The construction materials and chemicals company, one of the largest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> road repair concerns, agreed Wednesday to be acquired for $ 61 a share by <ORGANIZATION> BNS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a company formed by <ORGANIZATION> Beazer </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Westminster </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>. `` We set out to keep the company independent, but business as it is currently conducted did n't give us that opportunity,'' <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Pullin </PERSON> said after the board unanimously approved the merger. <ORGANIZATION> Beazer </ORGANIZATION>'s struggle to acquire <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION> aroused intense hostility in <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, where <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION> is a major employer. It led to legal wrangling in federal court and compelled local members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to introduce anti-takeover measures. The battle also ignited sharp criticism over <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION>'s role in participating in a hostile takeover while helping to finance it. <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION>' congressional allies were quick to note that <ORGANIZATION> Beazer </ORGANIZATION>'s victory does not quiet those concerns `` The question for the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> remains about the role of the investment bankers, where they were essentially both soliciting the deal and providing the wherewithall,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Walgren </PERSON>, D-Pa. `` That to me is something that we ought to remain concerned about,'' said <PERSON> Walgren </PERSON>, one of 15 congressmen who petitioned the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> for an investigation `` It's not approprite for securities firms and foreign corporations with banking interests to be involved in hostile takeovers,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Ridge </PERSON>, R-Pa., who vowed to support new regulations Ridge and <PERSON> Walgren </PERSON> co-sponsored a bill barring foreign banks and domestic financial services firms from hostile takeovers. But their efforts, like a bill introduced by Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON>, R-Pa., fell short of helping <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION> A key feature of the merger agreement is job guarantees for <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION> employees. About 7,000 salaried workers will be guaranteed jobs for at least one year or get a year's pay, and hourly employees are covered by contracts that remain in force, <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION> said. In addition, payments from a 32-year-old deferred compensation plan will be accelerated to some of <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION>' 460 active and retired managers, but `` nobody is going to get more under this merger than they had when <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION> was ... totally independent,'' <PERSON> Pullin </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Beazer </ORGANIZATION> said he would delay for 45 days plans to sell the chemicals business, giving managers a chance to make an offer. He agreed that <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION> will remain headquartered in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> for at least three years. <PERSON> Pullin </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION>' greatest hope of surviving on its own was a recapitalization plan it claimed would compete with <ORGANIZATION> Beazer </ORGANIZATION>'s offer. But management's deal collapsed last week when an unidentified prospective buyer backed out of purchasing part of the construction materials business, he said. Koppers opposition to <ORGANIZATION> Beazer </ORGANIZATION> traces back to March 3, when <ORGANIZATION> BNS </ORGANIZATION> launched a $ 45-a-share tender offer. BNS boosted the offer to $ 60 a share on March 25 and sweetened it by $ 1 during weekend negotiations. <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION> won anti-takeover injunctions in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Courts </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> ruling, concerning antitrust issues, fell last week on appeal, and the judge in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> offered BNS options for overcoming apparent violations of securities laws. On Wall Street, <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION> stock closed Wednesday at $ 60.50 a share, up $ 1.50. Analysts were satisfied with the $ 61-a-share payout. `` That's a good value for <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION> shareholders,'' said analyst <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Willis </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Brown </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Brothers </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harriman </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. In the end, <PERSON> Pullin </PERSON> insisted that the merger agreement was reached `` with my complete cooperation'' and that the takeover fulfills management's commitment to enhance shareholder value. `` Now that the drama has ended, we are looking forward to getting on with the job, putting together a world class aggregates company and beating the competition,'' <ORGANIZATION> Beazer </ORGANIZATION> said. The tender offer was extended until June 15.
