<TEXT>
 Financially troubled <ORGANIZATION> Coleco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> says it plans to offer to make its debtholders majority owners of the company if they agree to a restructuring of the company's debt. The ailing <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION> toy maker made the announcement Wednesday as it extended a debt-exchange proposal a fourth time, this time until June 30. <ORGANIZATION> Coleco </ORGANIZATION> has pinned its hopes for recovery on a plan to exchange $ 335 million of debt for $ 119 million of new debt and 6 million shares of common stock. But that offer, launched March 23, was rejected by debtholders because it reduced the value of their investment in the company by about 65 percent. Debtholders also complained that the plan did not require similar sacrifices from <ORGANIZATION> Coleco </ORGANIZATION> stockholders, who would have seen only a 34 percent reduction in the value of their investment if 6 million more shares of stock were issued. In a short statement, <ORGANIZATION> Coleco </ORGANIZATION> said it is preparing a revised offer that would respond to the concerns of debt holders. Without giving specifics, <ORGANIZATION> Coleco </ORGANIZATION> said the new plan would offer more bonds, nearly as much as the $ 335 million of original securities that would be replacing. In addition, <ORGANIZATION> Coleco </ORGANIZATION> said the new offer would include enough new shares of common stock to give bondholders `` more than a majority equity interest'' in the restructured company. With 17.8 million shares of stock outstanding currently, that indicates that 18 million new shares of stock would have to be issued under the new plan. <ORGANIZATION> Coleco </ORGANIZATION> officials have said the company might have to seek protection from its creditors under federal bankruptcy laws unless it can restructure the debt and raise working capital. <ORGANIZATION> Coleco </ORGANIZATION>'s other products include ALF dolls, Big Wheels plastic tricycles, and board games such as Scrabble and Trivial Pursuit. Industry sources say the company holds about 5 percent of the nation's toy market.
