<HEAD>Stock Rally Falters, Major Retailers Post Lackluster May Sales</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: TOPS with 7 new grafs with morning market activity, retail
sales reports. Picks up 6th graf pvs, The Commerce ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Stock prices pulled back today after rising sharply over the past two sessions, and the nation's largest general retailers reported May sales that analysts described as lackluster. At noon on Wall Street, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which had climbed 107.57 points Tuesday and Wednesday, was off 6.76 at 2,057.25. Analysts said some traders sold stocks to cash in on the gains of the past two sessions. They noted that interest rates, which had fallen earlier this week, turned higher today. In the latest round of retail sales reports, major storeowners reported their sales were marginally higher or actually fell last month. <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Roebuck </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's largest retailer, said its overall sales last month rose 5.1 percent from May 1987 levels, while sales from stores open at least a year _ also known as same-store sales _ rose only 0.2 percent. K mart <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said its overall sales rose 6 percent last month, while same-store sales rose only 2.3 percent. <ORGANIZATION> J.C. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Penney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said its overall sales fell 1.2 percent last month and same-store sales fell 1.4 percent On Wednesday, the government reported April gains in its chief economic forecasting gauge as well as in factory orders and construction spending. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported its Index of Leading Indicators rose 0.2 percent in April, following rises of 0.2 percent rise in March and 1.5 percent in February. The March increase in the leading index originally was reported as a much stronger 0.8 percent rise. However, weakness in consumer and business borrowing pulled the index down sharply. The government also reported that orders to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> factories for manufactured goods climbed 1.2 percent in April to a seasonally adjusted $ 218.7 billion following an even bigger 1.6 percent March increase. Most economists had been forecasting only modest growth in new orders of 0.5 percent in April. The bigger-than-expected number likely will do little to alleviate concern among some analysts that strong demand, particularly for exports, will trigger greater inflation. The strength in new orders in April came in electrical machinery, lumber and wood products and in petroleum, chemicals and paper. In a third report, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said construction spending rose 0.1 percent in April to an annual rate of $ 401.8 billion, following a 1.3 percent jump in March and a 0.4 percent February increase. Analysts tended to discount the weak overall change and focused on a big 8.8 percent rise in spending on industrial plants, which put activity in this sector up 39.8 percent from where it was a year earlier. <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Jasinowski </PERSON>, chief economist of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION>, said the gain reflected the boom in export sales, which has meant plants in many industries are operating near full capacity. Government construction fell by 3.1 percent in April to an annual rate of $ 79.3 billion. Residential construction posted a 0.4 percent advance in April to an annual rate of $ 191.9 billion, while non-residential construction climbed 2.1 percent in April to an annual rate of $ 94.4 billion. In another economic report Wednesday, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> farm exports climbed to a 3 -LCB- - year high of 14.8 million tons valued at $ 3.3 billion in March A year earlier, farm exports were 11.4 million tons valued at $ 2.4 billion.
