<HEAD>British Banks Raise Base Rate to 8 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s major commercial banks, heeding a signal from the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION>, announced they would raise their base lending rate by half a percentage point to 8 percent. <ORGANIZATION> Barclays </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Midland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Westminster </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Lloyds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday they would increase the benchmark rate, effective Friday. The Bank of <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, apparently responding to the slumping British pound, sent its signal at noon local time by announcing it would raise a key money-market intervention rate. The pound has fallen sharply against the dollar and the West German mark in the last few days as the market's attention has shifted away from sterling into the dollar and other major currencies. The British base rate was last changed on May 17, when it was cut to 7.5 percent from 8 percent as British authorities attempted to estrain a strong rise in the pound. Corporate borrowers can obtain loans from commercial banks at one percentage point above the base rate.
