<FIRST>r f BC-Yugoslavia-Stocks     06-02 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Yugoslavia-Stocks,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Proposes Stocks In Yugoslav Economy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Yugoslav government, faced with a deepening economic crisis, is considering a plan to allow citizens of this communist country to buy stocks and securities, the state-run press reported Thursday. A draft of the reform, proposed by a government-appointed comission of about 140 prominent economists and scientists, has been presented to the federal parliament for debate, newspapers said. Stocks and bonds would be issued by state-run companies and could be purchased by their workers or other citizens, said the <ORGANIZATION> Vecernje </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Novosti </ORGANIZATION> newspaper. `` In this case, a shareholder takes over -LRB- part of -RRB- the risk of managing the company,'' said the report. Except for small cooperative and private ventures, the majority of Yugoslav enterprises are owned by the state. <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s economy, a mixture of free-market elements and Soviet-style central planning, has been growing at a sluggish rate averaging less than 1 percent annually over the past six years. The reform also calls for the sale or a temporary lease of a state-run company to its workers or other citizens in case the state is not interested in ownership. The draft of the reform also indicates that <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> plans to gear its economy more to the market to overcome difficulties that include a 15 percent unemployment rate, a $ 21 billion foreign debt and an inflation rate of around 170 percent, the highest in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The government last Saturday launched a major austerity program that included substantial price hikes, wage cuts of up to 30 percent and a 23.9 percent devaluation of the Dinar, the national currency. The program also lifted price controls for about 60 percent of goods and services, under a price freeze since last November. As a result, Yugoslavs have been hit by a new wave of price hikes for hundreds of goods and services of up to 127 percent. Food, drinks, cars, rents and air transport were affected by the increases. Meat went up by an average 50 percent, rents in <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION> by 90 percent and domestic air travel by 127 percent. The price hikes are bound to contribute to a further decline in living standards, which have already fallen by one-third since 1980. Labor unrest is also expected to grow.
</TEXT>
