<HEAD>Eastern, Continental Operated Safely, Feds Say</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Combines pvs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> are being operated safely but labor turmoil at <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> raises the risk of safety problems there, an investigation by the <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> concluded today. The report said that a close inspection of <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the parent company of the two airlines, showed no serious management or financial problems, but that labor strife at Eastern may have a future impact on public safety. As a result of the continuing labor problems, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> planned to continue close scrutiny of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s operations and former <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Brock </PERSON> will attempt to work with <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> management and labor to ease tensions. <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> Administrator <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> McArtor </PERSON> told a news conference that `` an unsafe condition does not currently exist'' at either Eastern or Continental. But <PERSON> McArtor </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Burnley </PERSON> voiced concerns that safety may be jeopardized at Eastern in the future by the `` extreme labor-management tensions'' at the airline. <ORGANIZATION> Burnley </ORGANIZATION> said that the department's investigation of <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> and its two major airline subsidiaries showed no safety problems at <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION>. It did, however, find a serious lack of communication between labor and management at Eastern. The department also said it found no evidence that <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s extensive financial losses last year posed any serious financial problems, saying the company had adequate resources and its management was found to be `` fit, willing and able'' to run an airline. <ORGANIZATION> Burnley </ORGANIZATION> said that <PERSON> Brock </PERSON>'s role will be to `` work for ways to de-escalate the -LRB- labor-management -RRB- tensions'' at Eastern. <PERSON> Brock </PERSON> said he had been in contact with most of the parties involved in the Eastern turmoil but that he had not yet developed a game plan on how to ease those tensions. <PERSON> McArtor </PERSON> said that an in-depth, plane-by-plane inspection at both <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> had not shown anything that would warrant extreme safety concerns. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>'s chairman, repeatedly has blamed labor unons at <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> for his two airlines' problems, accusing the unions of waging a campaign against the airline to discredit its safety record. The <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> announced its two-pronged investigation of <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> on April 13, including a plane-by-plane examination of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s aircraft by <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> inspectors. Five days later the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> safety inspection was broaded to include <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> as well. In conjunction with the announcement of the investigation, the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> disclosed that it was proposing a $ 823,000 fine against <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> because of safety violations found in special reviews of the Miami-based airline last year. During the 30-day inspections of Eastern and <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> officials repeatedly examined each aircraft at airport gates to determine if they were following federal air safety requirements. The separate probe of the parent company focused on possible management and financial concerns. DOT investigators wanted to determine if the executives of the Houston-based holding company are `` fit, willing and able'' to operate an airline according to federal aviation laws. There had been pressure from <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for the department to open an investigation of <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> in light of the company's huge losses, including $ 466 million last year, and its continuing labor turmoil at Eastern. A resolution calling for a such an investigation gained the support of 150 congressmen. In announcing the special probe, officials cited a pattern of safety violations at <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> reflected by the latest $ 823,000 fine, which came on top of a $ 9.5 million civil penalty from earlier <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> safety violations. The department also had raised concern about recent financial transactions involving <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> and Eastern, including attempts by the airline to spin off <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s lucrative Northeast shuttle. The shuttle spinoff has been blocked by the courts. These transactions raised quetions about whether the managers of <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, have complied with federal safety and economic practices that are required of commercial air carriers under federal aviation law, <ORGANIZATION> DOT </ORGANIZATION> officials said in April. <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> are the key airlines under <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. It also owns <ORGANIZATION> Rockey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mountain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Britt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Bar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Harbor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Provincetown-Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>. None of the smaller carriers specifically was subject to the DOT or <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> investigations.
