<HEAD>Soybeans Soar; Grains Close Higher</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS final graf to CORRECT direction of oats trading.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soybean futures prices surged Thursday on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> and grain futures posted moderate gains on forecasts for continued warm, dry weather in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>. The soybean market, already more sensitive than the grains to weather factors because of tight-supply concerns, got an additional boost from indications the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> had recently purchased more than 1 million metric tons of soybean meal from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> processors and was looking for more. `` There was tremendous strength coming out of the meal market,'' said <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> <PERSON> Karlin </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. `` I think the bean rally was due to the rally in meal more than anything else.'' Soybean meal futures posted near-limit gains with the contract for delivery in July closing $ 7.30 higher at $ 253 a ton. The chances for widespread rains in the Corn Belt remained slim, and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> predicted below-normal rainfall in most grain-producing areas for most of next week. At the close, wheat was -LCB- cent to 3 \ cents higher with July at $ 3.51 a bushel; corn was 1 cent lower to 3 -RCB- cents higher with July at $ 2.24 -LCB- a bushel; oats were 7 \ cents to 8 -RCB- cents higher with July at $ 1.86 -LCB- a bushel; soybeans were .01 cent lower to 18 \ cents higher with July at $ 8.20
