<HEAD>IBM Announces New Models Of PCs, Including Fastest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> fleshed out its 14-month-old Personal System-2 line of personal computers Thursday with reliable new models that include what would be the world's fastest PC. But <ORGANIZATION> Compaq </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s top rival in speedy personal computers, hinted it would strike back with one even faster that would reach the market before <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s. <ORGANIZATION> Compaq </ORGANIZATION> has scheduled a product announcement for June 20. `` In the time frame that <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> has indicated they might deliver their product, we will continue to have the highest performance 386-based machines in the marketplace,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Swavely </PERSON>, vice president for marketing at Houston-based <ORGANIZATION> Compaq </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> said the fastest version of its new Model 70, to be available in the July-September period, will be up to 50 percent faster than the Model 80, its fastest currently available computer. Its price will be $ 11,295. <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> also announced two other versions of the Model 70 available immediately, starting at $ 5,995, and a version of its Model 50 starting at $ 3,995 that is up to 35 percent faster than the current model. Also introduced was a version of the Model 25, the smallest and cheapest member of the Personal System-2 family, that is designed for use in office networks. Hard disk drives are also available for the Model 25 for the first time. Those products are available this month. <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> said the new computers are up to five times more reliable than the original PC, introduced in 1981. It said its one-year maintenance contract on a Model 60 is about $ 200 a year, compared to the $ 600 to $ 800 a year charged by competitors for computers of similar power. <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> reduced prices on the Model 60 and Model 80 by 5 to 18 percent to keep them in line with the improved new models. Analysts are expecting announcements of improvements in those products in coming months.
</TEXT>
