 <ORGANIZATION> Quaker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a major refiner of engine lubricants, said Thursday it signed a definitive agreement to sell its Western chain of 102 <ORGANIZATION> Arctic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circle </ORGANIZATION> restaurants to a Pittsburgh-based investment fund. <ORGANIZATION> Quaker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> acquired the restaurants in 1985 in order to get Arctic Circle's chain of motor oil changing shops, which have been renamed <ORGANIZATION> Quaker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Minute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lube </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. The sale, for undisclosed terms to the Maverick Fund, was planned before <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> investors led by <ORGANIZATION> Ardshiel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> made an unsolicited bid in April of $ 26.50 per share, or $ 675 million, for the company, said <ORGANIZATION> Quaker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Benton </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Faulkner </PERSON>. `` Our position continues to be one of silence'' on the takeover bid, <PERSON> Faulkner </PERSON> said.
