<HEAD>Defense Summations Continue, Cancer Victim's Free Choice Stressed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 4th graf pvs, `Mrs. Cipollone...', to
UPDATE with later summation arguments from another tobacco company
lawyer, picking up 5th graf, `The companies...'. A verion moving on
financial wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A lung-cancer victim's intelligent decision to smoke despite the known risks of smoking should not be second-guessed, a tobacco company lawyer said Thursday during final arguments in a cigarette liability trial. <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON> `` made an informed choice, a choice people in this country have a right to make'' to use a product with associated risks, said <ORGANIZATION> Lorillard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> attorney <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Northrip </PERSON> in the second day of summations. In a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> civil suit against <ORGANIZATION> Liggett </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Lorillard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Philip </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON> contends the tobacco companies misled the public about the danger of cigarettes. He has not specified damages. Mrs. <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON> died four years ago at the age of 58, and if the jury awards damages it would be the first time a tobacco company has been ordered to pay liability claims brought by smokers and their families. Another tobacco company lawyer, <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Bleakley </PERSON>, argued that people have been talking about the risks of smoking for hundreds of years. `` People have been claiming that smoking is bad for you, that it's bad for your health, that it kills you, as long as these products have been on the market,'' he told the jury Thursday. `` People do things all the time they know to be risky.'' <PERSON> Bleakley </PERSON>, who represents <ORGANIZATION> Philip </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morris </ORGANIZATION>, also defended the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tobacco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION>, formed and funded by the tobacco companies to study the health effects of smoking. He said no evidence in the case shows that the scientists on the council's advisory were anything but reputable and disinterested The companies presented evidence throughout the four-month trial to support their contention that Mrs. <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON> was intelligent, knew of smoking's risks through newspaper articles and warnings from relatives and made a strong-willed choice to smoke. `` It's our position that -LRB- smoking -RRB- was her decision to make, and we should n't second-guess her, not me, not Mr. <PERSON> Edell </PERSON>, not Mr. <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Northrip </PERSON> said, referring to <LOCATION> Cipollone </LOCATION> attorney <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Z. </PERSON> <PERSON> Edell </PERSON>, who was expected to make his closing statement Friday. Northrip on Thursday and <ORGANIZATION> Liggett </ORGANIZATION> attorney <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohn </PERSON> on Wednesday cited testimony by relatives who said <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON> constantly told his wife to stop smoking, her mother blamed cigarettes for her father's death and two sisters called cigarettes `` coffin nails'' as youths. They also cited newspaper articles relating charges about the dangers of cigarettes. Earlier Thursday, <PERSON> Northrip </PERSON> focused on medical testimony by physicians who treated Mrs. <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON>, pathologists who studied her cancer and cancer experts. He noted that physicians for the defense and the plaintiffs disagreed over what kind of lung cancer killed Mrs. <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON>. `` Some are statistically associated with cigarette smoking _ small cell carcinoma. Some are not _ carcinoid, or atypical carcinoid,'' said <PERSON> Northrip </PERSON>. <PERSON> Edell </PERSON> must convince the jury that cigarette smoking caused Mrs. <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON>'s lung cancer, not that smoking causes cancer in general, <PERSON> Northrip </PERSON> told an 11-member panel that will be randomly reduced to six for deliberations. The case was expected to go to the jury Monday.
