<HEAD>SEC Files Civil Action Against Roberto Polo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> sought a court order Thursday to force high-living investment adviser <PERSON> Roberto </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Polo </PERSON> to produce business records. The <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> action accused Polo, 37, and his <ORGANIZATION> Private </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Asset </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a registered investment advising firm, of failing to keep books and records as required by federal securities law. The agency launched an investigation following published reports last week that some of Polo's clients are suing him in state court, alleging that he diverted $ 110 million from their accounts to support a lavish lifestyle. The day after a May 26 Wall Street Journal article on the lawsuits against Polo, federal officials went to check the books of Private Asset Management at the Fifth Avenue address listed on public documents as the firm's offices. Instead, they found <ORGANIZATION> Miguel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cruz </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>, a fashion design firm owned by <PERSON> Polo </PERSON>, and were told the investment adviser business had moved to <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> `` sometime in 1986.'' The manager of <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> Cruz </PERSON> also told federal officials, according to court papers, that all of the investment records had been moved to <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> and that she and other <PERSON> Cruz </PERSON> employees had not been paid in several months. In its civil complaint, filed at federal court in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> claimed the withholding of books and records `` thwarted'' the commission's efforts to check whether the law had been broken. In other court papers, <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Padgett </PERSON>, associate regional administrator for the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said the agency had been unable to locate Polo or learn who his current attorney is. The front-page article in the Wall Street Journal described the Cuban born Polo as a voracious art collector with an expensively furnished apartment in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>. According to the article, 13 of Polo's investors filed civil suit in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> state court, claiming he diverted $ 110 million from their accounts. A state court has barred him from disposing of his assets, <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> authorities have seized the <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> apartment and Swiss and French police are searching for Polo on financial fraud charges in <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>.
