<HEAD>Drug Company Still Considering Selling Herbicide for Drug War</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lead, 6th, 12th grafs to uppercase Spike to reflect
trade name; also moving general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Eli </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lilly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> has not ruled out a sale of its herbicide `` Spike'' to the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> for aerial spraying of coca crops in <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>, a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee chairman said Thursday. Rep. <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> <PERSON> English </PERSON>, whose House Government Operations panel is reviewing the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> battle against illegal drugs, said the use of the chemical is still possible even though <ORGANIZATION> Lilly </ORGANIZATION> has expressed environmental and safety concerns. English, who spoke Wednesday to <ORGANIZATION> Lilly </ORGANIZATION> officials, did not repeat his Wednesday statement that the Indianapolis-based corporation was a `` deserter'' in the war on drugs. The <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> Democrat used that critical description after <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wrobleski </PERSON>, assistant secretary of state for international narcotics matters, complained to the subcommittee that the company refused to cooperate in the coca spraying program. <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Phyllis </PERSON> <PERSON> Oakley </PERSON> also had said <PERSON> Lilly </PERSON> apparently was worried about possible retaliatory measures by `` traffickers or terrorists.'' Speaking at a hearing Thursday, English said <ORGANIZATION> Lilly </ORGANIZATION> officials have objected to use of the chemical tebuthiuron, sold under the name `` <PERSON> Spike </PERSON>,'' because `` they have not done the proper testing of application by air over a wide section of countryside. They have no data. They have not seen data from -LRB- the -RRB- State -LRB- Department -RRB-, and can not assume responsibility or liability.'' But he added, `` We will continue discussions. We need to acquire a herbicide against coca bushes as quickly as possible. At this point, my own perception is the door is open, discussions will continue, and hopefully a solution can be found to this particular problem.'' Later, in an interview, English expanded his remarks to say there had not been proper aerial testing in the coca producing region of <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>, where the chemical would be sprayed. He said the area has considerable groundwater, and therefore is much different from the dry, brush areas where the herbicide is used in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. English added that the company also was concerned that the coca area in <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> `` may not be in friendly hands, and you may not have a pilot totally concentrating on the accuracy of spraying.'' <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> McKinney </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Lilly </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, had no immediate comment on English's statement on Thursday. But he did say the chemical is applied both by air and on the ground in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. He described `` Spike'' as `` a broad-spectrum, soil-applied herbicide for brush and weed control on non-cropland, pasture and rangeland.'' The herbicide is `` approved for use in grazing lands, wildlife openings along ditchbanks, and utility rights of way. It is safe for humans, livestock, wildlife and the environment when used according to label directions.''
