<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Over-extended lending and a slumping economy forced regulators on Thursday to shut down three banks in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and two in <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Guaranty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dallas </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Williamstown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> N.A </ORGANIZATION>. of <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> River </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Plaza </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fort </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Worth </ORGANIZATION> were declared insolvent, pushing the state's 1988 bank-failure tally to 32. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deposit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> was named receiver for the three banks, all of which will open Friday after being assumed by other banks, said <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Olcheski </PERSON>. Depositors of the failed banks automatically become depositors of the assuming banks. Guaranty had about $ 81.8 million in assets and will be acquired by the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oak </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Williamstown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> had total assets of about $ 23.6 million, and will reopen as a branch of <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Houston </ORGANIZATION>, and <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plaza </LOCATION>, which had