<FIRST>r f AM-WritersStrike     06-02 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Writers Strike,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scriptwriters' Strike Tactic Ignites Old Feud With Directors</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A 21-year-old Hollywood feud between scriptwriters and directors over who gets top credit for a movie is flaring anew over a tactic writers are using in their bitter strike against movie and TV producers. Negotiations between the writers' union and the <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Picture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Producers </ORGANIZATION>, representing management, were scheduled to resume Friday, following an unsuccessful nine-hour session Wednesday. In making a separate labor peace with 80 small producers this week, the <ORGANIZATION> Writers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guild </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> used a contract that requires a film be credited to the writer rather than the director. The Directors Guild of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> on Thursday threatened legal action against producers who sign the union's model contract, which also allows writers to encroach on directors' prerogatives in several other areas. The warning by the directors' guild, made in an advertisement published in <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> trade journals, is the latest complication in the writers' 13-week strike, which has already forced delays in the start of fall television season. The writers' independent contract with small producers who have broken ranks with the management group gives writers `` possessory credit,'' the right to have their name associated with the film title. Other objectionable provisions, said directors' spokesman <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Warn </PERSON>, require `` meaningful consultation'' with the writer on choice of director, actors and location, and give the writer a voice on script changes made during filming. Warn declined to discuss possible legal action, other than to say directors' lawyers were studying the matter. The unions fought in court over possessory credit in 1967 and the directors won. <ORGANIZATION> Writers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guild </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Cheryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Rhoden </PERSON> refused to comment on the directors' threat or the possessory credit issue. `` It shows their demands are not realistic,'' <PERSON> Herb </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>, a spokesman for the producers, said of the writers. `` They're just as unrealistic when it comes to the residuals for one-hour shows and foreign production,'' he continued, referring to the two main issues in the strike. The independent producers who have signed independent contracts with the union employ only about 100 of the union's 3,000 active writers, <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> said. The Writers Guild called the strike March 7, largely because the producers sought to reduce their compensation for reruns of one-hour television shows. With the demand for reruns of one-hour shows slipping, the producers sought to tie the writers' payments, called residuals, to a show's success in reruns.
</TEXT>
