 Stock prices turned downward Thursday, giving up some of their recent gains as interest rates rose. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up 107.57 points Tuesday and Wednesday, dropped back 11.56 to 2,052.45. Declining issues outnumbered advancers by slightly less than 3 to 2 in nationwide trading of <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> Exchange-listed stocks, with 614 up, 888 down and 476 unchanged. Volume on the floor of the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> came to 193.54 million shares, down from 234.56 million in the previous session. Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trading at regional exchanges and on the over-the-counter market, totaled 222.89 million shares. Interest rates rose in the credit markets, reversing a sharp decline Tuesday and Wednesday. Analysts also noted an increase in British interest rates. That prompted many traders to sell stocks in order to cash in on the gains of the past two sessions, brokers said. The upswing in stock prices since the start of the week was met with considerable skepticism on Wall Street, given continued signs of upward pressure on commodity prices. Futures prices for commodities ranging from soybeans to gold climbed in Thursday's activity. Next on the market agenda is the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s monthly report Friday on the employment situation. The figures will get a close look from Wall Streeters watching for evidence of the pace of economic activity. <ORGANIZATION> Burlington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Northern </ORGANIZATION> gained 1 -RCB- to 69 -LRB-. The company reported plans to sell a 13 percent interest in its <ORGANIZATION> Burlington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> operation to the public. <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> fell 1 -RCB- to 50 | Financier <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> said he w